<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--Long-FlyingBalloon     11-21 0180</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Long-Flying Balloon,0187</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Balloon Flies 2,500 Miles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten-year-old Marc Coleman doesn't care
that experts are having trouble explaining how his helium-filled
balloon flew 2,500 miles from Michigan to San Diego.
   He just thinks it's neat, said his mother, Liz.
   Marc's 11-inch, yellow balloon was one of 250 launched Oct. 23 to
commemorate a local church's anniversary. Each balloon was tied with
a string that carried a card asking the finder to return it to the
church.
   The church received 10 to 15 responses, mostly from within 20
miles.
   Marc's balloon wound up deflated in the swimming pool of a San
Diego sheriff's deputy Oct. 30.
   ``I can't explain how it got there,'' Deputy Kenneth Smith wrote
to Marc. ``At that distance, I can't believe it was the wind itself.
It had to have some help somewhere along the line.''
   The National Weather Service can't explain the trip, either.
   ``That would be some trick,'' said the weather service's Mike
Kalembkiewicz. If the balloon were only windblown, it would be ``a
once in a lifetime happening.''
</TEXT>
