<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Vietnam-Monks     11-21 0184</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vietnam-Monks,0188</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnam Commutes Death Penalty for Two Buddhist Monks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANBERRA, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnamese authorities have bowed to
international appeals and commuted the death sentences of two
Buddhist monks convicted of subversive activities, an Australian
government spokesman said today.
   Authorities in Vietnam told Australia's ambassador in Hanoi on
Friday that the sentences of philosopher and teacher Thich Tue Si
and scholar Thich Tri Sieu were commuted to 20 years in prison, the
Foreign Ministry official said.
   The two monks were condemned to death in October by the Ho Chi
Minh City Court on charges they participated in subversive
activities, the spokesman said on condition of anonymity.
   The two monks were arrested in 1984 with 19 Buddhist scholars.
The scholars received undisclosed terms of imprisonment. There were
no details on what kind of subversive activities they were alleged
to have undertaken.
   The status of a third person also facing capital punishment in
Vietnam, Tran Van Luong, was not known, the spokesman said.
   He said Australia and other countries began making pleas to
Vietnam after the death sentences were imposed. Australia opposes
capital punishment.
</TEXT>
