<2ND_LINE>PM--BRF--Poland-Cigarettes,0107</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cigarette Price To Go Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government raised cigarette prices
today, saying it wants to discourage heavy smoking and bring prices
more in line with production costs.
   The official PAP news agency on Sunday announced increases of
10.9 percent for all Polish-made cigarettes and 12.1 percent for
imported brands.
   Health officials have increasingly expressed concern about heavy
smoking among Poles. Cigarette consumption in Poland rose by nearly
a third between 1965 and 1985.
   Polish cigarettes cost an average of about 25 cents per pack. The
average monthly salary in Poland is about $100 at the official
exchange rate.
</TEXT>
