<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SkinheadArrest 1stLd-Writethru a0757 11-21 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Skinhead Arrest, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0757,0463</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three `Skinheads' Arrested in Beating Death of Ethiopian Immigrant</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of Mieske sted Miske throughout; UPDATES
throughout with new information, background; no pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three men belonging to a ``skinhead'' gang
were charged in connection with the beating death of an Ethiopian
immigrant a week ago, police said Sunday.
   Kenneth Mieske, 23, Kyle Brewster, 19, and Steven Strasser, 20,
were charged in what police said was a racially motivated and
unprovoked attack on Mulugeta Seraw, 27, who had just been dropped
off by friends in front of his home.
   The friends, who tried to intervene, suffered minor injuries.
Seraw died a short time after the beating, in which his attackers
used a baseball bat.
   Mieske and Brewster were charged with murder and remained in
custody, said Detective Dave Simpson. Bond for Strasser, charged
with second-degree assault, was set at $100,000, Simpson said.
   Mieske, who also uses the alias ``Ken Death,'' was arrested early
Saturday, and Brewster and Strasser were arrested about noon Sunday,
he said. The three were to appear in district court Monday afternoon.
   Mieske and Brewster face additional charges of assault and racial
intimidation in a Sept. 10 incident at a grocery store, Simpson
said. A black security guard and several store employees forcibly
ejected a large number of ``skinheads'' about 11 p.m. that evening.
   In another charge that resulted from the homicide investigation
but was unrelated to Seraw's death, police and the FBI arrested
Michael C. Barrett, 20, and charged him with unlawful flight to
avoid prosecution and escape, Simpson said.
   The charge relates to a Redwood City, Calif., case involving
vandalism to a place of worship, he said.
   The Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith said recently that
reports of violent crimes have surfaced in every area where skinhead
groups have organized. The civil rights group estimated in October
there were about 2,000 young people actively involved in skinhead
gangs in 21 states, but noted that many youngsters who adopt the
skinhead look reject the racist element.
   The skinhead subculture emerged in London as early as the 1960s.
Segments of the movement took on Nazi overtones in 1985 and since
have been supported by and associated with the white supremacist
Aryan Youth Movement and White Aryan Resistance.
   Portland has a skinhead group of about 20 called East Side White
Pride, with ties to the White Aryan Resistance, according to the
league. It also has a group called Preservation of the White
American Race, with about 10 members, half of whom are women, and a
suburban group, Youth of Hitler, the league said.
   Although police identified the suspects as part of a skinhead
gang, officers did not identify any group by name.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881121-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-88 0047EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-MappaMundi     11-21 0616</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mappa Mundi,0633</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cathedral's Plan To Sell Medieval World Map Stirs Anger</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prelate of Hereford Cathedral, which is
crumbling for lack of cash, has provoked a heated dispute among
churchmen and art experts by putting one of Europe's greatest
medieval treasures on sale.
   The 708-year-old Mappa Mundi, Latin for map of the world, has
been kept in the cathedral for centuries and is to be auctioned by
Sotheby's in London in June. News reports put its value at more than
$4.5 million.
   The sale announcement Wednesday prompted a leading member of the
cathedral's fund-raising committee to resign in protest. Newspapers
have published angry editorials against the sale, and Hereford town
leaders have vowed to fight it.
   The map shows historical events, Bible stories, topography,
animals, plants and 420 cities on a 6-by-4 sheet of vellum.
   Jerusalem is at the center of the map while Hereford, 144 miles
northwest of London, is drawn on one edge.
   The controversy illuminates the dilemma faced by custodians of
Britain's national heritage. The 900-year-old cathedral in Hereford
is one of many in need of cash, but sales of treasures such as the
Mappa Mundi threaten to put the nation's historical heritage into
the hands of foreign buyers and remove them from Britain.
   The Dean of Hereford, the Very Rev. Peter Haynes, said in
announcing the sale of the map that cathedral authorities need to
clear a $273,000 overdraft and spend millions more on repairs, more
staff, the cathedral's choir and new premises for its library of
medieval books.
   Announcing his resignation from the fund-raising committee, Sir
Roy Strong, a former director of London's National Portrait Gallery
and Victoria and Albert Museum, said Thursday, ``I was very upset to
see the Dean standing outside his cathedral and holding up the Mappa
Mundi, its finest treasure, for sale to the world.
   ``If that is the kind of church they are running, I no longer
want to be associated with it.''
   Replied John Champion, chairman of the cathedral's appeal
committee: ``I am sorry he feels the way that he does ... Put
bluntly, it is a choice of what is more important, continuing the
work of the cathedral ... or retaining a marvelous medieval
treasure.''
   John Newman, deputy mayor of Hereford, a town of 48,000, said he
wants Queen Elizabeth II, as secular head of the Church of England,
to intervene.
   The map ``may legally be the cathedral's, but morally it belongs
to the citizens of Hereford,'' Newman said.
   Sotheby's says that as a national treasure, the Mappa Mundi is
equivalent to France's 11th century Bayeux Tapestry depicting the
invasion of England by William the Conqueror in 1066.
   Georgina Nayler, deputy director of the National Heritage
Memorial Fund, said: ``We are outraged that one of the most
important documents in the world is about to be put into an auction
room.''
   Lord Gowrie, Sotheby's chairman, strongly denies allegations that
no effort was made to find a British buyer.
   ``I am sorry that national institutions have not felt able to buy
this great map,'' said Lord Gowrie, adding that he spent more than a
year seeking a buyer among government-funded bodies such as the
British Library.
   The Daily Telegraph said Thursday that chances of the map staying
in Britain appear slim.
   Critics accuse Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's Conservative
administration of starving the arts of adequate government funding.
The government favors sponsorship of the arts by private industry.
   Dr. Richard Gem of the Cathedrals Advisory Commission for England
was quoted by The Times as saying many other cathedrals in financial
trouble may have to sell off ``very important treasures.''
</TEXT>
