<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush     11-21 0659</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush,xxx</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EDs. Bush announcement skedded for 9:30 a.m. EST; will be topped.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect George Bush, faced with unease
in the financial markets over the gaping budge deficits, today will
name Richard Darman to run OMB and tap Stanford's Michael Boskin as
chief financial adviser, transition sources say.
   Bush scheduled a morning news conference today to make what his
office described only as an announcement about the transtion.
   But sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
president-elect has enlisted Darman as director of the Office of
Management and Budget and Boskin as chairman of the Council of
Economic Advisers.
   Darman was the right arm of James A. Baker III throughout the
Reagan administration, both when Baker was White House chief of
staff and later as Treasury secretary. He played a behind-the-scenes
role in negotiating the 1983 rescue plan for Social Security.
   Darman was a whiz kid for Elliot Richardson as secretary of
health, education and welfare in the early 1970s.
   Boskin is a well-known conservative economist and expert on the
Social Security system. He was a father of Bush's ``flexible
freeze'' idea to drive down the deficit in four years.
   The stock market has sagged and the value of the dollar fallen
since Bush captured the White House Nov. 8 from fears that his
no-tax-hike pledge will impede efforts to bring down the deficit,
now growing by $155 billion a year.
   Bush has said he takes the deficit seriously and will work with
Democrats in Congress to forge a solution.
   Bush spent a quiet weekend out of the limelight, attending church
Sunday, jogging and conferring at home with Gov. John Sununu of New
Hampshire, his chosen chief of staff.
   Bush was also meeting today with two former presidents, Gerald
Ford and Jimmy Carter, who have made some bipartisan recommendations
for the incoming president.
   Also on Bush's schedule is a meeting with David Packard, the
computer magnate who headed a commission that recommended an
overhaul of Pentagon procurement procedures.
   Bush revealed last Tuesday he is keeping his friend Nicholas F.
Brady as treasury secretary. He told reporters Friday he was
concentrating on naming the rest of his economic team before turning
his attention to defense and national security posts.
   In Reagan's second term, Darman was deputy to Baker as treasury
secretary. Both left the government when Baker resigned in August to
run Bush's presidential campaign.
   Boskin argued in a recent book titled ``Too Many Promises'' that
the program should be overhauled to separate its welfare and pension
functions.
   Boskin proposed a two-tier system, with a flat monthly payment
aimed at helping people stay out of poverty and the second or upper
tier tied strictly to how much people paid into the system.
   Currently there is a sharp tilt to Social Security benefits, with
lower-income workers getting a far heftier return on their payroll
taxes than middle- and upper-income workers.
   Bush named Baker, his longtime associate from Houston, as his
choice for secretary of state the morning after the election.
   Brady, who served eight months as a caretaker senator from New
Jersey in 1982, was sworn in two months ago as Baker's successor at
Treasury. He is a former chairman of the investment banking house of
Dillon, Read & Co. Inc.
   On Tuesday, the president-elect plans to fly to Alabama to visit
a conference of Republican governors and to Houston for a
get-acquainted meeting with Mexican president-elect Carlos Salinas
de Gortari, who takes office Dec. 1.
   Sununu was preceding Bush to the GOP governors conference to
deliver a luncheon speech there today. The governors will also hear
from Lee Atwater, Bush's campaign manager and now his choice for
chairman of the Republican party.
   Bush will return to Washington Tuesday night, then fly Wednesday
to Kennebunkport, Maine, for a long Thanksgiving holiday weekend
that could include a fence-mending session with Massachusetts Gov.
Michael Dukakis, the vanquished Democratic presidential nominee.
   cvc
</TEXT>
