<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RosierTrial     11-21 0566</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rosier Trial,0585</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Expects to Complete Mercy Killing Case By Thanksgiving</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT LEISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Less than a year after the death of
his cancer-stricken wife, Dr. Peter Rosier shocked television
viewers when he admitted, ``I administered something to terminate
her life.''
   Now the 47-year-old Fort Myers pathologist is on trial here on
charges of first-degree murder, attempted murder and conspiracy to
commit murder in the Jan. 15, 1986, death of Patricia Rosier, his
wife of 23 years.
   Mrs. Rosier, 43, suffered from lung cancer, which doctors say had
spread to other organs.
   The state contends the interview, broadcast Nov. 12, 1986,
amounted to a confession. Rosier admitted his wife didn't die of
cancer. He said she wanted to die before the situation became
horrible and that he merely helped her on her way.
   ``There was no question Patricia Rosier wanted to end her life,''
said Assistant State Attorney Ed Volz, who expects to finishing
presenting his case before Thanksgiving. The trial, now in its
fourth week, was moved from southwest Florida because of extensive
pretrial publicity.
   Rosier gave his wife 20 pills of Secanol _ a strong sedative _
and when that didn't work, he gave her morphine injections, then
morphine suppositories, prosecutors said.
   During the trial, however, Mrs. Rosier's stepfather, Vincent
Delman, has described in detail how he smothered her after Rosier's
botched attempts.
   ``I decided to gently cover her nose and mouth,'' Delman
testified, demonstrating on himself for the jury. ``I didn't give it
a second thought ... I didn't get any pulse ... I didn't hear any
more sound.''
   Delman, 68, a retired New York dentist, said he was afraid she
might become a ``vegetable'' after Rosier left her unconscious and
lingering near death for 12 hours.
   ``He obviously didn't do such a good job,'' Delman said, adding
that he decided, ``Enough is enough.''
   He testified as a key state witness under a grant of immunity.
   No charges were filed against him because he and his two sons,
Russell and Farrell Delman, successfully negotiated an immunity
agreement before prosecutors knew the extent of their involvment.
They are the state's star witnesses.
   The defense said the state was taken.
   ``This is not a murder case. It is wrongful prosecution,'' said
defense attorney Stanley Rosenblatt, who hasn't decided yet whether
to put Rosier on the stand. ``Prosecution is a face-saving device.''
   However, the state maintains it had no choice. Without the
Delmans' testimony, there was very little on which to build a case.
No autopsy was performed, and Mrs. Rosier was cremated 52 hours
after her death.
   Even if they had known beforehand, prosecutors still would have
extended immunity to the Delmans, testified James Fitzpatrick, lead
investigator.
   ``It changed nothing,'' he said. Rosier ``orchestrated his wife's
death.''
   Through a prior arrangement, permitted in terminally ill cases,
Rosier called the Lee County Medical Examiner's office and told
coroners officials his wife was dying. She was placed on an expected
death list. No autopsy would be necessary. A death certificate
signed by one of her treating physicians attributed death to lung
cancer, according to testimony.
   Attorneys for both sides agree the couple made a double suicide
pact after Mrs. Rosier's cancer was diagnosed in spring 1985.
   But Rosier didn't go through with it for the sake of his
children, Jacob, now 19, and Elizabeth, 21, Volz said.
</TEXT>
