<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0756,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Holds Steady, Stock Prices Hit Another Record High</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing Nikkei, dollar. Picks up 4th graf pvs,
`The dollar ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar inched up against the Japanese yen
Monday, while share prices rose moderately on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 122.52 yen, up 0.12 yen from Friday's close
of 122.40 yen. Opening at 122.40 yen, the currency moved in a narrow
range of 122.37 yen and 122.60 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 103.39-point
winner Friday, added another 104.06 points or 0.36 percent to finish
at 29,284.26, a new record high. On Friday, the index closed at
29,180.20.
   The dollar traded around its opening level in Tokyo as the market
turned increasingly cautious about selling the U.S. currency
following concerted intervention Friday by the world's major central
banks, said a dealer at the Bank of Tokyo.
   Because of the extent of intervention Friday during both European
and New York dealings, there is no apparent force in the market now
to push the dollar down further, he said, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   But he said upward momentum was also absent.
   ``Although the dollar-yen rate is stabilized for the moment, it
doesn't mean participants are willing to buy the dollar,'' he added.
   On the stock exchange, ``market players were interested in wide
variety of issues,'' said an analyst with Nomura Securities, Japan's
largest brokerage.
   ``It's a sign that more people are looking for places to invest
their money,'' he said, asking that he not be identified.
</TEXT>
