<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ConfederateAssassination     11-21 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Confederate Assassination,0544</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Book: Lincoln Assassination A Confederate Intelligence Plot</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX DOMINGUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Wilkes Booth wasn't a shiftless actor
who killed Abraham Lincoln out of despondency over the South's loss
in the Civil War, but a Confederate intelligence agent, a new book
contends.
   Confederate leaders sanctioned the assassination as a last-ditch
effort toforce the North into peace negotiations, three former U.S.
intelligence officers wrote in ``Come Retribution,'' recently
published by the University Press of Mississippi.
   Booth also used an underground intelligence network for his
escape after shooting Lincoln during a performance at Ford's Theatre
in Washington, D.C., on April 14, 1865, five days after Gen. Robert
E. Lee's surrender at Appomattox, the authors contend.
   ``The book challenges the long-held belief that, in the closing
months of the Civil War, the Confederacy stubbornly held out against
surrender even though it had no hope of winning its independence,''
William Tidwell, one of the authors, wrote in a recent article.
   ``It shows instead that the Confederates had a well-developed
plan for the campaign of 1865 which they believed would result in a
Southern victory or at least a stalemate.''
   The Confederacy had wanted to kidnap Lincoln, but when that plan
failed, it plotted to blow up the White House, Tidwell said. The
bombing plan was aborted when a Confederate demolition expert was
arrested, Tidwell said.
   Southern leaders finally decided to kill Lincoln, demoralize the
North and begin a last ditch offensive, Tidwell said. Lee's
surrender of the Army of Northern Virginia had virtually ended the
war by that time, but Booth thought he could save the South by
killing Lincoln, said Tidwell, a retired CIA officer.
   Tidwell's co-authors are James Hall, a retired Labor Department
official who served in Army intelligence during World War II, and
David Winfred Gaddy, a former National Security Agency official.
   Tidwell said the three used their intelligence experience to
re-examine the assassination and uncover what they alleged was a
well-established Conferederate intelligence network. They examined
thousand of documents in the National Archives over a 10-year period.
   ``Our evidence is largely circumstantial,'' Tidwell said.
``Basically, we are trying to tell our story by putting together
many small pieces of information, each well documented.''
   The authors contend Booth was not helped during his escape by
strangers or a rag-tag band of sympathizers hastily assembled before
the assassination. Instead, Booth appears to have followed the main
Confederate underground network leading from Washington to the
Confederate capital in Richmond, Va., the book contends.
   Of the 17 who helped Booth's escape, the authors were able to
link 12 with the Confederacy, eight of whom had participated in
Confederate intelligence activities.
   The authors also elaborate on the activities of a Southern
intelligence operation that spied in Washington, New York and
Chicago.
   The book's title comes from a code system the Confederate
intelligence used in which a certain word or phrase was used to
decipher messages.
   ``Come Retribution'' was the last code key used by Confederate
intelligence, Tidwell said. A chart used to decipher the code was
found among Booth's effects after he was shot by Union soldiers 11
days after the assassination of Lincoln.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
