<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scanlon     11-21 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scanlon,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Product Safety Chairman Quitting For Think Tank Post</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Terrence M. Scanlon, a Democrat who has
promoted voluntary safety programs as the Reagan administration's
chairman of the Consumer Product Safety Commission, is resigning to
take a post with a conservative think tank.
   The Heritage Foundation said Sunday that Scanlon would become
vice president and treasurer of the organization effective Jan. 3.
   One of the highest ranking Democrats in the Reagan
administration, Scanlon has run his agency with a philosophy close
to President Reagan's emphasis on voluntary safety programs and
cooperation with industry.
   Consumer advocates attacked his approach and urged promoting
product safety more aggressively, but Scanlon responded that
voluntary programs can be established more quickly than government
regulations.
   ``You can do a voluntary standards approach at the same time you
have an enforcement program,'' he said in a telephone interview.
   Scanlon said that under his leadership, the independent agency's
civil penalties against companies violating safety standards reached
an all-time high.
   Scanlon cited as a major accomplishment of his tenure at the
agency an agreement last year to cooperate with the U.S. Customs
Service in halting imports of unsafe products before they reach
domestic store shelves.
   A former aide to Presidents Kennedy and Johnson, Scanlon served
in the Small Business Administration and Commerce Department before
he was appointed to the safety agency.
   He was the agency's chairman from December 1985 to December 1986,
but had to relinquish the post when Congress failed to confirm his
appointment within a year.
   The delay coincided with an investigation of charges that Scanlon
had used the commission's staff for personal projects. He was
exonerated of any criminal wrongdoing and was confirmed as
commission chairman in July 1986.
   The commission consists of five members, and a quorum of three is
needed to conduct business. Currently, only three commissioners are
serving because Congress has not provided funds for the two
remaining positions.
   Scanlon's departure would leave only Carol Dawson and Anne Graham
as commissioners, too few for the agency to conduct business.
   Scanlon will be in charge of fund raising and financial
management at the Heritage Foundation, which also has attracted
several former Reagan administration officials including former
Attorney General Edwin Meese and former U.N. ambassador Charles
Lichtenstein.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
