<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Cross-BorderCriminal     11-21 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cross-Border Criminal,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trying To Cross Into United States, Canadian Learns He's A Criminal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ARNPRIOR, Ontario (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Schinkel says he didn't know he
had a criminal record until he was barred entry into the United
States.
   After a U.S. customs officer did a computer check, Schinkel, 41,
was told there was a record of a narcotics offence _ cultivation of
marijuana _ that meant he wasn't allowed into the country.
   Four years ago, police seized two marijuana plants from
Schinkel's garden at his home in White Lake, Ontario, near Arnprior.
   When he went to court, Schinkel received a conditional discharge
and the judge told him he was a lucky man because he wouldn't have a
criminal record.
   But the United States records as convictions all sentences handed
down by Canadian courts _ discharges included.
   ``As far as we are concerned, a conditional discharge is the same
thing as a conviction,'' said John Hogan, port director for U.S.
immigration at Alexandria Bay, N.Y. ``We don't recognize Canadian
pardons either.''
   Schinkel's experience ``points out something pretty outrageous,''
said Ottawa lawyer Bob Wakefield. ``The whole intent of the
discharge provisions in Canadian law is to remove any stigma, any
prejudice attached to the person involved.
   ``But what's really amazing here is we are supplying (U.S.
officials) with information about discharges, knowing it is being
used in a manner that clearly undermines the intent of Canadian
law.''
   The legal hitch meant trouble for Schinkel, a woodworker.
   When he was refused entry to the United States in March at
Cornwall, Ontario, Schinkel _ determined not to cancel a Florida
vacation _ tried again down the road at the Ivy Lea Bridge, near
Gananoque, Ontario.
   Another computer check showed Schinkel had tried to cross the
border only a few hours before, and Schinkel says U.S. customs
officials held him for 4{ hours for questioning.
   He said he was was photographed, fingerprinted, and officials
confiscated his girlfriend's pickup truck and sent him back across
the bridge on foot to Canada.
   Six months later, Schinkel says, he got the truck back after
paying a $500 U.S. penalty.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
