<1ST_LINE>d a PM-SDX-NameChange     11-21 0139</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SDX-Name Change,0141</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Society of Professional Journalists Drops Greeks Letters From Name</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Society of Professional Journalists has
voted to drop the Greek letters Sigma Delta Chi from its name.
   The society was founded in 1909 at DePauw University as Sigma
Delta Chi, or SDX, accepting only men as members. In 1969, it
allowed women to join and added ``The Society of Professional
Journalists'' to its name a few years later.
   Delegates at the organization's 79th annual convention on Sunday
approved the name change by 197-66, ending a nearly 20-year debate.
   The organization also approved a resolution urging
President-elect George Bush to step up efforts to win the freedom of
American hostages Alann Steen, a journalism teacher, and Terry A.
Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated Press.
The two were abducted in Lebanon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
