<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Canada-Business     11-21 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Canada-Business,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Companies Encourage Workers To Support Free Trade On Eve Of
Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Canada-Elections, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of Canada's largest supermarket chains is
encouraging its workers to back the U.S.-Canadian free trade pact,
joining several other companies using similar tactics to try to
affect today's elections.
   Along with their paychecks last Thursday, Loblaws workers
received a seven-page letter from company president David Stewart
supporting the free trade accord with the United States.
   The Loblaws letter claims the deal, which requires Canadian
parliamentary ratification, could knock 8,000 Canadian dollars
($6,480) off the price of a house ``or an extra $20 (Canadian) off
the price of winter coats for the kids this year.'' The U.S.
Congress has already approved the measure.
   At least one worker thinks the letter is an attempt to intimidate
employees into voting for the Progressive Conservatives, the
governing party and architects of the controversial deal.
   The Liberals and New Democratic Party oppose the pact.
   ``They should give people free choice. That's the way it's
supposed to be,'' one Loblaws worker was quoted as telling the
Toronto Star newspaper.``I don't think they should do anything like
that.''
   A company spokesman denied the letter is meant to sway workers
into voting for the Conservatives.
   ``It was a personal message that was meant to be non-political in
nature,'' said Michael Arnett, Loblaws vice-president of
merchandising and development.
   The retail giant, which employs 33,000 workers at stores across
the country, is one of several large corporations to have entered
the free-trade debate by calling on workers to support the deal.
   Stelco Inc., a Hamilton steel manufacturer with 12,500 employees,
and Canadair, a Montreal aircraft company, have distribted similar
letters to their workers.
   Ford Motor Co. made a video of president Ken Harrington defending
the deal. The tapes were sent to the company's factories in Ontario,
said spokesman Jim Hartman. Some plants chose not to show the video
to employees, he added.
   Several other companies have distributed pro-free trade leaflets
produced by the Canadian Alliance for Trade and Job Opportunities.
</TEXT>
