<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea-Chun, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0499,0529</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Says He Wants Political Resolution To Chung Controversy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Roh comment, other details,
changes byline. Picks up 7th graf pvs, `Dong-A-Ilbo'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Roh Tae-woo was quoted as
saying today he wants to resolve the controversy involving his
predecessor, Chun Doo-hwan, and indicated the former leader would be
pardoned.
   Roh made the remarks as the 56-year-old Chun reportedly was
preparing to make a public apology for alleged corruption and other
misdeeds during his seven-year term in office.
   ``I will take actions under the principle that any wrongdoings by
a chief executive should be dealt with politically and that any
political reprisal would only hurt democratic development,'' the
Seoul Shinmun newspaper quoted Roh as saying.
   Chun had planned to leave Seoul Tuesday to live in seclusion in
the countryside, but the plan was delayed because of difficulty in
finding him a safe, rural home, news reports said.
   Chun is expected to apologize at a natioally televised news
conference Wednesday, newspapers quoted Chun's aides as saying. He
also is to turn over most of his wealth to the government and accept
rural exile, a traditional way of repentence for disgraced Korean
leaders.
   The former president, who stepped down in February, denies any
personal wrongdoing. But about a dozen of his relatives and
associates have been convicted or charged with corruption involving
millions of dollars in public funds.
   Dong-A-Ilbo newspaper said Chun would leave immmediately after
reading his statement Wednesday to live in a mountainside Buddhist
temple or near an army unit in the northern part of the country.
Chun, the paper said, needs a refuge where he will be safe from
attacks by radicals and other opponents.
   Other newspapers said he might move to the countryside in central
South Korea, but not to his hometown in the south, where residents
reportedly oppose his return.
   National Assembly hearings on abuses under the Chun government
focused today on attempts to stifle press freedom. More than 700
journalists were blacklisted and many newspaper and broadcast
operations were placed under state control by the Chun
administration.
   Chun has been a virtual prisoner in his luxurious Seoul house,
guarded by hundreds of riot police to prevent attacks by dissidents.
Opposition groups have held major protests and tried to march on his
home to demand his arrest.
   President Roh Tae-woo's government is under criticism for trying
to protect Chun and the government is trying to defuse public anger
without being implicated in the furor.
   Yonhap, the South Korean news agency, said the government was
considering a probe by prosecutors against Chun if his apology and
surrender of property does not satisfy the public.
   There have been increasing numbers of street protests urging
Chun's arrest in recent weeks. Over the weekend, thousands of
students and dissidents battled riot police in downtown Seoul after
police stopped a march to Chun's house.
   Chun, a former general, took power with military backing in 1980.
He was succeeded by Roh, another former general and a close Chun
associate.
</TEXT>
