<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Sudan-Missile     11-21 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sudan-Missile,0404</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Minister Says Rebel Leader Denies Ordering Plane Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A southern rebel leader denied ordering
missile attacks on aircraft, including one that damaged a plane
carrying many of Sudan's military heirarchy, a government minister
said today.
   The plane carried 60 people, including Defense Minister
Abdul-Maguid Khalil.
   Osman Omer, minister for construction and public works, said
rebel commander John Garang said he has held off ordering his Sudan
People's Liberation Army to escalate the war, even though a
tentative new agreement to end 5{ years of civil war has not been
implemented.
   Omer said Garang made the statements in a telephone conversation
Sunday with his negotiating partner, Mohamed Osman Mirghani.
   On Sunday, military spokesman Brig. Mohamed Osman Malik blamed
the incident on Garang's rebels. After Malik's comments, Prime
Minister Sadek Mahdi said the incident proved Garang has ``lost
credibility. The rebel movement is not serious about its peace
claims.''
   Mirghani is patriarch of the Democratic Unionist Party, a junior
partner in Sudan's governing coalition. Omer said Prime Minister
Sadek Mahdi was with Mirghani when Garang told him he gave no orders
for ``shooting this plane or any other plane.'' Garang spoke from
his headquarters in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia.
   Last Thursday, unidentified men fired a SAM-7 missile at a
Hercules C-130 just after it took off from the besieged city of Wau
in southern Sudan with the defense minister, the army
commander-in-chief and other top military commanders aboard.
   The missile badly damaged the plane's engine and control system.
But the pilot managed to maintain control and landed without injury
or other damage.
   Rebel broadcasts from Ethiopia took responsibility for the
shooting down of two civilian aircraft in southern Sudan in 1986 and
1987 that killed more than 70 people. The first, in August 1986,
prompted Mahdi to cease contacts with rebel leaders that had held
early promise of agreement.
   The incident came a day after an initial cease-fire agreement was
signed in Addis Ababa between Garang and Mirghani.
   Mahdi and other political leaders have endorsed the peace
initiative, although the prime minister has not discussed the issue
publicly since the shooting.
   Garang took up arms in 1983 in a quest for autonomy and economic,
administrative and social reforms in southern Sudan. Its Christian
and animist African-descended people traditionally have been
dominated by the ethnic Arab Moslems of the north.
</TEXT>
