<HEAD>Hirohito Reported Feeble But Stable</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito lay in stable condition today at
the Imperial Palace, more than two months after he was bedridden
with internal bleeding, a spokesman said.
   The 87-year-old monarch slept most of the day, said Kenji Maeda,
spokesman for the Imperial Household Agency.
   He said Hirohito's temperature in the evening was 99.68 degrees,
up from his normal reading of about 95.9.
   Since he feel ill Sept. 19, Hirohito has been bleeding
intermittently from the upper intestine, which underwent a bypass
operation in September 1987. But Maeda said the emperor has shown no
signs of new bleeding for almost two weeks. Hirohito has received
transfusions of about 42 pints of blood since he became ill _ more
than three times the amount circulating in his body.
   According to news reports, Hirohito's weight has fallen to 66
pounds from the 110 pounds he weighed before his illness.
   Hirohito, who is being fed intravenously, also suffers from
jaundice and anemia.
   Palace officials have refused to confirm or deny reports that the
world's longest-reigning monarch has pancreatic cancer.
