<HEAD>Reservist Killed When Plane Depressurizes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARCH AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Air Force reservist died
after a window burst on a KC-135 tanker aircraft flying over the
Atlantic Ocean and the cockpit depressurized, officials said.
   Master Sgt. James L. Borland, 47, of Moreno Valley was killed in
the accident as the plane was en route from England, said Capt.
Richard Williamson, a spokesman for the air wing. The precise cause
of death was not immediately determined, officials said.
   He died when a 10-inch-by-8-inch sextant sighting window in the
cockpit broke, officials said. A flight surgeon among the 17 others
aboard the aircraft tended to Borland. None of the others was
injured, Williamson said.
   The accident, four to five hours into the flight from Lakenheath,
England, was ``one of those bizarre things. The odds are one in 2
billion,'' said Lt. Col. Duncan Bridewell.
   Col. Tom Frank, the aircraft's commander, said he heard a sharp
bang as the plane flew at 35,000 feet above the ocean and miles from
land. The crew landed the plane about 400 miles away at Iqaluit, on
Baffin Island, 1,500 miles north of Montreal off the coast of Canada.
   The tanker, a military version of the Boeing 707, was on a
weeklong refueling mission in support of Air Force fighter aircraft.
   An Air Force board of inquiry was sent to Iqaluit to investigate.
</TEXT>
