<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Onassis 1stLd-Writethru a0511 11-21 0615</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Onassis, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0511,0632</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper Says Death Attributed to Natural Causes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with report on coroner's report,
medicine being analyzed, details on Onassis' health, famly fortune.
Adds byline. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The coroner's report on Christina
Onassis' death says the Greek heiress died of natural causes, the
newspaper La Nacion reported today.
   The 37-year-old daughter of Greek shipping tycoon Aristotle
Onassis died Saturday of an apparent heart attack at the country
club home of friends. Autopsy results on the cause of death are
expected to be released today.
   The coroner's report is key to the release of the body for burial
in Greece, and might provide details of Miss Onassis' death. The
report was to be delivered today to Buenos Aires Judge Fernando Nino.
   In another development, three jars of medicine and other evidence
found in Miss Onassis' bedroom were taken by police Sunday for
analysis, the private news agency Diarios y Noticias said today.
Another bottle of pills reportedly was missing.
   One of three doctors who allegedly examined Miss Onassis at the
country club and pronounced her dead there was questioned by police
and two judges who have jurisdiction in the case, DyN reported.
   Miss Onassis frequently dieted to combat an obesity problem and
was known to take diet pills. It was not known if she was on diet
pills at the time of her death.
   Judge Nino tentatively ruled the death suspicious because the
body arrived dead at the hospital. The coroner's report he ordered
is based on an autopsy conducted Saturday night.
   A federal judge on Sunday night prohibited the removal of Miss
Onassis' body from Argentina without his authorization, citing
procedural errors in transfering the body from his district to
Buenos Aires.
   Miss Onassis was the stepdaughter of Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis,
the widow of President John F. Kennedy who married Aristotle Onassis
in 1968.
   In Piraeus, Greece, a spokesman for the family's Springfield
Shipping company said Miss Onassis will be buried on her family's
island, Skorpios, off northwest Greece later this week.
   The spokesman said the Onassis fortune had been left to the
daughter born in 1985 to Miss Onassis and her fourth husband,
Thierry Roussel.
   ``The entire fortune goes to little Athena,'' the spokesman said,
speaking on condition of anonymity. ``Mr. Roussel will have custody
of the child until she comes of age.''
   Miss Onassis, who made headlines with her jet-setting lifestyle
and four marriages, all of which ended in divorce, married Roussel
in March 1984 and filed for divorce eight months later.
   Half of the estimated $1 billion family fortune went to Miss
Onassis upon her father's death in 1975. The other half is
controlled by the Alexander Onassis Foundation, which was set up in
memory of Onassis' only son, Alexander, who died in a 1973 plane
crash.
   Miss Onassis was visiting the country home of Marina and Alberto
Dodero 25 miles northwest of Buenos Aires when she was stricken.
   She was taken to a first-aid station at the club, then to a
Buenos Aires hospital, where she was pronounced dead of an apparent
heart attack, said hospital director Hernan Bunge.
   Federal Judge Alberto Piotti was quoted as telling Diarios y
Noticias that he issued the order Sunday night prohibiting the
departure of the body from Argentina.
   Piotti said the transportation of the body from the country club
to the Buenos Aires hospital involved ``errors of procedure, perhaps
involuntary'' by medical personnel, the news agency said.
   No further details were immediately available.
   The body was at the Greek Orthodox Church in Buenos Aires, where
a private funeral Mass was held Sunday.
</TEXT>
