<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Thornburgh-Thumbnail     11-21 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Thornburgh-Thumbnail,220</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a sketch of Attorney General Richard L.
Thornburgh, who has been asked to keep that post in George Bush's
administration:
   AGE: 56.
   EDUCATION: He earned a civil engineering degree from Yale
University, and a law degree from the University of Pittsburgh Law
School.
   JOB HISTORY AND BACKGROUND: Thornburgh was appointed U.S.
attorney for western Pennsylvania in 1969. In 1975, he was appointed
by President Ford as assistant attorney general in charge of the
Justice Department's criminal division.
   In 1978, he defeated former Pittsburgh Mayor Pete Flaherty for
governor, running on a platform of cleaning up corruption in the
Democratic administration of then-Gov. Milton Shapp, a Democrat. He
was re-elected in 1982, narrowly defeating former congressman Allen
Ertel. Barred by law from seeking a third term, Thornburgh left
Pennsylvania at the end of 1986 to head the Institute of Politics at
Harvard University's Kennedy School of Government. In August,
Thornburgh replaced Attorney General Edwin Meese III, who resigned
after saying he had been vindicated by an independent counsel
investigation of his affairs.
   After becoming attorney general, Thornburgh made a speech on
ethics at the Justice Department that was widely perceived as being
indirect criticism of Meese, who had been under criminal
investigation for 14 months during his 3{-year tenure. Thornburgh,
who later denied that his remarks had anything to do with the Meese
tenure, called for a review of Justice Department ethics policies.
