<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Brazil-OilStrike     11-21 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brazil-Oil Strike,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brazilian Oil Workers End Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of oil workers
today began returning to work after a 10-day nationwide walkout, the
state oil monopoly Petrobras and strike leaders said.
   Local unions voted Sunday night to accept a government offer of
wage increases, Petrobras press officer Lucio Pimentel said Monday.
   Mauro Costa of the national strike command in Brasilia, the
capital, said some unions still were voting on the proposal, but
``the tendency is to accept the offer.''
   ``It was a great political victory, although economically it
didn't attain what we wanted,'' he said in a telephone interview.
   The strike by more than 50,000 petroleum workers paralyzed the
nation's 11 refineries and caused severe shortages of cooking gas
and diesel fuel.
   In weekend emergency meetings, the government offered strikers a
15 percent cost-of-living raise retroactive to June 1987 and 4
percent more for productivity.
   Petrobras agreed not to punish strikers and to discount only four
days from their paychecks.
   Strike leaders urged unions to accept the offer, although it fell
short of the 26.6 percent increase they were demanding.
   The government suspended cost-of-living raises last year, saying
they fuel inflation now running at more than 1,000 percent a year.
   Oil workers earn an average $300 a month _ good wages by
Brazilian standards.
   The strike forced the government to import emergency shipments of
diesel fuel, cooking gas and kerosene. Gas rationing was imposed in
some parts of the country.
   Brazilian refineries can produce 1.5 million barrels of petroleum
by-products a day. The country consumes about 1.1 million barrels of
oil daily, of which nearly 50 percent is imported.
</TEXT>
