<2ND_LINE>PM-Darman-Thumbnail,230</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a sketch of Richard Darman, chosen by
President-elect George Bush as director of the Office of Management
and Budget.
   AGE: 45.
   EDUCATION: He received an undergraduate degree from Harvard in
1964 and an M.B.A. from the Harvard School of Business three years
later.
   JOB HISTORY AND BACKGROUND: From 1970 to 1977, Darman served in
the Nixon and Ford administrations in policy positions in the
departments of Defense, Justice, Commerce, State and Health,
Education and Welfare. He also was a member of the faculty of
Harvard's Graduate School of Government and a partner of ICF Inc., a
management and economic consulting company.
   He entered the Reagan administration in 1981 as a top aide to
James A. Baker III, then White House chief of staff. He followed
Baker to the Treasury Department when Baker switched jobs in 1985
with former Treasury Secretary Donald T. Regan. Darman was a key
architect of the administration's policy to join with America's
major trading partners in late 1985 to drive the value of the dollar
lower as a way of solving the country's huge trade deficit.
   He resigned as deputy Treasury secretary, the No. 2 post, in
April 1987 to take a job with Shearson Lehman Brothers investment
banking division at a salary, with stock options, reportedly
approaching $1 million annually.
   Over the summer, Darman joined the Bush campaign. He served as
the stand-in for Democrat Michael Dukakis during Bush's practice
sessions for his two debates.
