<1ST_LINE>u i PM-HamadiTrial     11-21 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hamadi Trial,0481</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hostage Holds Back Tears; Lawyer Wants Psychiatrist to Check Hamadi</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American hostage in the 1985
TWA hijacking fought back tears today while testifying he feared his
son-in-law would be shot during the ordeal.
   Also at the trial, a defense attorney said confessed hijacker
Mohammed Ali Hamadi was ``mentally disturbed'' during the crime and
asked that his client be given a psychiatric examination.
   Hamadi, a Lebanese Shiite Moslem, is accused of air piracy and
murder in the June 1985 hijacking. U.S. Navy diver Robert Stethem
was killed and 39 Americans were held hostage for 17 days.
   Vincente Garza, a real estate developer, testified that his
son-in-law, Robert Trautmann, was among several hostages taken off
the plane at Beirut Airport and then hidden in the city before the
ordeal was over.
   Garza, 57, said he offered to take Trautmann's place.
   ``I thought he could be ... shot, and I asked Hamadi `don't take
him away, take me.' Hamadi just pushed me back and told me to sit
down,'' Garza testified, choking back his emotions and seeming on
the verge of crying.
   Garza said Hamadi also took part in robbing passengers.
   Earlier today, defense attorney Hans-Burkhardt Steck asked that a
psychiatrist examine Hamadi. He said he has evidence from a
psychiatrist that Hamadi had been ``hindered in his development''
because of injuries he sustained in war-torn Beirut.
   Another American testified that she feared the hijackers would
deal with her severely because she was Jewish.
   ``I was very afraid because I am Jewish and I didn't know if they
knew it,'' Mauri Schwarz, a 36-year-old computer saleswoman, told
the court. ``I heard screams and beatings on more than one
occasion.''
   Ms. Schwarz said one of the passengers sitting near her had asked
for medical help because he had a heart condition ``but the
hijackers refused.''
   Following Ms. Schwarz' testimony, Hamadi was asked to comment.
   ``I never took part in the robberies and if anyone had asked me
for a doctor, I would have done that,'' he said.
   Under court guidelines to protect witnesses, former hostages do
not reveal their hometowns.
   They have testified about savage beatings and the death of
Stethem, who was shot and thrown out onto the tarmac in Beirut.
   Hamadi admits being one of the hijackers, but denies shooting
Stethem.
   He was arrested at Frankfurt Airport in January 1987 after custom
officials found liquid explosives in his luggage.
   The United States requested Hamadi's extradition last year, but
the West German government turned it down, fearing for the lives of
two West Germans held hostage in Lebanon. The hostages since have
been released.
   Hamadi's older brother, Abbas, is serving a 13-year prison term
in West Germany in connection with the kidnappings.
  
</TEXT>
