<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Pakistan 1stLd-Writethru a0476 11-21 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pakistan, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0476,0584</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Benazir Bhutto Meets With Possible Coalition Partner</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Bhutto meeting with possible
coalition partner, other details. Picks up 5th graf pvs, `Last
week's vote...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Populist leader Benazir Bhutto met
with the leader of an ethnic Indian immigrant party today to try to
forge an alliance that would make her the first woman prime minister
of an Islamic country.
   The Pakistan People's Party, led by Ms. Bhutto, captured the
largest bloc of votes in Wednesday's national election but fell
short of a majority in the National Assembly.
   Ms. Bhutto, who has said she expects to be the country's new
prime minister, is seeking the support of elected independent and
smaller parties to form a governing majority.
   She met today with Altaf Hussain, leader of the Mohajir Quami
Movement, which came in third in the election and represents ethnic
Indian Moslem immigrants.
   Wasim Sajjad, minister for justice and parliamentary affairs,
announced today that President Ghulam Ishaq Khan intends to persuade
Ms. Bhutto and her conservative rival Nawaz Sharif to unite in a
coalition government. Sajjad said Khan will meet separately with the
two leaders Tuesday.
   A government spokesman, who requested anonymity, said ``the
discussion with the two major party leaders will be to form a
broad-based government. It's only natural.''
   But Ms. Bhutto said she will not accept a coalition with Sharif,
whose Islamic Democratic Alliance was second in the election,
officials said.
   Last week's vote, the first free elections in Pakistan since
1977, had no majority winner.
   Ms. Bhutto's party won 93 seats in the 237-member National
Assembly, compared to 55 for the right-wing Islamic Democratic
Alliance led by Sharif. The remaining 68 seats contested went to
independents, minor parties and non-Moslem candidates.
   Ms. Bhutto, 35, says she has enough recruits among newly elected
members of the National Assembly to command a majority in the
chamber, and expects the president to ask her party to form the new
government.
   In voting for provincial assembly seats on Saturday, Ms. Bhutto's
party was only able to obtain an outright majority in one of the
country's four provinces.
   She virtually swept her home province of Sind in southern
Pakistan. But in the heavily populated Punjab province, where 60
percent of the country's 107 million people live, the majority went
to the right-wing alliance.
   In Pakistan, the Senate, National Assembly and the four
provincial assemblies elect the president, who is head of state. The
president, in turn, has the power to name the prime minister.
   However, the Constitution has two clauses on naming a prime
minister.
   One gives the president discretion both in timing and selection
of a prime minister. The other, originally meant to apply to
elections held after 1990, requires the new legislature to convene
first and the person with the majority of votes to head the
government.
   Ms. Bhutto maintains that the 1990 provision applies to the
current situation. Pakistan's military leader, Gen. Mohammed Zia
ul-Haq, had added the 1990 provision to the Constitution after
deciding he would continue as president with the powers to decide
prime minister until 1990.
   Zia died in a plane crash Aug. 17, just weeks after calling
national elections. Zia ousted Bhutto's father, former Prime
Minister Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, in a bloodless 1977 coup and had
Bhutto executed two years later.
</TEXT>
