<1ST_LINE>u a PM-PrisonEscape 1stLd-Writethru a0516 11-21 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Prison Escape, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0516,0402</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convicted Murderer Escapes From Trenton State Prison</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Recasts first 2 grafs to ADD that Marrero received two life
sentences; 60 years is earliest time before parole considered; ADDS
three grafs with details of search and of Marrero's convictions.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An inmate convicted of two murders and
sentenced to two life terms escaped from a 153-year-old section of
the Trenton state prison early this morning after burrowing out of
his cell and using a handmade ladder to scale an outer wall,
officials said.
   Gonzalo Marrero, who would have to serve at least 60 years before
being considered for parole, was spotted scaling the 20-foot outer
wall of the prison at 4 a.m. today by a tower guard, said Jim
Stabile, spokesman for the state Department of Corrections.
   Stabile said Marrero, 37, jumped over the wall after the guard
called out at him. Two other inmates who had also escaped from the
cell _ Jorge LaBrada and Andrew Bisesi, both 28 _ did not try to
escape after they heard the guard, he said.
   The three were cellmates in the prison's oldest section, which
opened in 1835, and burrowed through a 3-foot-thick wall to escape.
They squeezed through a narrow opening into the prison compound, and
then Marrero used a 19-foot ladder fashioned from wood scraps to
scale the outer wall, Stabile said.
   Marrero apparently cut himself on razor wire on the top of the
outer wall because blood was found on the ladder and outside the
wall, the spokesman said.
   Stabile said it was not immediately known how the three cut
through their cell wall or where they found the wood to build the
ladder. He said LaBrada and Bisesi were being questioned this
morning.
   Corrections officials and local authorities were conducting a
wide search of Trenton this morning.
   Tracking dogs following a partial trail of blood believed left by
Marrero led authorities to a drainage system along Route 29, and
authorities believed Marrero was in the area, said Robert Vasquez,
head of special operations groups for the corrections department.
   Helicopters traveled up and down the river as authorities opened
manholes and rifle-toting officers stood guard at streets closed off
in the area, a densely populated blue-collar neighborhood of
rowhouses.
   Marrero, sent to the prison in 1986, also was convicted of
robbery, sexual assault and burglary.
</TEXT>
