<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RadioRemarks     11-21 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Radio Remarks,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>News Director Wins Arbitration Fight Over Sexual Jokes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A radio news director who walked off the job
after being subjected to on-air sexual jokes by two disc jockeys has
won $8,000 in severance pay.
   Arbitrator Ronald F. Talarico said various sex-related jokes made
on WBZZ-FM about newscaster Liz Randolph ``were lewd, offensive,
sophomoric, in bad taste and beyond anything that an employee should
have to be subjected to _ even if they are part of an `entertainment
vehicle.'''
   Ms. Randolph walked off the Jan. 22 morning show of Jim Quinn and
``Banana'' Don Jefferson after a joke of a sexual nature was aired
about her.
   The station fired her and refused to give her severance pay,
saying her walk-off constituted a ``flagrant neglect of duty'' in
violation of WBZZ's collective bargaining agreement with the
American Federation of Television and Radio Artists.
   In voluntary arbitration between the federation and WBZZ's owner,
EZ Communications Inc., Talarico said the station could not deny Ms.
Randolph the severance pay. The written opinion was received by Ms.
Randolph's attorney last week.
   Talarico ordered the station to pay her 10 weeks' salary, plus
interest. Station Manager Tex Meyer estimated the award at $8,000.
Meyer said the station planned to appeal.
   Talarico agreed with WBZZ that Ms. Randolph knew her job would
require her to be involved in ``banter and interplay'' with other
on-air employees, some of which might be risque.
   But, he wrote, Ms. Randolph's participation in earlier jokes did
not prevent her from objecting to the ``vile and filthy'' Jan. 22
joke.
   ``Obviously, we're pleased with the decision,'' said Samuel
Kamin, Ms. Randolph's attorney. But Meyer said he was surprised by
the decision, because ``the arbitrator determined Liz Randolph
willingly participated in humorous banter.''
   A civil suit filed by Ms. Randolph against the station, EZ
Communications, Quinn, Jefferson, Meyer and former program director
Jim Richards is pending.
</TEXT>
