<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Salvador-Killings     11-21 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Salvador-Killings,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Archbishop Calls For Investigation Of Farm Worker Deaths</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archbishop Arturo Rivera Damas
called for an investigation into the deaths of three farm workers
killed during last week's meeting of the Organization of American
States.
   Rivera Damas said Sunday that in addition to the three deaths in
the eastern province of Morazan, 20 people were killed in combat
during the conference in San Salvador.
   The prelate gave no details of the civilian slayings, which had
not been reported previously.
   ``The information available involved national army troops in this
action and we consider a detailed investigation necessary,'' the
archbishop said in his homily.
   ``We believe acts of this type make the public react negatively
against whomever uses that method, whether it be the armed forces or
(the guerrillas),'' he said.
   The five leftist guerrilla groups, which have been fighting for
nine years to overthrow the U.S.-backed government, declared a
temporary truce during the six-day OAS meeting that ended Saturday.
   
   Rivera Damas said the meeting of the Washington-based
organization left ``an atmosphere of hope'' for peace.
   It ``has meant, in a way, a certain possibility of support in
that it could stimulate a political solution to our conflict,'' the
church leader said.
   More than 15,000 people from churches and labor organizations
marched through the main streets of the capital on Nov. 15 to urge
rebel and government representatives to hold new peace talks.
   ``This is reason for joy for those of us who believe in the
possibility of promoting peace through non-violent actions,'' he
said.
   The church mediated the few meetings between the two sides in
recent years, the latest on Oct. 20, 1987 in San Salvador, and has
been critical of killings of civilians by both the left and the
right.
   An estimated 65,000 people have died in the war, the majority of
them civilians.
