<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Bush-Thornburgh 2ndLd-Writethru a0520 11-21 0502</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-Thornburgh, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0520,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush Rdp</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 8 grafs new with Bush announcement, Thornburgh comments;
pick up 5th graf pvs, He said</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect George Bush announced today he
will retain Attorney General Dick Thornburgh, saying the Justice
Department chief has ``a record of unquestioned integrity and a
commitment to upholding the highest ethical standards.''
   At a news conference, Bush said he is appointing Thornburgh
because ``I know that he will work with me to fight drugs with every
tool at our disposal'' and on other issues as well, including
attacking crime ``at every level'' and defending the civil rights of
all Americans.
   Since election day Nov. 8, a number of other names had emanated
from the Bush camp as possible replacements for Thornburgh.
   In a brief interview at the Justice Department, Thornburgh said
that he had learned of Bush's decision to retain him at a weekend
meeting initiated by the president-elect and that ``I was extremely
pleased and gratified that he made this appointment.''
   Bush's decision ``gives me the opportunity to continue what I
hope will be a positive and productive course for the department,''
Thornburgh said in the interview. ``My priorities will be the
president-elect's priorities.''
   In addition to fighting drugs, Thornburgh said ``our efforts in
... white-collar crime, official corruption should be important to
ensure high ethical standards in government and our business
institutions.'' He singled out the environment and civil rights as
other areas warranting attention.
   Thornburgh, 56, has been in the Cabinet only since Aug. 12, when
he succeeded Edwin Meese III, who resigned at the conclusion of a
14-month criminal investigation of his affairs. Meese declared he
had been vindicated. But the independent counsel who conducted the
probe, while deciding not to seek an indictment, said Meese probably
had twice broken a federal conflict-of-interest law and violated tax
laws.
   Bush, asked the day after he was elected president if he would
keep on Thornburgh and several other Reagan Cabinet members
considered to be ``Bush people,'' did not answer directly.
   He said that ``some people at various levels may be asked to
remain,'' but that ``there is something to be said for
reinvigorating the process by, with new people.''
   Indeed, Bush insiders had sent mixed signals about the future of
Thornburgh, who was said to be eager to keep his job. At one point,
those insiders had gone out of their way to discourage reports that
his reappointment was assured.
   Other names that had been tossed about as possible replacements
for Thornburgh were William D. Ruckelshaus, a former deputy at
Justice and former Environmental Protection Agency administrator,
and Illinois Gov. James R. Thompson.
   In taking over the Justice Department, Thornburgh, a former
governor of Pennsylvania and U.S. attorney in Pittsburgh, had vowed
to ``make drug trafficking and drug abuse Public Enemy No. 1.''
   Thornburgh headed the department's criminal division during the
Ford administration and established the agency's public integrity
section, which prosecutes corrupt public officials.
</TEXT>
