<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Yugoslavia     11-21 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yugoslavia,0564</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kosovo Calm, Leaders Renew Campaign For More Control</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SLOBODAN LEKIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 4,000 ethnic Albanians today
defied threats of a crackdown on street demonstrations and marched
to the capital of the restive province of Kosovo, Pristina
television said.
   Leaders of the republic of Serbia renewed their campaign for more
control of Kosovo province following a wave of protests.
   In the liberal northern republic of Slovenia, meanwhile, an
estimated 10,000 people held a peaceful rally in driving snow to
demand a referendum on controversial constitutional amendments.
   Pristina television said today's crowds marched from Orohovac, 40
miles southwest of Pristina, to demand reinstatement of two ethnic
Albanian leaders who were forced to resign under Serbian pressure
last week.
   Police outside Pristina shepherded the crowd as it passed through
the predominatly Serb suburb of Kosovo Polje, the state-run Tanjug
news agency said. No clashes between the rival groups were reported.
   The demonstrations in the southern province of Kosovo, involving
up to 100,000 people last weekend, have been the biggest there since
World War II. The protesters have been angered by the forced
resignations last Thursday of Azem Vlasi and Kacusa Jasari, two
ethnic Albanians from Kosovo's 13-member ruling Politburo.
   The provincial party leadership has promised to review the
resignations of Vlasi and Jasari at a meeting later this week.
   Asked why the the protesters had decided to defy warnings from
numerous Communist party leaders against more protests, student
Skelzen Malici said, ``We are aware of this, but we intend to
continue coming here until the (two leaders) are reinstated.''
   Serbian Communist leader Slobodan Milosevic, who has led the
campaign for more Serbian control of Kosovo, appeared to reject
protesters' demands that the two ethnic Albanian leaders be
reinstated.
   In a speech to Serbian Communist leaders in Belgrade, Milosevic
made no direct reference to the Kosovo protests, but said ethnic
Albanian youths, who made up the majority of the protesters, are
``victims of indoctrination.''
   ``The ideologues of counterrevolution should be held responsible
and not those who are just their arm,'' he addded.
   He said that restoring Serbian control over the judiciary,
schools and policing of Kosovo to stop alleged harassment of the
Slav minority are ``a precondition for Serbian unity.''
   Milosevic said in his speech today that about 500 ethnic
Albanians who have been jailed on charges of fomenting
counterrevolution with alleged nationalism should be freed.
   ``We should let these people out of jail and jail those who are
really responsible for the genocide and terror,'' he said.
   Milosevic and his supporters commonly use terms such as
``genocide and terror'' when talking about the alleged harassment of
Kosovo's Serb and Montenegrin minorities by ethnic Albanians.
   Official statistics show little if any evidence of ethnically
motivated murder or proof of frequently alleged rapes of Serbian
women by ethnic Albanian men.
   Milosevic's is campaigning for changes in the 1974 constitution
that gave Kosovo broad autonomy.
   Communist leaders in Yugoslavia's other five republics see the
campaign as part of a drive to increase the influence of Serbia, the
largest republic, on the Yugoslav federation.
   But Milosevic has said the changes would only put Serbia on an
equal footing with other republics, which have no administrative
provinces like Serbia's Kosovo and Vojvodina.
</TEXT>
