<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Baltics 1stLd-Writethru   11-21 0732</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Baltics, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0484,0751</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lithuanians Rally to Protest Lawmakers' Indecision on Autonomy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 19 grafs to UPDATE with Soviet lawmakers
recommending changes in amendments limiting power of republics. Pick
up 14th pvs, `Their ruling ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Lithuanians chanting ``for shame!''
jammed the center of their capital Vilnius today to protest their
legislature's refusal to declare the Sovutonomy from
Moscow, residents said.
   In Moscow, lawmakers recommended changes in constitutional
amendments that have touched off the furor in Lithuania and the
other Baltic republics, iet republic's aEstonia and Latvia, because of
limits they
place on the republics' powers, the daily Pravda said.
   The amendments were proposed by Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev as the keystone of his political reform program, which
includes the creation of a more powerful presidency and a full-time
national legislature.
   In Vilnuis, the Lithuanian Movement for Perestroika's call for a
10-minute noon protest halted traffic in the city center, and about
10,000 people rallied on the city's Gediminas Square, said movement
spokeswoman Rita Dapkus.
   Alvydas Medalinskas, the movement's acting secretary, addressed
the crowd from a balcony and called for the removal of three members
of Lithuania's Communist Party Central Coithuanian words meaning ``for
shame, for shame,'' to criticize the
inaction of their republic's lawmakers, Ms. Dapkus said.
   Medalinskas told the crowd that what happened on Friday ``was
detrimental not only to the (Lithuanian Perestroika) movement, but
to all of Lithuania,'' she said.
   The grassroots movement has called for another meeting of
Lithuania's Supreme Soviet by Nov. 29, and is collecting signatures
on petitions that call for such a session.
   What Ms. Dapkus called a ``symbolic strike'' was to last for 10
minutes throughout Lithuania. She said traffic had come to a
standstill in Vilnius, but there was no word yet from Lithuania's
other cities.
   Police in central Vilnius took no steps to interfere with the
rally on Gediminas Square, she said.
   Ms. Dapkus, who is from Chicago, said she will be leaving the
Soviet Union this week to set up an information bureau for the
Lithuanian movement in the United States.
   Pravda said today that a commission of the Supreme Soviet had
recommended modifications in amendments to the Constitution that
were proposed by Gorbachev and the national leadership as an
apparent attempt to placate the Baltic republics.
   As originally written, the amendment to Article 108 authorizes a
newly created Council of People's Deputies to ``take decisions
relative to the composition of the U.S.S.R., the approval of the
formation of new autonomous republics and autonomous regions in the
composition of the union republics.''
   The commission recommended that article be changed to limit the
council to questions ``of national-state structure relative to the
jurisdiction of the U.S.S.R.''
   Article 108 also authorized the council to annul legislation and
acts of the Soviet republics if they contradict the Constitution.
The commission, which met Saturday, recommended that such language
be stricken as part of an effort to increase ``the development of
the sovereign rights of the republics,'' Pravda said.
   However, the lawmakers also condemned the action of the Estonian
Supreme Soviet, saying its decision on Wednesday to give local laws
primacy over Soviet legislation was at odds with the 1977 Soviet
Constitution.
   Their ruling was transmitted to the Supreme Soviet Presidium, the
nation's highest executive body, possibly presaging a striking down
of the Estonian decision by the Kremlin leadership.
   Estonia, Lithuania and the third Baltic republic, Latvia, were
independent after the 1917 Bolshevik revolution until 1940, when
they were annexed by the Soviet Union.
   The small Westward-looking republics have used President Mikhail
S. Gorbachev's political reforms _ dubbed ``perestroika'' _ to push
for greater economic and cultural autonomy.
   Baltic residents contend that proposed amendments to the Soviet
Constitution will limit their autonomy.
</TEXT>
