<1ST_LINE>u a PM-ChicagoMayoral 3rdLd-Writethru a0565 11-21 0595</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chicago Mayoral, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0565,0606</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Illinois High Court Orders 1989 Election For Chicago Mayor</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 10th graf, `In this...', to CLARIFY that reference is to
Chicago, not dateline city.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DOWLING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chicago must hold a mayoral election
next year to fill the two years remaining of the term of the late
Mayor Harold Washington, the Illinois Supreme Court ruled today.
   The high court ruled without dissent. It said that a reading of
state election law, along with the state law governing
municipalities, requires that a special election be held to fill a
vacancy that occurs with more than 28 months left on a four-year
term.
   Washington, the city's first black mayor, died of a heart attack
Nov. 25, 1987, with 3{ years left of his second term.
   ``The scheme recognizes the importance of the voters not to have
a mayoral appointee who is not of their own choosing for more than
28 months,'' Justice Joseph Cunningham wrote in the court's opinion.
   A lower court ruling already has called for a primary Feb. 28,
followed by a general election April 4.
   The decision was eagerly awaited by a crowded field of announced
and unannounced mayoral candidates. Unannounced candidates include
the incumbent acting mayor, Eugene Sawyer, and front runner Richard
M. Daley, who were both said to be awaiting the ruling before
announcing. Neither had any immediate comment after the ruling was
handed down today.
   Daley, son of the late mayor Richard J. Daley who died in 1976,
just won a landslide re-election as Cook County state's attorney and
was the leader in a recent poll of potential mayoral contenders.
   ``That's no surprise. ... I never had any doubt that it would be
1989,'' said Democratic Alderman Edward Burke, who has already
announced his candidacy. ``We of course would have preferred that
the question would have been cleared up a lot earlier.''
   Sawyer, who is black, was appointed acting mayor a year ago by a
bitterly divided City Council after receiving the support of
Washington's white council opponents. He has trailed in the mayoral
polls to another black Democrat, Alderman Tim Evans, who has claimed
to be Washington's true political heir.
   In Chicago, a strongly Democratic town where no Republican has
been mayor for more than a half-century, the primary is considered
decisive. Many observers have said that if Evans and Sawyer split
the black vote in the February primary, and other white candidates
step aside, it could pave the way for a victory by Daley. The city's
population is 40 percent black.
   Sawyer, 54, had supported the 1991 date, but has said repeatedly
he is prepared to run a campaign immediately.
   Though Daley, 46, has declined to say whether he will run, close
associates have been quoted as saying they expect him to make a bid.
There are three other white candidates who have already announced,
but two of them are considered likely to pull out if Daley runs.
   Daley lost to Washington in a three-way Democratic primary in
1983, when he and incumbent Mayor Jane Byrne split the white vote.
   Evans today called the ruling ``a great victory'' for the people
of Chicago.
   Candidate Lawrence Bloom, the white liberal alderman who was a
staunch Washington ally, agreed.
   ``I think it's the decision the public wanted. They didn't want
29 members of the City Council to elect their mayor for three
years,'' said Bloom. He is not considered to be much of a factor in
the race but insists he's in it to the end.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
