<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Egypt     11-21 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Egypt,0213</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Considers Sanctions On Egypt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel is considering taking sanctions against
Egypt, such as delaying resolution of a border dispute, following
Cairo's recognition of a declared Palestinian state, a government
official said today.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said Israel's
10-member Inner Cabinet would discuss Egypt's move at its meeting
Wednesday and debate possible sanctions in response.
   One sanction idea likely to be raised was delaying an Israeli
withdrawal from the Taba Beach in the northern Sinai Desert, he
said. A team of international arbitrators ruled two months ago that
the disputed beach belonged to Egypt under a 1979 peace treaty.
   Foreign Minister Shimon Peres summoned Egyptian Ambassador
Mohammed Bassiouny for a meeting today to express his ``sorrow and
disappointment'' at the Egyptian decision, a Foreign Ministry
spokesman said.
   Peres said Sunday he regretted Egypt's decision and called the
proclamation of a state by the Palestine Liberation Organization ``a
setback in political terms because it has succeeded from a media
point of view.''
   Egypt is the third country which has diplomatic relations with
Israel to recognize the Palestinian state declared last week by the
Palestine National Council, the PLO's parliament-in-exile, in
Algiers, Algeria. The others are Turkey and Cyprus.
</TEXT>
