<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GOPGovernors 1stLd-Writethru a0452 11-21 0598</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-GOP Governors, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0452,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reappointed Cabinet Members Highlight Governors Forum</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with meeting opening, Cabinet members to attend in top
9 grafs, picking up in 8th graf pvs, Before the</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KENDAL WEAVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>POINT CLEAR, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Upbeat Republican governors opened a
conference today with top appointees to George Bush's new
administration on hand and newly renamed Cabinet members on the way.
   ``The transition happening in Washington is actually happening
right here,'' said Delaware Gov. Michael N. Castle, chairman of the
conference.
   Twenty of the nation's 23 Republican governors, along with two
governors-elect, were on hand for opening ceremonies, with all
holding hand on heart for the Pledge of Allegiance and national
anthem.
   The formal opening occurred after President-elect Bush said he
would retain Attorney General Dick Thornburgh and Education
Secretary Lauro F. Cavazos in their Cabinet posts in the new
Republican adinistration.
   Thornburgh and Cavazos both were on the governors conference
program today, along with Gov. John Sununu of New Hampshire, whom
Bush recently named as his new chief of staff, and former Bush
campaign manager Lee Atwater, whom Bush has recommended to be
chairman of the Republican National Committee.
   The president-elect is to meet with the governors Tuesday.
   Castle said the lineup of influential Bush staff members and the
president-elect put the conference ``as much in the forefront of
changing events'' as any such meeting could be.
   ``I think this administration in Washington is going to be even
more sensitive to the states,'' said Missouri Gov. John Ashcroft.
   Castle and Ashcroft commented Sunday aboard the U.S.S. Lexington,
an aircraft carrier docked off Pensacola, Fla. Nine of the GOP
governors put on flight helmets and flew by jet to the carrier for a
tour.
   Before the conference, being held at the Grand Hotel resort on
Mobile Bay, most of the Republican governors made clear they support
Bush on major domestic issues, including his pledge against new
taxes.
   ``I think right now would be an inappropriate time to talk about
new taxes,'' said New Mexico Gov. Garrey Carruthers.
   ``If he believes he can do without taxes, I am going to support
him,'' said Florida Gov. Bob Martinez, who did not plan to attend
the conference because of a legislative session. His and Carruthers'
comments were made in interviews before the start of the forum.
   Castle said the conference this year was unique in that a new
administration was coming into power and the president-elect planned
to attend along with influential members of the new administration.
   ``We will be able to lay out some of our priorities,'' he said.
   Ashcroft added, ``We want to develop an even better dialogue with
the president-elect.''
   Alabama Gov. Guy Hunt, the host of the conference, was one of the
few governors who said Bush may yet switch from his no-tax stand. He
said Bush may support an increase in taxes if necessary after ``you
cut all the waste you possibly could.''
   But, he said, ``not having looked at the books on the national
level, I really couldn't answer the question.''
   Castle said he opposed more taxes, emphasizing that initiatives
being taken at the state level are helping to reduce long-range
government problems and costs.
   ``Welfare reform demonstrated the states' ability to put forward
a workable solution to a complicated problem, one that will save a
great deal of money in the long run by helping people get off
welfare,'' he said.
   ``In virtually every area where the federal government mandates
programs, I believe the states can do a better job in running
them,'' Castle said.
</TEXT>
