<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Philippines-Foulups 2ndLd-Writethru a0455 11-21 0914</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Foulups, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0455,0937</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lack of Accountability Helps Perpetuate Inefficiency</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS three grafs after 10th graf pvs, `Kintanar's host...'
with Aquino comment today. Picks up 12th graf pvs, `Mrs. Aquino...</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lack of public accountability and an
inefficient bureaucracy have created a nightmare of sinking ships,
rebels who escape from birthday parties and foodstocks that vanish.
   Some problems which have beset the Philippines recently can be
explained by bad luck, including three tropical storms that killed
more than 600 people in two weeks.
   But others appear the result of appalling lack of organization,
resources and efficiency in President Corazon Aquino's
administration. Lack of public accountability contributes to an
atmosphere where accidents wait to happen.
   That in turn may be undermining public confidence in government.
   A recent survey by Ateneo University of 1,200 people nationwide
found just 31 percent expected their lives to improve. Forty-two
percent expected conditions to remain the same and 17 percent said
they would get worse.
   ``It is not enough that the president sets the example,'' wrote
the Philippine Daily Inquirer on the issue of accountability. ``She
should also find the strength and conviction to make examples of
officials who do not measure up.''
   On Nov. 12, the alleged chief of the Communist rebel army
escaped. The military says Romulo Kintanar, 41, and his wife Gloria,
38, walked away from a birthday party for the former stockade
commandant.
   Acting stockade commander, Maj. Benjamin Landrito, offered as an
excuse that he was asleep in his office at the time.
   It was not the first security breach at the stockade.
   Kintanar's host, Lt. Col. Robelito Comilang, was suspended last
month when a right-wing officer jailed for a leading role in an
August 1987 coup attempt reportedly walked through three doors that
were supposed to be locked, climbed the stockade wall and was
fatally shot by guards.
   Mrs. Aquino today blamed the six military coup attempts that
rocked her administration on her efforts to seek rapproachment with
communist rebels during a 60-day cease-fire that expired in February
1987.
   ``The right-wing fringe of the military ... launched a succession
of destabilizing attempts to topple me from power,'' she said. ``The
assassination of leftist leaders discredited my commitment to human
rights.''
   In June, dozens of armed men tried to free former Gov. Orlando
Dulay, jailed in the 1986 deaths of several Aquino supporters.
Raiders failed to free Dulay but made off with armory weapons.
   Mrs. Aquino has demanded a full investigation into Kintanar's
escape. Three senior officers, including Landrito and Comilang, have
been relieved and restricted to quarters.
   But there is widespread skepticism about change.
   ``There has not been any real investigation, much less real
punishment of people concerned,'' fumed Sen. Ernesto Maceda,
chairman of the Senate Defense Committee. ``There is a tendency to
cover up. In the spirit of comradeship, they just cover up the
incident to control the damage.''
   Maceda's doubts were based on the failure of previous
investigations to fix responsibility, punish those at fault and
implement changes.
   Commissions failed to solve the September 1986 assassination of
labor leader Rolando Olalia, the August killing of Local Governments
Secretary Jaime Ferrer and the September 1987 slaying of leftist
leader Lean Alejandro.
   Another commission organized after the January 1987 killing of 13
land reform protesters by soldiers guarding the presidential palace
never established who gave the order to fire.
   The senior officer on duty at the time, Brig. Gen. Ramon Montano,
was furloughed as capital regional commander during the probe. But
months later, he was promoted to major general and given command of
the national police.
   Three separate commissions investigated the December 1987
collision of the passenger ship Dona Paz with the oil tanker, in
which more than 3,000 people were believed to have perished.
   All three found evidence of widespread inefficiency in the
maritime industry, including overloaded ships, lack of adequate
communications, poorly trained crew and the absence of effective
search and rescue procedures.
   But Commodore Carlito Cunanan, who as coast guard commandant was
responsible for maritime safety, was promoted to navy commander
after the Dona Paz disaster.
   Last month, the Dona Marilyn, another passenger ship owned by the
same company, sailed into Typhoon Ruby and sank with 500 people
aboard, about half of whom remain missing and feared dead.
   Although the investigations into the second sinking have not been
completed, officials say they have found evidence of many of the
same shortcomings which led to the Dona Paz disaster.
   ``The country is one big Dona Marilyn sinking in the middle of a
storm while the captain snores on top of a mahjong table,'' wrote
columnist Francisco Tatad. ``Many (heads) should roll.''
   Lack of accountability has not been limited to the military. In
September, Mrs. Aquino fired Emil Ong as chairman of the National
Food Authority after two investigating committees found evidence of
widespread incompetence.
   They cited, among other things, the disappearance of $350,000
worth of rice, which Ong said sank on three barges. The coast guard
had no record of the sinking.
   Ong was furloughed during the investigations, then fired. Two
days after he was dismissed for incompetence, Ong was named
presidential adviser for regional government affairs.
   Also in September, retired Maj. Gen. Cesar Tapia quit as security
chief of Manila's international airport, claiming he was powerless
to stop rampant corruption there. Despite his allegations, most
customs and immigration officials remain on the job there.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
