<HEAD>Government Says About 30 Dead in Afghan Plane Downing</HEAD>
<HEAD>LEADS with 8 grafs with Afghanistan confirming plane downed, 27
dead; PICKS up 6th pvs, `Pakistan has ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghanistan's state-run radio today
said all 27 passengers and crew members aboard a Afghan transport
plane died when it was shot down by Pakistani forces over the
weekend.
   A Pakistani Foreign Ministry spokesman said the plane was flying
several miles inside Pakistani airspace when it was attacked
Saturday evening near the border town of Parachinar.
   The spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity said it was not
clear how many people were aboard the plane.
   The Radio Kabul broadcast, monitored in Islamabad, said the An-26
plane was en route to the eastern city of Jalalabad from the Afghan
capital when technical trouble developed.
   The pilot put out a call for assistance but was ignored by
Pakistan authorities, the radio said.
   ``Instead of helping pakistan shelled surface-to-air rockets at
the plane against all international laws and norms,'' said the radio
broadcast.
   The Pakistani spokesman said: ``The plane was asked to identify
itself and it didn't. It was going deeper into Pakistan's territory
when it was shot down.''
   He did not say how contact had been made with the plane.
   Pakistan has repeatedly complained of air violations by
neighboring Afghanistan.
   The two countries signed a U.N.-mediated agreement in April
providing for the withdrawal of more than 100,000 Soviet troops
estimated to be in Afghanistan.
   The Kremlin pulled out half of its troops Aug. 15. The remainder
are expected to leave by Feb. 15, 1989.
   The Soviet Union has been supporting the Marxist Kabul government
in its fight against U.S.-backed Moslem insurgents.
