<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Trade     11-21 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Trade,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trade Officials to Seek Opinions on World Policies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. officials will travel to 15 American
cities next year to get opinions about what world trade policy
should be in the administration of George Bush, Anne Brunsdale,
acting chairwoman of the International Trade Commission, said Monday.
   ``Listening to America ... the concerns of business executives,
labor leaders, politicians and others interested in the impact of
tariffs on U.S. industries and consumers ... is crucial if the
International Trade Commission is to offer informed advice to the
U.S. Trade Representative,'' she said in a statement.
   At a briefing she added that other barriers to trade as well as
tariffs will be discussed at the hearings to be held by the
six-member commission. They will begin Jan. 30, 1989, in Houston and
conclude in Washington on April 4.
   Ms. Brunsdale said she expects that Clayton Yeutter, the U.S.
Trade Representative, will be writing her in the next few weeks to
outline the kind of information he wants. Yeutter has been the chief
U.S. representative in the ``Uruguay round'' of negotiations with
nearly 100 countries covering the entire range of international
business, not only in manufactured goods but also in farm products
and services such as banking and air traffic.
   A key meeting is due next month in Montreal, Canada. Yeutter is
expected to resign his post afterwards and to be replaced after Bush
takes office Jan. 20.
   The commission is a federal agency that decides whether imports
hurt or threaten to hurt particular U.S. industries, and it
recommends what action should be taken. Its advice goes directly to
the president.
   If the ITC decides that an imported item has been sold in this
country at less than its fair value, or has been subsidized by
another government, it can issue an order imposing extra customs
duties.
   It also makes extensive reports to the president and his advisers
on trade issues.
   The commission also will appear at hearings in: New Orleans, Feb.
1; Miami, Feb. 3; Atlanta, Feb. 6; Los Angeles, Feb. 13; San
Francisco, Feb. 15; Portland, Ore. Feb. 17; Denver, Feb. 24;
Chicago, Feb. 27; Minneapolis, March 1; Kansas City, Mo, March 2;
New York, March 13; Boston, March 15; and Pittsburgh, March 17.
</TEXT>
