<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mexico-Bush     11-21 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Bush,0535</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Salinas Hopes Meeting Will Set Pattern for Relations</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush-Mexico, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carlos Salinas de Gortari, president-elect of
Mexico, hopes his meeting Tuesday with George Bush will establish a
personal bond and set the pattern for U.S.-Mexican relations.
   His task will not be easy, given the Mexican view that its
powerful neighbor constantly tries to impose its political and
economic will south of the border, but Salinas' advisers hope he and
the U.S. president-elect will form the basis for a working
relationsship.
   Salinas, a Harvard-educated economist who takes office Dec. 1,
will meet Bush for three hours Tuesday in Houston.
   ``Both Bush and Salinas are men with open minds who are willing
to listen to the interests and concerns of others. We have different
problems and common interests,'' said Juan Enriquez, a former
Harvard University professor who works in the Mexico's governing
Revolutionary Institutional Party, known by its Spanish initials PRI.
   As Salinas sees it, Mexico must resume economic growth and cannot
do so without reducing the burden of payments on its $102 billion
foreign debt, which drain economic resources and leave little money
for development.
   Some Mexicans fear Bush and the U.S. government may see drug
trafficking as the main bilateral problem and try to blame Mexico
for letting drugs into the United States.
   The governments have managed to work out temporary or partial
solutions to other problems, including water contamination along the
border and access to U.S. markets for Mexican products.
   Even foreign policy disagreements over Central America have been
played down in recent years.
   Victor Hugo Celaya, a Mexican congressman who is president of the
Border Commission, said the United States ``is becoming more aware
of our economic realities. The United States must re-examine its
policies in the region or it will risk the chance of being isolated
geopolitically.''
   He said the Houston meeting underlines ``the need to resume and
expand our dialogue and start the two new administrations with
common points of view and programs for collaboration and
development.''
   Outgoing President Miguel de la Madrid had six meetings with
President Reagan marked by U.S. demands, often irritating to Mexico,
that it do more to fight drug trafficking.
   ``Our relations with the United States have always been
difficult, so difficult that we lost half of our territory last
century,'' de la Madrid said in an interview last month. ``Nowadays,
it is a challenge for Mexico to live next to the biggest, richest
and most complex country in the world.''
   Mexican foreign policy is often at odds with that of the United
States, especially in Central America, and Mexicans feel U.S.
government officials do not understand their culture and politics
well enough.
   Mexico is an easy target for U.S. officials who complain of
corruption and failure to stop the drug trafficig drug trafficking.
The Mexicans say they do the best they can with limited resources.
   At his final meeting with Reagan, last February, de la Madrid
said bluntly the best way to fight the drugs was for citizens of the
United States to stop using them.
</TEXT>
