<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Cocaine     11-21 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cocaine,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Customs Announces Record Cocaine Confiscation In New Orleans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Customs Service inspectors seized more
than 1,400 pounds of high-grade cocaine with an estimated street
value of $28 million, the Customs Service said Monday.
   The cocaine was found Nov. 11 in suburban Jefferson in a shipment
of 55-gallon drums of resin from Guatemala, but announcement of the
confiscation was delayed because Customs wanted to try to catch the
buyers, said spokeswoman Liz Orgeron.
   ``What we were trying to do was make a controlled delivery to see
if we could make an arrest,'' said Orgeron.
   She said that was done last week, but no arrests were made and
the 1,424 pounds of the drug was turned over to the Drug Enforcement
Administration.
   The seizure was the largest ever in New Orleans, said Orgeron.
   She said the cocaine was on a ship that carried goods from
Central America _ a fact that prompted Customs agents to look
closely at the cargo. The resin containers got special attention
because resin rarely comes into the Port of New Orleans, she said.
   She said the Customs' Contraband Enforcement Team drilled into 60
drums of resin and found cocaine in 12. When those 12 drums were cut
in half with acetylene torches, inspectors found smaller, 30-gallon
drums surrounded by layers of tar and each containing about 45
one-kilogram bricks of cocaine.
</TEXT>
