<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hussein     11-21 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hussein,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraqi President Accuses Son of Killing His Bodyguard</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Saddam Hussein said Monday his
eldest son, Odai, bludgeoned to death a presidential bodyguard, and
he ordered an investigation into the slaying.
   In a letter to the minister broadcast on state radio, Hussein
said Kamel Hana Gegeo was killed the night of Oct. 18 when the
trusted bodyguard was firing his gun in a private villa near the
presidential palace in Baghdad.
   He said Odai sent his own bodyguard to ask Gegeo to stop
shooting, but Gegeo did not obey. Odai and his bodyguard went to see
why Gegeo disobeyed him, as well as a presidential order that
prohibits firing personal weapons during celebrations.
   Odai went to Gegeo and asked him if he received his order to stop
shooting and when the bodyguard said yes, Odai hit him with a wooden
bat.
   Gegeo was rushed to a hospital where he died the next day from a
head wound.
   Odai, 25, is the oldest of the president's five children.
   In Nicosia, Cyprus, sources said the bodyguard was particularly
close to the president and a distraught Hussein accompanied Gegeo's
body to a church for funeral preparations.
   The guard, believed to be in his 20s, was the son of the
president's cook and the governess of his three daughters, the
sources said.
   They detailed a different version of the killing circulating in
Baghdad, with Odai firing the gun and the bodyguard killed while
trying to quiet him.
   Hussein said he investigated the murder and referred the case
``so that justice is done.''
   He said Odai is in jail and has tried to commit suicide three
times since Gegeo died.
   The president described his Gegeo as a trusted person and ``a man
who never disobeyed him.''
   He said his son had not committed such a crime before and
described the murder as ``a will of God which cannot be prevented.''
   ``It is my constitutional responsibility to enforce justice in
the society ... and that does not exempt anyone,'' Hussein said in
his letter.
   Hussein ordered Justice Minister Akram Abdul Qader Douri to
investigate the death.
</TEXT>
