<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Theater     11-21 0254</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Theater,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New York-bound Play, Broadway Musical Head Drama Awards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David Hare's ``The Secret Rapture,'' due
off-Broadway in May, was named best play for 1988, and a revival of
the musical ``South Pacific'' was honored as best musical in awards
presented by Drama Magazine.
   Top acting awards went to Pauline Collins as best actress for the
one-woman comedy ``Shirley Valentine'' and, in a tie vote for best
actor, Alex Jennings for the Russian satire ``Too Clever By Half''
and Tom Wilkinson for Henrik Ibsen's ``An Enemy of the People.''
   Vanessa Redgrave was named best supporting actress for her
performance as Nora Melody in a revival of Eugene O'Neill's ``A
Touch of the Poet.'' Best supporting actor went to Peter Lindford,
who played Mephistopheles in a west London production of Johann
Wolfgang Goethe's epic ``Faust.''
   Best director went to Peter Brook, the Paris-based British
director, for his marathon staging of ``The Mahabharata,'' which was
seen in Glasgow, Scotland, in May as part of its world tour.
   The design award went to Richard Hudson for his season of work at
the Old Vic Theater, where he is the resident designer under its
artistic director, Jonathan Miller.
   Sir Michael Hordern, 77, received a special award in honor of his
distinguished acting career. He most recently appeared onstage a
year ago in a revival of George Bernard Shaw's ``You Never Can
Tell.''
   The quarterly published by the British Theater Association
announced the winners, which were decided by a committee of theater
critics and journalists.
</TEXT>
