<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Housing     11-21 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Housing,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Military To Make Plumbing Parts to Ease Housing Crunch</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN GILMOUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Part of the Soviet Union's vast defense industry
will be turning out plumbing parts for use in a crash program to
build more housing, a government official said Monday.
   Yuri P. Batalin, deputy chairman of the Council of Ministers, or
cabinet, said the military has the facilities for manufacturing the
items needed, so defense plants will be put to work turning out the
equipment.
   ``This is happening because available capacities in the defense
industry will be reoriented. Rather than producing armaments, they
will produce plumbing items,'' Batalin told a news briefing.
   The involvement of the military in civilian housing programs is
just one way Soviets hope to tap various sources for increasing the
country's stock of construction equipment and supplies.
   One city dweller in five lives in a dormitory or communal
apartment shared with other families. President Mikhail S. Gorbachev
has proclaimed the goal of building enough new housing so each
Soviet family can have its own apartment or house by the year 2000.
   In February, the government announced a plan for citizens to take
out large bank loans to build private homes. But even for the
enterprising, housing construction often is frustrated by lack of
necessary materials.
   ``The market resources will have to grow,'' said Yuri P. Boyev,
deputy Soviet minister for material and technical supplies. ``We
will have to provide the market with the needed materials.''
   Boyev said officials understand the shortage of supplies and are
trying to speed up production of everything from plumbing parts to
linoleum. He said his department made 20,000 square yards of
linoleum in 1985 and expects to make 57,000 square yards next year.
   Individual credits for housing construction are not new, but had
been issued on a limited basis until the announcement of the private
loan program. Last year, the government provided $720 million and in
10 months of this year will have provided $2.8 billion, Batalin said.
   Private construction had been discouraged in official attempts to
cut down on pilferage of hard-to-come-by building materials from
state enterprises.
   Batalin said recent changes to permit more economic autonomy in
the country's 15 constituent republics will create more of a
marketplace atmosphere, alleviating the shortages of materials.
   N.A. Nazarbayev, chairman of the Council of Ministers of
Kazakhstan, one of five Central Asian republics, said the exchange
of goods between the republics had at times been arbitrary and
unresponsive to needs.
   For instance, he said, Kazakhstan provides the Baltic republic of
Estonia with grain and receives footwear in return, when what
Kazakhstan really needs is timber, which is plentiful in Estonia.
   Nazarbayev said the self-financing plan will permit the republics
to barter or sell products directly for much-needed supplies, adding
impetus to the housing construction program.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
