<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Banks-FederalReserve     11-21 0210</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Banks-Federal Reserve,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fed Proposes New Curbs On Bank Acquisitions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Reserve Board on Monday proposed a
rule imposing tighter restrictions on the ability of state-chartered
banks to acquire non-banking subsidiaries.
   The rule, proposed by a 6-1 vote with board member Martha Seger
dissenting, would require that the approximately 7,000
state-chartered banks owned by holding companies get the Fed's
permission before estabishing real estate, insurance and other
non-banking subsidiaries.
   Proponents of the rule say some states have moved aggressively to
authorize new activities without regard for bank safety and
soundness. Opponents say the Federal Reserve should not seek more
power over state banks.
   Regulation Y, adopted in 1971, has allowed state banks to
purchase non-bank firms without Fed approval under the Bank Holding
Company Act.
   The change could be adopted in three to six months. It would
exempt non-bank businesses already owned by state-chartered banks,
although Federal Reserve Vice Chairman Manuel Johnson asked the Fed
staff to solicit comment on the possibility of requiring divestiture
of such activities.
   A recent federal court ruling requires nationally-chartered banks
to receive Federal Reserve permission before acquiring a non-bank
subsidiary. The decision is being appealed and the Federal Reserve's
staff said it would propose rules for national banks later.
</TEXT>
