<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hamadi     11-21 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hamadi,0557</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Asks For Psychiatrist to Examine Hamadi</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer for confessed TWA
hijacker Mohammed Ali Hamadi said Monday his client was mentally ill
and he asked the court to authorize a psychiatric examination.
   Also Monday, a former hostage fought back tears as he recalled
offering to take his son-in-law's place when the hijackers took
several hostages off the plane in Beirut.
   Chief Judge Heiner Mueckenberger made no immediate ruling on
lawyer Hans-Burkhardt Steck's request for a psychiatrist.
   Hamadi, a Lebanese Shiite Moslem, is charged with murder and air
piracy in the hijacking of TWA Flight 847 after it left Athens for
Rome in June 1985. U.S. Navy diver Robert Stethem was killed and 39
Americans were held hostage for 17 days.
   Hamadi admits he was one of the hijackers but denies killing
Stethem.
   Steck said Hamadi ``appears to be an adult in many things, but is
a child that had been hindered in his development.''
   He said Hamadi was ``mentally disturbed at the time of the
hijacking'' but had wanted ``a bloodless hijacking.''
   ``The mental and physical damage'' Hamadi had suffered from
fighting in Lebanon ``should have an influence on the sentence.''
   While Steck spoke, the mother of the slain diver, Patricia
Stethem, walked out of the courtroom, apparently fighting back tears.
   She and her husband, Richard, have followed all 34 sessions since
the trial opened July 5.
   Later, American real estate developer Vincente Garza testified
that his son-in-law, Robert Trautmann, was among several hostages
taken off the plane at Beirut Airport and hidden in the city.
   ``I thought he could be the first to be shot, and I asked Hamadi
`don't take him away, take me.' Hamadi just pushed me back,'' said
Garza, 57, his voice cracking with emotion.
   Another American testified that she feared the hijackers would
harm her because she is Jewish.
   ``I heard screams and beatings on more than one occasion,'' said
Mauri Schwarz, a 36-year-old computer saleswoman. ``I was very
afraid because I am Jewish and I didn't know if they knew it.''
   Ms. Schwarz said she saw one passenger ask for medical help
because he had a heart condition ``but the hijackers refused.''
   Hamadi denied this when asked to comment.
   ``If anyone had asked me for a doctor, I would have done that,''
he said.
   The court Monday completed cross-examining Dr. Burton Weber,
whose testimony was interrupted Nov. 15 when Hamadi said he felt ill.
   Weber said Hamadi appeared ``less wild and less mean'' than his
accomplice, Hassan Ezzeddine, who is a fugitive.
   ``He (Hamadi) was not kind and nice and good, but in my mind he
was less frightening,'' Weber said.
   Under court guidelines to protect witnesses, former hostages do
not reveal their hometowns.
   Hamadi was arrested at Frankfurt Airport in 1987 after customs
officials found liquid explosives in his luggage.
   The United States requested his extradition last year, but the
West German government turned it down, fearing for the lives of two
West Germans held hostage in Lebanon. The hostages since have been
released.
   Hamadi's older brother, Abbas, is serving a 13-year prison term
in West Germany in connection with the kidnappings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
