<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DangerousToys     11-21 0644</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dangerous Toys,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Baby Walkers, Crib Gyms Top This Year's Dangerous Toys List</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parents who go Christmas shopping for their
kids should beware _ there are more dangerous toys than ever before,
a consumer group warned Monday.
   While there are a variety of specific toys which are potentially
harmful, entire classes of toys _ baby walkers and crib gyms _ were
singled out as dangerous by the Consumers Affairs Committee of the
Americans for Democratic Action.
   The 17th annual report of the private, non-profit organization
also was critical of the Consumer Product Safety Commission, the
federal agency which oversees toys and other consumer goods.
   A ``major reason for the abundance of dangerous toys'' is ``the
pitiful ineptitude'' of the CPSC, the report said.
   Elaine Tyrrell, a spokeswoman for the CPSC, said the agency would
not have any comment because it hadn't yet seen the report. But she
noted that the CPSC soon will issue its own set of Christmas toy
guidelines.
   The report said ``dangerous and potentially dangerous toys are
more available than ever this year. Our consumer group was inundated
by potentially dangerous toys.''
   The report cited CPSC statistics which blamed toys for causing
131,000 injuries last year, including 105,000 to kids under 15 years
old.
   Baby walkers can tip over or topple down stairs, making them
``highly dangerous,'' the report said. The CPSC received 20,790
injury reports last year from baby walkers, the group noted.
   Crib gyms have caused 12 deaths and 662 other injuries in the
past five years, the report said.
   ``Warnings aren't enough. Crib gyms need to be designed in the
first place without hazards,'' the report said. ``Babies begin to
enjoy crib gyms just at the age that parents are advised to remove
them. So human nature enters the picture and parents leave the crib
gyms a little longer.''
   Among the toys cited by the ADA panel as potentially dangerous:
   _Inflatable sleds, some of which throw up snow that could blind
the driver.
   _Flammable items, including stuffed animals.
   _Household-type toys urging children to imitate adults in a
dangerous fashion. The report cited an electric oven which could
burn a kid and a toy iron that has a realistic-looking plug that
could send children to the nearest electrical outlet.
   _Items which could be dangerous if broken. One example cited was
a toy doctor's kit which included realistic-looking plastic
instruments that could break when a child puts them up to his face,
throat, ears or eyes.
   _Items dangerous for babies, including rattles that don't meet
specified width requirements. A baby could choke on that rattle, the
report said.
   _Toys with inadequate or misleading age labels. In some
instances, manufacturers label a product containing small parts as
``for ages over 3,'' but it still appeals to younger kids.
   Parents who go toy shopping in the next month should keep several
things in mind, the report noted, including:
   _Safety. Look for sharp edges, small parts, projectiles and
potential danger if the toy breaks. Toys with fabric in them should
say the material is flame retardant or flame resistant. Painted toys
should be non-toxic.
   _Look at the toy, not the box. Examine the contents to make sure
it is the same as what's pictured outside.
   _Consider the toy's play value. Will the child enjoy it more than
once or be bored after 15 minutes?
   _Batteries. Few toys include batteries.
   _Save sales receipts. Some stores will match the price of their
competition.
   _Read the directions. Avoid toys with instructions that are too
complicated.
   _Check newspaper ads. Popular toys may go on sale just before
Christmas and be more readily available late in the season.
   _Consider the child's age. Good toys should not require constant
supervision to ensure safety or correct use.
   _Avoid ``hot'' items. They might be cheaper next year, and ads
overglamorize them.
</TEXT>
