<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Dubcek     11-21 0217</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dubcek,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dubcek Visits World War II Massacre Site</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARZABOTTO, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alexander Dubcek, the former
Czechoslovak Communist Party leader, paid homage Monday to victims
of a World War II massacre and condemned fascism as ``the enemy of
democracy.''
   Dubcek, who is on his first visit outside Czechoslovakia in 18
years, visited a shrine honoring the hundreds of civilians killed by
Nazi troops in this town near Bologna on Oct. 2, 1944.
   He paused in silence in front of a monument honoring the
Czechoslovak village of Lidice, which was rebuilt after being razed
by the Nazis and is a sister city to Marzabotto.
   ``I am honored to be here, in this place which testifies to what
Nazism meant,'' Dubcek said. ``Fascism is the enemy of democracy. We
should remember that and do what is necesary so that what happened
is never repeated.''
   He laid a wreath at a tombstone and signed the guest book with a
message expressing hope for ``peace, understanding and general
collaboration among nations.''
   Dubcek, who came to Italy earlier this month to receive an
honorary degree from the University of Bologna, tried to liberalize
Czechoslovakia's political and economic system through the ``Prague
Spring'' reforms of 1968.
   The movement was crushed by a Soviet-led invasion and Dubcek was
removed from the party.
</TEXT>
