<1ST_LINE>r p AM-ChicagoMayoral     11-21 0593</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chicago Mayoral,0608</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Supreme Court Sets Chicago Mayoral Vote Next Spring</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DOWLING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Illinois Supreme Court set the stage
Monday for Chicago's third mayoral free-for-all in six years, ruling
that voters must decide who serves the last two years of the late
Mayor Harold Washington's term.
   Siding with city officials who scheduled a Feb. 28 primary and an
April 4 general election next year, rather than waiting until 1991,
the court said Mayor Eugene Sawyer's appointment by the City Council
after Washington's death does not extend through 1991, when
Washington's term ends.
   Washington died of a heart attack on Nov. 25, 1987, less than
eight months after winning a second term.
   The seven justices ruled without written dissent that state laws
governing vacancies in office were designed to ensure that an
appointed official would not serve such a long portion of an
unexpired term.
   Supporters of a 1991 election had argued their case was supported
by the state Election Code, which says the mayor of Chicago should
be chosen in a spring election every four years beginning in 1979.
The court said that only prescribes regularly scheduled elections
``where the incumbent official continues in office.''
   Sawyer, who supported a 1991 election but has indicated he is
prepared to run next year, said he was ``pleased that this decision
has been made and that the people in Chicago are no longer in
limbo.''
   ``We are ready for the upcoming election and look forward to
winning it,'' said Sawyer, who raised nearly $3 million in less than
a year against the possibility of a spring election.
   The ruling also drew applause from the field of announced and
would-be candidates poised to make next year's mayoral race the most
crowded in the city's recent history.
   ``I think it's the decision the public wanted,'' said Alderman
Lawrence Bloom, a staunch Washington ally who was among the first to
announce his candidacy for a 1989 mayoral race. ``They didn't want
29 members of the City Council to elect their mayor for three
years.''
   Cook County State's Attorney Richard M. Daley, widely reported to
be planning a second bid for the job his father held for two
decades, said he would make an announcement ``in the next two
weeks.''
   ``This is a serious decision,'' Daley said.
   Aldermen Timothy Evans and Danny Davis, both considered leading
contenders for Washington's mantle of black political leadership in
Chicago, also praised the decision.
   According to a recent Chicago Sun-Times-ABC television poll,
Daley is supported by 37 percent of all voters. Evans was second at
22 percent, Sawyer third with 10 percent, and Bloom fourth with 9
percent.
   The remaining 22 percent was divided among the other announced
candidates _ Davis, Alderman Edward Burke, former Chicago Parks
District Superintendent Edmund Kelly _ and ``undecided.''
   The possibility of three black candidates _ Sawyer, Evans and
Davis _ raises the possibility of a split in the black voting bloc
that made Washington the city's first black mayor in 1983, and
lifted him to re-election in 1987.
   Such a split would strengthen Daley, who split the white vote
with former Mayor Jane Byrne in a 1983 Democratic primary and thus
helped Washington move into the general election, in which Democrats
historically have been prohibitive favorites. No Republican has been
Chicago's mayor for more than half a century.
   Monday's court ruling came in a suit filed in April by Evans'
supporters, who sought the early election in an effort to deny
Sawyer time to consolidate his power.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
