<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LibraryHistory     11-21 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Library History,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Library Faced Ideological, Environmental Pitfalls</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Reagan Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SIMI VALLEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sponsors of a library documenting the
Reagan presidency have had to steer around a variety of pitfalls,
from liberal Stanford University professors to a rare six-inch
sunflower.
   Groundbreaking here Monday for the Ronald Reagan Presidential
Library was made possible by a compromise with environmentalists
that protects the sunflower and two other rare plants.
   Before that, the Ronald Reagan Foundation had to overcome
concerns that the project would detract from a section of rolling
coastal mountain range set aside by local planners as a protected
area.
   And all that came after the foundation abandoned its original
plans to construct the library on a 20-acre Northern California site
at Stanford in conjunction with a proposed policy center.
   Neighbors of the university had complained about expected tourist
traffic, while liberal professors didn't want the campus used to
enshrine the memory of a conservative champion.
   Stanford's trustees split the library from the proposed policy
center in 1984, but planning for the library continued into 1987, up
to the point that blueprints were unveiled with fanfare in
Washington.
   In April 1987, the foundation canceled its Stanford plans,
publicly citing the separation three years earlier of the library
from the policy center.
   In the ensuing months, a number of potential sites in Southern
California were rumored to be under consideration, including the
University of California, Riverside and the University of Southern
California.
   But the nod went to a site outside Simi Valley, some 50 miles
northwest of Los Angeles, a former country town that has become a
bedroom community. The library will be set in dry hills covered with
scrub brush and dotted with cactus _ perhaps a fitting setting for
the first president whose start in public life was as a cowboy actor.
   Community concerns, more muted this time, centered on visitor
traffic and the location in an area set aside as a natural buffer
between three growing communities. Environmentalists envisioned
bulldozers rumbling over the tiny yellow sunflower known to
scientists as Pentachaeta lyonii, as well as two other rare plants.
   But environmental objections were headed off by compromise: The
foundation will try to replace any plants it destroys, work to
protect and spread the species on the site, and limit public hours
to minimize traffic.
</TEXT>
