<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Bush-Mexico 1stLd-Writethru a0602 11-21 0611</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Mexico, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0602,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Presidents-Elect Seek Harmony on Economics, Other Issues</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 3rd graf to update with Wright meeting, clarify Bush
pledge</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect George Bush and Mexico's
incoming President Carlos Salinas de Gortari meet Tuesday in Houston
in a bid to move cross-border relations onto a smoother track after
an extended period of recriminations.
   Bush said last week that with new administrations in both
countries taking office at about the same time, a ``tremendous
opportunity'' is available for a cooperative relationship.
   Last Friday, Bush conferred at length on the meeting with House
Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas. Bush has promised that after taking
office he will take no measures that affect Mexico without first
consulting Mexican authorities.
   Bush will be accompanied to the luncheon meeting at the Johnson
Space Center by Secretary of State-designate James Baker and
Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady. Salinas, who will be inaugurated
on Dec. 1, will be accompanied by top aides as well.
   Economic issues will be at the top of the agenda, but the
discussions also are expected to touch on drug smuggling, Central
America and other issues.
   Salinas has said that Mexico's obligations in servicing its $108
billion foreign debt should be designed in a way that permits
continued economic growth.
   He is worried that protectionist trade pressures in the United
States could lead to a decline in Mexico's cross-border exports,
further aggravating an economic crisis that has afflicted the
country since 1982.
   A rise in U.S. interest rates also would impair Mexico's ability
to repay its debt.
   While the two countries have shown an ability to cooperate on
economic issues, there have been serious disagreements over Central
America and drugs.
   The Reagan administration has said that, aside from Cuba, no
hemispheric country has supported Nicaragua's leftist government
more enthusiastically than Mexico, which has played a leading role
in the Central American peace process.
   In the 1987 U.N. General Assembly, Mexico supported the U.S.
position on issues of high priority to the United States less than
15 per cent of the time, according to State Department figures.
   One official, insisting on anonymity, said Assistant Secretary of
State Elliott Abrams and Mexico's Foreign Secretary Bernardo
Sepulveda have a ``shoot on sight'' relationship.
   Both Abrams and Sepulveda will be replaced by their respective
incoming presidents. A State Department official said there are
preliminary indications that the new foreign ministry team being
assembled by Salinas may be less ideologically opposed to U.S.
administration views.
   In a recent interview, Abrams said, ``We have been very unhappy
with what we consider the kind of ideological tone in some of
Mexico's foreign policy as distinct from a pragmatic tone.
   ``There have been occasions when we felt that Mexico was picking
a fight with the United States, not because it was in the interest
of Mexico to do so, for what must have been complex reasons in
Mexico's foreign policy and Mexico's domestic politics.''
   One recent sign of Mexico's pursuit of an independent foreign
policy was a visit to Cuba by outgoing Mexican President Miguel de
la Madrid, who conferred Mexico's highest civilian decoration on
President Fidel Castro.
   On the drug issue, Mexico believes the United States bears much
of the blame for continued narcotics trafficking across the border
because of the strong U.S. demand for drugs.
   The Reagan administration has been increasingly emphasizing a
need to reduce demand but maintains that ``corruption and
inefficiencies'' in Mexico have impeded efforts to curb the drug
flow.
   According to the State Department, Mexico is the principal source
country for the production, processing and trafficking of heroin and
marijuana entering the United States.
</TEXT>
