<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-88 1558EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-KennedyMonument     11-21 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kennedy Monument,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Almost 25 Years Later, Kennedy Monument Recovered In Wolcott</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WOLCOTT, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A marble-and-brass monument commemorating
John F. Kennedy's visits to the Waterbury area has been found nearly
25 years after it was cast and stored to await the opening of the
presidential library in Massachusetts.
   Robert Carroll, a member of the committee that commissioned the
monument in 1964 in the wake of the president's assassination, said
Monday that he discovered the monument in a Wolcott High School
storage room in September.
   He said he didn't tell anyone about the discovery until recently
so the news would coincide with the 25th anniversary of the
assassination on Tuesday.
   The Wolcott residents who commissioned the monument intended to
send it to the John F. Kennedy Presidential Library on the
University of Massachusetts campus in Boston's Dorchester section.
   ``I think once they (at the library) see this, it's really the
kind of a monument _ it's probably valued at $4,000 to $5,000 _ that
belongs there,'' Carroll said.
   The white marble plaque with a brass plate, the cost of which was
underwritten by the Scovill Manufacturing Co. and Chase Brass &
Copper Co., both of Waterbury, memorializes Kennedy's visits to
Waterbury on the eve of the 1960 election and in 1962.
   An estimated 50,000 people greeted Kennedy on Nov. 6, 1960 at 3
a.m. in downtown Waterbury. Wolcott borders Waterbury and Carroll
said many of its residents hail from the blue-collar city.
   The monument bears the presidential seal and a quotation from a
speech Kennedy delivered on his second visit to Waterbury, on Oct.
17, 1962:
   Carroll said a black-tie ball in Waterbury in November 1964 was
held to remember the late president's promise. His mother, Rose
Kennedy, attended, Carroll said.
   ``The problem (in 1964) was that the Kennedy Library had not been
built yet, so the plaque had to be stored somewhere until the
library was complete,'' he recalled.
   Carroll said he suggested keeping it in a closet in the high
school. The monument was promptly forgotten, he said.
   He said he had intended to bring it to the library on the
assassination anniversary, but the library's curator and one-time
Kennedy assistant, David Powers, reminded him that ``the family
doesn't prefer to remember that date.'' Instead, Carroll said he
will take the plaque to Boston next year on May 29, the late
president's birthday.
   Powers said the library will accept the plaque, but he couldn't
say whether or not it will be displayed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
