<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-88 1607EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Bush-Boskin     11-21 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Boskin,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Economist Says Monday's Non-Appointment No Surprise</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stanford economist Michael Boskin said Monday
he was surprised by reports that President-elect George Bush was
about to name him chairman of the president's Council of Economic
Advisers.
   Boskin said he was sitting at home in California watching
television when he first heard news reports over the weekend that he
was about to be appointed Bush's chief economic adviser.
   ``I was quite suprised by the rumors,'' Boskin said in a
telephone interview. ``It is flattering to have my name mentioned as
a possibility, but President-elect Bush has many outstanding
individuals who would make excellent appointments to the CEA.''
   A conservative economist and expert on the Social Security
system, Boskin is the father of Bush's ``flexible freeze'' idea to
drive down the deficit. He is still considered the front-runner to
be named chairman of the economic council.
   Bush, when asked by reporters on Monday what had happened to
Boskin's appointment, said, ``Nothing happened. Just don't believe
all the leaks you read in the newspapers.''
   Craig Fuller, co-director of the transition, said, ``We have a
high regard for him. We're still working on the chairman's
appointment.''
   Boskin called reports of the appointment ``premature'' and said
he has not yet received any offer of a job in the Bush
administration.
   Boskin, who described himself as a ``mainstream conservative,''
said he expects Bush ``will move quickly and decisively to assemble
an outstanding team to assist him in the transition and the
government. But this won't happen overnight. It may take a few
weeks.''
   He praised Bush's selection of Richard Darman as head of Office
of Management and Budget, saying, ``Dick Darman is one of the most
talented people I know.''
   In addition to Darman as OMB director, Bush has asked Treasury
Secretary Nicholas Brady to stay on in his administration.
   That leaves the chairman of the Council of Economic Advisers as
the only top economic post remaining to be filled.
   Bush has said that he considered the naming of his economic team
to be a priority as a way of sending a signal to jittery financial
markets that the new administration planned to get a quick start in
reducing the federal budget deficit.
</TEXT>
