<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     11-21 0627</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0648</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUNSWICK, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A coastal Georgia town has regained its
honor as the home of the Brunswick stew champions of the world.
   Two local women reclaimed the stew championship this weekend in a
spoon-to-spoon battle with the dreaded enemy from Brunswick County,
Va.
   Lisa Cook and Fran Kelly, restaurant partners from nearby St.
Simons Island, won top honors in the latest battle in the ``Stew
Wars'' between Brunswick, Ga., and the Virginia county, both of
which claim to be the birthplace of Brunswick stew.
   ``The honor of Georgia has been very successfully defended on the
Brunswick stew battlefield,'' said Phyllis Taunton of Main Street
Brunswick, a sponsor of Saturday's stew-cooking contest.
   Last year, Virginians swept the first Brunswick stew cookoff,
held in Virginia and judged by an all-Virginia panel of judges.
   Georgians have contended since then that the Virginia contest was
rigged. Saturday's contest, on the other hand, was fair, Mrs.
Taunton said.
   Why?
   The judges were three Georgians: Atlanta TV personality Leroy
Powell, Atlanta chef and author Nathalie Dupree and Missy
Castleberry McDavid, of the Castleberry Foods family in Augusta.
   Mrs. Taunton said the fact that George Daniels of Alberta, Va.,
and Bill Denton of Richmond took second and third places in the
professional ``stewmaster'' category proved that the contest was on
the level.
   For the uninitiated, Brunswick stew is a spicy concoction of
smoked meat, chicken, corn, tomatoes and other ingredients.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WINTERGREEN, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Women will have 50 percent more restrooms
than men in new public buildings in Virginia, as officialdom tries
to compensate for the different lengths of time the sexes spend in
the bathroom.
   Jack Rollison of the House of Delegates proposed the ``potty
parity'' revision to the state building code after a study showed
that women take longer in restrooms and are forced to wait in lines
to use the facilities at sporting events and theaters. The study
said women take more time because they frequently are accompanied by
small children and because they wear more clothes than men.
   The State Housing and Community Development Board voted Saturday
to increase the required number of women's restrooms in public
places by 50 percent, effective March 1. The provision will apply
only to new construction of large public gathering places such as
sports arenas and movie theaters. Men's and women's restrooms are
currently required to be built in an even ratio.
   ``I'm pleased they made the change,'' Rollison said. ``I think
this will open some new doors for women in the commonwealth.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After 15 years as a grade-school teacher, Bob
Anton made a quantum career change that is letting him look forward
to a winter with little more to do than tinker with his river boat.
   Last spring, Anton, 42, left teaching for the opportunity of his
dreams: to captain the brand new $1.8 million Spirit of Peoria
paddlewheeler.
   ``I liked teaching and I thought I would really miss it when
September rolled around. I was afraid I'd drive by a school
playground full of kids and really be drawn to it. But that hasn't
happened,'' said Anton, whose deeply etched face, bushy mustache and
tousled hair make him resemble an earlier river boat captain, Mark
Twain.
   Instead of spending nine months fantasizing about the river,
Anton is now living his dream in a pilot house.
   ``This is my favorite place,'' he said, looking down on the
wind-whipped Illinois River and the Peoria skyline.
   ``I look at the boat as a time machine. While everyone else in
the world is moving around at fast speed, we go up and down the
river at five miles per hour. You really go back in time when you go
out on a boat.''
</TEXT>
