<HEAD>2 Men Arrested In Theft Of $1 Million In Jewelry; Most Recovered
In
N.H.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men have been arrested in the theft of a
shipment of about $1 million worth of jewelry, much of which was
found buried in a cracker tin in New Hampshire, a federal prosecutor
said Monday.
   Carroll Hiscock Wade Jr., 26, formerly of Conway, N.H., was
arrested by the FBI in Anchorage, Alaska, on Nov. 15 and indicted
the same day on a charge of interstate transportation of stolen
property, acting U.S. Attorney Peter Papps said.
   Ralph Hernandez, 26, was picked up by the FBI in Los Angeles the
same day and charged with stealing from an interstate shipment,
Papps said.
   Both men were to appear before U.S. magistrates for bail hearings
in the cities where they were arrested, and the case will be heard
in Anchorage.
   The FBI opened an investigation in Anchorage after 136 loose
diamonds and 105 gold rings were stolen from a Federal Express
shipment in March, Papps said. The jewelry was being sent from an
Indianapolis jewelry store to Anchorage.
   Ninety-two diamonds and 84 gold rings, valued at about $850,000,
were recovered in June buried in a cracker tin in a forest in
Conway, where Wade lived until several years ago, Papps said. He
declined to say how authorities learned where the jewelry was buried
or disclose more about the investigation.
   Additional items were recovered in Alaska, and some jewelry still
is missing, he said.
