<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Shooting,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Soldier Kills Lieutenant, Self</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Israeli soldier disciplined for unruly
behavior opened fire near a commander's office Monday, killing an
officer and wounding another soldier before committing suicide, army
officials said.
   Pvt. Yitzhak Kalfon apparently was upset because a disciplinary
court had sentenced him to 21 days in a military prison, said the
officials, who insisted on anonymity.
   Killed was Lt. Yair Levy, reported to be a commander in the unit
in which Kalfon served but not Kalfon's direct supervisor.
   The state-run Itim news agency said Kalfon, a cook at a southern
Israel army base, was informed of the court's ruling Monday. The
army said he was disciplined for unruly behavior, but would not
elaborate.
   Kalfon took a M-16 assault rifle from the armory and ran toward
the commander's office, Itim said.
   ``He came into the office breathing deeply and sprayed the gun in
every direction,'' Itim quoted a lieutenant colonel as saying. He
was not identified by name in keeping with military regulations.
   The lieutenant colonel said Levy tried to escape to a nearby room
but was struck by a bullet that penetrated the door.
   The woman soldier, struck in the left arm, was identified as
Perla Yudovsky.
   The army would not give the exact location of base for security
reasons.
   Military police launched an investigation into the incident, the
officials said.
