<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Stormie Jones,0140</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heart-Liver Transplant Patient Discharged</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 11-year-old Texas girl who was the world's
first recipient of a heart and liver transplant was released from
Children's Hospital of Pittsburgh on Monday following surgery to
clear blocked bile ducts.
   Stormie Jones of White Settlement, Texas, was released in fair
condition and was scheduled to return home immediately, said a
hospital spokeswoman.
   She was readmitted to the hospital Oct. 26 because doctors feared
she was rejecting her organs, but she began improving after surgery
on Nov. 8 to clear blockages from her bile duct.
   Stormie received her donated heart and liver Feb. 14, 1984. She
needed the transplant because of a rare congenital disease that
increased the cholesterol in her blood to dangerous levels.
   She is the only surviving recipient of the double transplant.
  
