<HEAD>25 Harlem Children Assured College Tuition In Year 2000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-five Harlem first-graders were told Monday
that they will be assured of money for college if they finish high
school, and they declared: ``We are the happiest children in the
world.''
   The potential members of the class of the year 2000 are
beneficiaries of the ``ScholarshipBuilder'' program of Merrill Lynch
& Co. and the National Urban League.
   ``You may not fully understand the significance of this,''
Manhattan Borough President David Dinkins told the 6-yeremony at their
school, Rafael Hernandez-Langston Hughes
Elementary. ``But with an education you can be anything you want to
ear-olds in a
cbe.''
   The program, underwritten by the Merrill Lynch Foundation, will
provide the 25 children here and an additional 225 in nine other
cities full college tuition or cash incentives if they don't drop
out.
   The other cities are Atlanta, Boston, Chicago, Detroit, Houston,
Los Angeles, Miami, Washington and Philadelphia.
   Private college tuition when the first graders are ready to enter
will average about $17,500 per year, by foundation estimate.
Students who elect to skip college and get a job or join the Army
after high school will get a one-time $1,000 payment for clothes and
travel expenses.
   Asked what she wanted to be when she grew up, 6-year-old Ashley
Lightbourn replied: ``Maybe a doctor.'' But mLorain
area veterans, service and professional organizations and schools
and churches urging participation in the drive.
   Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated
Press, has been held captive by Shiite Moslem extremists in Lebanon
since he was kidnapped March 16, 1985, from a Beirut street.
   The committee must receive cards at P.O. Box 391, Lorain, by Dec.
8 so they can be shipped to Lebanon in time for Christmas. Rep.
Donald Pease, D-Ohio, is handling arrangements to mail the cards and
letters to Lebanon, the group said.
   The effort is being cheered by Anderson's sister, Peggy Say, now
of Cadiz, Ky. Such a campaign, she said, demonstrates to both her
brother and the federal government that the hostages will not be
forgotten.
   ``Everybody I've talked with, and that's an awful lot of people,
said the thing we need to do is keep the issue alive. Certainly,
Christmas cards are a way to do that,'' Mrs. Say said.
