<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ThorsonSentenced     11-21 0194</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Thorson Sentenced,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Liberace Companion Gets Probation for Robbery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who once sued entertainer Liberace for
palimony was placed on three years' probation Monday and credited
with time already served in jail for his role in a series of
drug-related robberies.
   Scott Alan Thorson, 31, who described his homosexual relationship
with the late Liberace in a recent book, also was sentenced to a
year in the county jail, but the judge credited him with the 348
days he's already spent in custody.
   Thorson pleaded guilty in July to one count of robbery for his
role in a ring prosecutors said staged a series of violent
drug-related robberies. He is awaiting trial on an unrelated charge
of receiving stolen property.
   Thorson lived in Liberace's Las Vegas home and worked as
bodyguard and servant before the flamboyant entertainer died last
year of complications of AIDS.
   The palimony lawsuit Thorson brought against Liberace, claiming
the dancer had an ``intimate sexual and emotional relationship''
with the entertainer, was dismissed in May 1983. A Superior Court
judge ruled there were no grounds for Thorson to make claims for
support payments from the pianist.
</TEXT>
