<DOCNO> AP881121-0142 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-88 1618EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Bush-Confirmation     11-21 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Confirmation,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Holdover Cabinet Appointees Don't Need New Confirmation</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush's three holdover Cabinet appointees
won't face a second round of Senate confirmation hearings thanks to
a ruling 60 years ago on then-Treasury Secretary Andrew Mellon,
Senate officials said Monday.
   Bush has asked Attorney General Dick Thornburgh, Education
Secretary Lauro Cavazos and Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady to
stay in their jobs in his new administration.
   All three men have joined the Reagan administration since August,
and all experienced no problems being confirmed by a majority of the
Senate.
   Michael Davidson, the Senate's legal counsel, said they wouldn't
have to undergo the confirmation process next year _ unless Bush
wanted them to. If he did, the men would formally resign, only to be
re-nominated by Bush.
   That won't happen, Bush's transition aides said.
   ``We're following the precedent that we think was wisely ...
followed by Martin Van Buren, who did not submit his nominees that
were held over for reconfirmation,'' said Craig Fuller, co-director
of Bush's transition office.
   Since George Washington's time there have been cases of Cabinet
appointees remaining in office over the span of more than one
president, according to Davidson, the Senate's legal counsel.
   For example, Secretary of State Timothy Pickering served both
Washington and John Adams without separate confirmation hearings, he
said.
   But the practice was tested in 1929 when a Senate Judiciary
Committee panel investigated the case of Mellon, a Republican
financier who was treasury secretary in the Harding, Coolidge and
Hoover administrations, Davidson said.
   ``This was undertaken in the case of Mellon but it is applicable
to Thornburgh, Cavazos and Brady,'' he said.
   Six decades ago, the senators concluded Cabinet appointees need
not face additional Senate confirmation rounds because there was no
statute limiting their terms, Davidson said.
   ``They (the members of the Senate) were of the opinion such
officials could remain in office indefinitely,'' he said, at the
pleasure of the president.
   If the Senate wanted to require new confirmation hearings on
holdover appointments at the end of an administration, it would have
to pass a law on that subject, Davidson said.
   Two days after Bush was elected on Nov. 8, President Reagan
ordered all his appointees to submit their resignations in a timely
fashion.
   Bush's decision to name the holdover Cabinet people obviously
signals that Reagan will not accept resignations from Thornburgh,
Brady and Cavazos, according to Melinda Kitchell, a spokeswoman for
the Education Department.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881121-0143 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-88 1759EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Smoking-ChipMaker     11-21 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Smoking-Chip Maker,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Company Uses Austin, San Antonio As Test Sites For No-Smoking
Policy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting a0682 to change slug to avoid duplication with
AM-No Smoking from Frankfort, Ky.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A computer chip maker has adopted a strict
no-smoking policy in its Texas plants in a policy shift that some
predict will sweep the U.S. semiconductor industry.
   The new rules, which take effect Jan. 2, apply to all Texas
employees of Advanced Micro Devices Inc. _ 2,200 in Austin and 900
in San Antonio.
   ``It's kind of a pilot project in Texas,'' said David Frink, a
local spokesman for the California-based company.
   The company plans to remove ash trays and cigarette machines and
has encouraged workers to join smoking cessation classes, designed
by the American Cancer Society.
   Employees previously were allowed to smoke in designated areas,
although never in the ``clean rooms'' where delicate computer chips
are made.
   Frink said the company revised its smoking policy to eliminate a
potential source of chip-destroying contaminants. A speck of dust or
smoke particle can block part of a microscopic circuit and ruin a
chip.
   He said it also responds to recent evidence linking nonsmokers'
health hazards to second-hand smoke.
   The company chose Texas for the experiment because its operations
are smaller here than in California, Frink told the Austin
American-Statesman. In addition, chips made in Texas are among its
most sensitive.
   Other chipmakers predicted more companies would follow suit.
   Stan Victor, a spokesman for Texas Instruments in Dallas, said
the company discourages smoking but has not yet gone as far as
Advanced Micro Devices.
   Texas Instruments offers smoking cessation classes to employees
and their spouses, Victor said, and asks clean room employees who
smoke during breaks to rinse their mouths with water and wait at
least five minutes before re-entering the chip-making area.
   Scott Wyman, a spokesman for International Business Machines
Corp., said the company has banned smoking in some of its newer
manufacturing buildings. But it allows designated smoking areas in
compliance with an Austin ordinance.
   The manager of contamination engineering for Sematech, Keith
Dillenbeck, said Advanced Micro Devices' policy likely will spread
through the industry.
   ``There is a trend in that direction,'' Dillenbeck said.
   Dillenbeck said technical journals have indicated smoke can
linger in the mouth and lungs, as well as cling to clothes and hair,
as long as two hours after smoking.
   As a result, he said, smokers in the clean room may generate as
many as 10 times more particles than non-smokers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
