<HEAD>Blood-Stained Mattress Leads to Murder Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST LYME, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The discovery of a bloodstained mattress
in a motel has led police in Connecticut and Georgia to begin a
murder investigation, although authorities said Monday no body has
been recovered.
   A maid entered Room 12 at the Starlight Motel in East Lyme near
the Connecticut shoreline about noon last Friday to find that a
mattress that ``had been stained with a large quantity of blood,''
state police said in a statement.
   Two men riding in a gray or silver Cadillac with a Georgia
registration had checked into the motel room on Nov. 15 for several
days, and left before the discovery, state police said.
   Police said they are working on the case with the Georgia Bureau
of Investigation, issuing a nationwide alert in an effort to find
the men.
   State police said they are not aware of any missing person's
report that might have been linked to the incident.
   Marcy Stamm, a state police spokeswoman, said no weapon was found
in the room. She said police would not comment on other evidence
that led them to conclude a crime had occurred.
