<1ST_LINE>r w AM-AcidRain     11-21 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Acid Rain,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>States Go To Court With EPA Again Over Acid Rain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine states filed a new lawsuit Monday against
the Environmental Protection Agency in their 5-year legal effort to
force the agency to order new acid rain controls in the Midwest.
   The states, joined by the National Audubon Society, asked the
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia to review
EPA's refusal to act on their petition seeking those controls.
   That petition called on EPA to publish for public comment the
determination of the Carter administration's EPA chief that sulfur
dioxide emissions from the United States were harming Canada. Such a
publication is the first step in drafting a regulation.
   The Canadian province of Ontario and two environmental
organizations filed a similar lawsuit in the same court on Nov. 1.
   A few days before leaving office in January 1981, EPA
Administrator Douglas Costle wrote Secretary of State Edmund Muskie
that these emissions were harming Canada by being transformed in the
atmosphere into sulfuric acid, which falls as acid rain in eastern
Canada.
   Many of these sulfur dioxide emissions originate in the U.S.
Midwest in power plant and factory smokestacks.
   Once such a determination is made, U.S. law requires EPA to order
affected states to revise their air pollution control plans to
eliminate the offending emissions. But the appeals court, in a
decision upheld by the Supreme Court, ruled earlier that a letter to
the secretary of state was not formal enough, and any such
determination had to be made in formal proceedings leading to a
regulation.
   Ontario, the nine states and various environmental groups all
petitioned for such formal proceedings, but EPA in October said it
would not act on those petitions because it still did not know
enough to tell states in the Midwest how to revise their air
pollution control measures.
   Environmentalists say acid rain has made hundreds of lakes in the
Adirondack Mountains of New York State unlivable for fish. Canada
says 14,000 lakes in the eastern half of that country have been
damaged.
   David Wooley, an assistant attorney general of New York State,
one of the plaintiff states, said in Albany, N.Y., the states are
entitled to sue because they are harmed by the same pollutant
harming Canada. He said he has asked that his lawsuit be
consolidated with Ontario's.
   In addition to New York, the plaintiff states are the six New
England states, New Jersey and Minnesota.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881121-0148 </DOCNO>
