<HEAD>Lawyer Whose Passport Seized Denied Hearing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief justice on Monday refused to
grant a hearing to a lawyer who says his constitutional rights were
violated when the government seized his passport.
   The lawyer, Gibson Kamau Kuria, had his passport seized when he
was arrested last year after filing a case on behalf of three people
who said they were tortured by police while being detained without
charges.
   Kuria, who also was detained without charges for eight months,
was released in December 1987.
   Kuria's lawyer, Murungi Kiraitu, petitioned for a hearing to
determine whether the government denied Kuria his legal right to
travel by withholding his passport.
   Justice Cecil Miller said Monday that Kuria's application for a
constitutional court was ``misconceived.''
   ``The constitutional court can only be constituted where there is
a contitutional point in the case,'' Keiwua had argued. ``In this
case there is no such constitutional point raised by the applicant.''
   Kiraitu, who is Kuria's law partner, said he would appeal
Miller's ruling.
   On Wednesday, Georgetown University gave Kuria the Robert F.
Kennedy Human Rights Award for his work in defense of political
prisoners. The award said he was ``one of the few lawyers in Kenya
who defends political prisoners.''
</TEXT>
