<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Sahara     11-21 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Sahara,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N.-Mediated Talks on Western Sahara Set for Dec. 1-2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.N.-mediated talks to end Western Sahara's
guerrilla war will take place Dec. 1-2 between representatives from
Morocco, which controls most of the territory, and the Polisario
independence movement, a U.N. spokeswoman said Monday.
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar will mediate the talks,
said the spokeswoman, Nadia Younes. She did not know who the
representatives from Morocco or Polisario would be.
   The Marxist-led Polisario has been battling Morocco since 1975,
when the Spanish colonial administration pulled out of Western
Sahara and Morocco invaded the northwest African desert territory.
   In August, Polisario and Moroccan officials gave tentative
approval for the United Nations to monitor a referendum leading to
independence or affiliation with Morocco. No date has been set and
other details are in dispute.
   Polisario representatives in New York have said they have about
7,000 fighters, and they want all but 7,000 of the 185,000 Moroccan
troops in Western Sahara withdrawn before the referendum.
   Polisario also wants an end to Moroccan administration and law in
Western Sahara before the referendum.
   The United Nations plans to send 2,000 peacekeeping troops to the
110,000-square-mile territory to monitor the referendum.
   At the last census in 1974, the population was set at about
76,000. Only Saharans counted in that census will be eligible to
vote in the referendum.
</TEXT>
