<2ND_LINE>AM-Farm Loans,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Want Farmers Given More Time to Answer Payment Demands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Farmers Home Administration should allow
more time for delinquent borrowers to file replies to the agency's
demand that they come up with a plan to settle overdue accounts,
Rep. Byron L. Dorgan, D-N.D., said Monday.
   Dorgan said 14 members of Congress sent a letter last week to
Vance Clark, head of the FmHA, asking that the 45-day time period be
extended. Notices were sent out last week to 83,500 FmHA borrowers
who are behind in loan repayments.
   Under the rules, the borrowers will have 45 days to reply to FmHA
with information on how they intend to repay, refinance or
restructure overdue loans totaling more than $8 billion.
   Dorgan said the notices, scheduled for mailing Nov. 14-25, put
the 45-day deadline just after the first of next year. Borrowers who
fail to respond in time, or whose proposals are rejected, face
foreclosure by FmHA, he said.
   ``These notices include over 200 pages of complex regulations,''
Dorgan said. ``I feel the farmers should be given sufficient time to
analyze the regulations and compile the necessary information to
fill out the forms corrently.''
   FmHA spokesman Marlyn Aycock said he did not know of any plan by
the agency to extend the 45-day period. ``Not at this point,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
