<2ND_LINE>AM-Sundlun Concedes,0186</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sundlun Concedes Governor's Race</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two weeks after he lost to Republican
Gov. Edward D. DiPrete, Democratic gubernatorial candidate Bruce G.
Sundlun conceded defeat Monday, but said he was leaving the door
``wide open'' for a third run in 1990.
   ``The outcome of this election was disappointing, but the
campaign we waged makes me take heart,'' Sundlun said at a news
conference.
   Sundlun refused to concede on election night, after returns
showed him the loser by a margin of almost 2 percent _ 202,962 votes
for DiPrete and 196,188 for Sundlun. Sundlun's campaign requested a
recount and counting of about 16,000 mail-in ballots, a process that
concluded Thursday with Sundlun still trailing by about 6,800 votes.
   In his first attempt to wrest the governorship from DiPrete, in
1986, Sundlun lost by a 2-1 margin. But this year he made the race
close by repeatedly questioning DiPrete's ethics.
   Sundlun, multimillionaire chairman of Outlet Communications Inc.,
said he would maintain a small staff of researchers and program
developers with an eye toward running for governor again in two
years.
