<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     11-21 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0484</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wet In Northwest, Stormy In Northeast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Windy, wet weather blew across the Northwest on Monday, and a
departing storm dragged wind and showers across New England.
   A cold front across the Pacific Northwest was accompanied by
gusty wind and numerous showers. Wind gusted to 50 mph early in the
day at Friday Harbor, Wash., and Astoria, Ore.
   Rain spread from western and central Washington state through
western Oregon into northern California, and Astoria, Ore., got 1.11
inches of rain in 24 hours.
   A low pressure system moving away from New England left gusty
northwesterly wind in its wake, plus snow showers scattered across
northern parts of New England, from northeastern New York state into
northern Maine. Showers were scattered across western New York state
with snow scattered over the mountains of Pennsylvania.
   High wind knocked out power to at least 3,500 utility customers
in western Massachusetts, sent a 53 mph gust through Chicopee and
may have caused a truck to overturn on a Massachusetts highway
Monday, authorities said.
   Police said wind in Palmer, Mass., took a 5-foot section of brick
off the top of a Main Street building, damaging a few cars parked
below.
   Parts of western Massachusetts got up to 2{ inches of rain
overnight. The Connecticut River at Montague City rose to 15.88 feet
by Monday from 10.56 feet Saturday, according to the Greenfield
Pollution Control Facility. Flood stage there is 28 feet.
   Tropical Storm Keith had moved into the Gulf of Mexico and was
just short of hurricane strength by late afternoon. Meteorologists
said it probably would head toward the west coast of Florida later
in the week.
   Temperatures dipped in Texas early Monday, with a record low of
22 at Midland and a record low of just 20 at San Angelo.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 17
degrees at Minot, N.D., to 86 at Avon Park, Fla. Monday morning's
low was 8 degrees below zero at Alamosa, Colo.
   For Tuesday, scattered showers and thunderstorms from tropical
storm Keith were forecast over northern Florida. Rain and gusty wind
was forecast along the northern half of the Pacific Coast region and
inland through the Pacific Northwest.
   Highs in the 20s were predicted over northwestern Minnesota; in
the 30s from the rest of the northern Plains through the upper
Mississippi Valley and the upper Great Lakes into New England; in
the 60s from the southern Atlantic Coast through the Gulf Coast,
Texas, the central high Plains and the southern Rockies into
southern California; in the 70s from southern Arizona into the Los
Angeles basin, the lower Rio Grande Valley of Texas and the northern
Florida Peninsula; in the low 80s across central and southern
Florida; and in the 40s or 50s across much of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
