<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-88 1945EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-GAO-Trade     11-21 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-GAO-Trade,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Advised to Use New Powers on World Trade</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect George Bush should make
vigorous use of new powers that Congress has given the president to
get satisfaction from other countries in trade disputes, a
congressional investigative agency said Monday.
   In one of a series of reports on important issues for the
transition to the new presidency, the General Accounting Office said
it has found many instances when a follow-up was needed to get the
benefits of an international trade agreement.
   It added that delaying tactics and slow dispute settlements have
often frustrated efforts to get satisfaction, but the new Trade Act
strengthens the U.S. hand.
   ``Failure to gain timely satisfaction can now trigger a
unilateral U.S. response,'' the GAO report said. ``The new
administration should show strong resolve to vigorously use these
new powers.''
   One provision of the trade law Reagan signed in August permits
him to specify what he considers high-priority unfair trade
practices and to start action toward retaliation while trying to get
a settlement by negotiation.
   Another provision permits him to rule that a country denying
internationally recognized rights to labor can be considered as
engaging in an unfair trade practice, and to retaliate against its
trade.
   The GAO complained of defects in efforts to promote exports. It
said the Commerce Department has chosen questionable trade promotion
events and has been active in countries with little or no potential
for buying more U.S. goods. It did not specify the nations.
   It characterized as ``largely symbolic'' the controls put on
exports to further foreign policy objectives, as distinct from
controls that have security objectives.
   ``When these controls are symbolic, they do not prevent the
targeted country from getting the controlled products from other
countries,'' the report said.
   ``Instead their costs are borne by American businesses in the
form of export sales lost to firms in other countries.''
   The report did not specify either the countries targeted by the
U.S. controls or their suppliers. One nation to which exports are
controlled for foreign policy reasons is South Africa, where
Japanese and West European suppliers have replaced many exports that
can now no longer be shipped by Americans.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
