<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Transition-Defense     11-21 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Transition-Defense,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Urged To Name Only Experienced People to Top Defense Jobs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect George Bush should only appoint
civilians to the top Pentagon jobs if they have a substantial
background in national security issues, the leaders of the Senate
Armed Services Committee said Monday.
   ``Strong defense leadership will be needed during the next four
years,'' said Sens. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., and John Warner, R-Va. Nunn
chairs the committee and Warner is the ranking Republican.
   In a letter sent before the election to both Bush and Democratic
candidate Michael Dukakis, the two senators outlined what they said
should be some general qualification standards for top-level
civilian appointments to the Defense Department.
   The letter was released Monday. There was no reply from Bush, who
hasn't yet named any members of his national security team. Former
Sen. John Tower of Texas is considered to be a leading candidate to
become secretary of defense.
   Nunn and Warner said they didn't want to spell out specific
qualifications for each civilian appointment. The Armed Services
Committee will oversee top-level appointments requiring Senate
confirmation.
   The two senators said criteria should include integrity, a
commitment to public service and ability to get along with other
top-level Pentagon officials.
   In addition, there should be ``substantial experience and
expertise,'' they said, because ``there is no time for `on-the-job'
training in the Department of Defense.''
   Nominees also ``should have a substantial understanding of
national security policy and international security affairs,'' the
senators said.
</TEXT>
