<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0637,0703</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ethnic Albanians Defy Threats of Crackdown, Protest</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-6 UPDATE with bad weather conditions, second rally
in Slovenia. PICKS up 5th pvs, `The two ...' SUBS 11th pvs `Local
Communist Party ...' to CORRECT to Imsa, sted of Isma. Minor editing
to TRIM</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SLOBODAN LEKIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 7,000 ethnic Albanians
angered by the ouster of two leaders defied threats of a crackdown
and took to the streets in heavy rain Monday, extending a wave of
ethnic protest for a fifth straight day.
   The demonstrators marched about 40 miles to Pristina, capital of
the restive southern province of Kosovo.
   In the northern republic of Slovenia, about 13,000 people braved
a snowstorm Monday to press for more democracy. The two protests
were not related.
   The Slovenians called for a referendum on controversial
constitutional changes and for acquittal of four men sentenced to
jail for making public a classified military document. A rally in
Revolution Square in Ljubljana, the Slovenian capital, drew 10,000
people and another rally in Celje, 42 miles northeast of Ljubljana,
drew 3,000.
   Slovenian courts acted at the last minute Monday to postpone the
scheduled jailing of the three journalists and one army officer,
whose sentencing last summer led to protests and petitions in the
most liberal of Yugoslavia's six republics.
   Kosovo protesters were angered by the resignations Thursday of
Azem Vlasi and Kacusa Jasari, both ethnic Albanian members of the
province's 13-member ruling Politburo.
   The two stepped down under pressure from Serbian Communist Party
leader Slobodan Milosevic, who wants greater control over Kosovo for
its republic, Serbia. He has demanded changes in the 1974
constitution that gave Kosovo broad autonomy.
   Provincial party leaders have promised to review the resignations
of the two ethnic Albanians later this week.
   In a speech Monday in Belgrade, Milosevic reiterated his demand
for the constitutional changes he says are needed to protect
Kosovo's Serb minority from harassment by ethnic Albanians. He made
no reference to the weekend protests in Kosovo by up to 100,000
ethnic Albanians.
   At Monday's protest in a Pristina sports hall, a crowd of about
7,000, mostly workers who trudged 40 miles from the town of
Orohovac, dispersed after a Serbian factory worker defied Milosevic
and backed the ethnic Albanians.
   The worker, Ruzica Imsa, was cheered wildly as she spoke out
against the constitutional reforms pressed by many of her fellow
Serbs.
   ``The working class will not allow itself to be pushed around,''
she said. ``We will not let anyone impose constitutional changes the
people do not want.''
   Local Communist Party leaders were jeered and whistled when they
tried to get the crowd to return home. They then persuaded Imsa to
return to the microphone, and her calm appeal succeeded in
dispersing the crowd.
   Later, another crowd of about 2,000 people arrived from the town
of Klina, some 40 miles north of Pristina.
   Officials had warned of a crackdown if protesters took to the
streets. At an earlier gathering at Pristina University, acting
provincial party head Remzi Koljgeci told students ``unspecified
measures'' would go into force if more protests occurred.
   Under a package of constitutional amendments due to be passed by
each republic by next week, Milosevic wants to restore Serbian
control over Kosovo's judiciary, education and policing.
   The amendments are designed to simplify the complex federal
constitution and give the legal framework to introduce
market-oriented economic reform.
   Most of Milosevic's address dwelt on the need for economic change
and strongly attacked bureaucrats for opposing it.
   Communist leaders in Yugoslavia's other five republics see
Milosevic's campaign as a drive to increase the influence of Serbia,
the largest republic, on the Yugoslav federation.
   But Milosevic claims the changes would only put Serbia on an
equal footing with other republics, which have no administrative
provinces like Serbia's Kosovo and Vojvodina.
   In Slovenia, the proposed reforms have run into opposition from
intellectuals who fear greater central control of the republic's
relatively liberal judiciary.
   The rally in Ljubljana pressed demands for a referendum on the
reforms, which intellectuals believe would be strongly opposed in
Slovenia.
</TEXT>
