<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Brazil-Strike     11-21 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brazil-Strike,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Workers End Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of oil workers
returned to work Monday, ending a 10-day strike that caused
widespread shortages of cooking gas and heating oil.
   Unions meeting Sunday and Monday voted to accept a government
offer of wage increases, said Lucio Pimentel, spokesman for the
Petrobras state oil monopoly.
   The strike by more than 50,000 petroleum workers paralyzed the
nation's 11 refineries. In emergency bargaining during the weekend,
the government offered strikers a 15 percent cost-of-living raise
and a 4 percent raise tied to productivity.
   Oil workers earn about $300 a month, good pay by Brazilian
standards.
   Petrobras also agreed not to punish strikers and to deduct only
four days' pay from their checks.
   Strike leaders urged unions to accept the offer, although it fell
short of the 26.6 percent raise they demanded.
   The government had suspended the cost-of-living raise last year
when it decreed a 90-day price freeze. Officials said granting the
raise would create more inflation, now at an annual rate of more
than 1,000 percent.
   ``It was a great political victory, although economically it
didn't attain what we wanted,'' Mauro Costa of the national strike
command said in Brasilia.
   During the strike, the government was forced to import emergency
shipments of diesel fuel, cooking gas and kerosene when stocks
threatened to run out completely. Gas rationing was imposed in some
parts of the country.
   Brazil has suffered a recent wave of strikes caused by a
sputtering economy under President Jose Sarney. The strikers have
included national park employees, doctors and nurses at
government-run clinics, electricity workers, subway personnel,
steelworkers and federal employees in at least 17 of 26 ministries.
</TEXT>
