<HEAD>Reagan Attends Ground-Breaking for Library</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 7th graf pvs, bgng: ``The journey...'' to remove
reference to prepared remarks; SUBS 14th graf pvs, bgng: ``The
library...'' with 4 grafs to add details; picks up 15th graf pvs,
bgng: ``The building...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIMI VALLEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan on Monday helped
break ground for the library that will house his White House papers,
saying he hoped historians and scholars would ``judge our efforts
well.''
   ``This is a most humbling moment for me,'' said Reagan, who will
relinquish the presidency to George Bush in 60 days. ``The story
that will be told inside the walls that are yet to be built here is
the story not only of a presidency, but of a movement.''
   The president and his wife Nancy flew from Washington to Southern
California to take part in the ceremonies for the Ronald Reagan
Presidential Library. The 153,000-square-foot, Spanish-style
facility will be built on a 100-acre site about 45 miles northwest
of Los Angeles.
   The Reagans gave final approval to the site last summer, after
the president viewed the sweeping, hilly area from a helicopter
following a ground inspection by the first lady.
   The selection of the Simi Valley site, about 70 miles southeast
of the Reagans' ranch in Santa Barbara County, came after planners
of the Reagan library were thwarted in an attempt to build it at
Stanford University in Palo Alto, Calif.
   Appearing at the ceremony at the outset of a six-day Thanksgiving
vacation at his ranch in the Santa Ynez Mountains, Reagan talked
reflectively of his eight years as president.
   ``The journey has not been just my own,'' he said. ``It seems I
have been guided by a force much larger than myself, a force made up
of ideas and beliefs about what this country is and what it could
be.''
   Reagan takes credit for a resurgence of conservatism in America,
and much of the 1988 campaign rhetoric during the Republican primary
season was about what man could best carry on the ``Reagan
revolution.''
   This sea-change was based on a fiscal policy at home aimed at
stimulating economic growth through tax cuts and deregulation of
business, and a resurgence of U.S. international influence brought
about principally by a major military buildup, projections of
American power in the Third World and warming, if unsteady,
relations with the Soviet Union.
   ``What this library will house is the record of ideas and
policies that have undergirded our accomplishments,'' Reagan said.
``There will be much to study here, much to discuss, much to mull
over.''
   ``This library will allow scholars of the future to cast their
own judgments on these years, and I would not presume to predict the
result of their researches,'' he said. ``But I have to believe that
scholars of good will, upon examining the historical record that
will be contained herein, will judge our efforts well.''
   ``But as for us, at present we can only say this: We have done
our best and we pray that it has been enough.''
   The land for the library was donated by a Los Angeles development
company, Blakeley-Schwartz. The selection sparked opposition by
environmentalists initially because the site impinged on a greenbelt
area protected from large-scale development by a decade-old,
non-binding agreement among Simi Valley, Moorpark and Thousand Oaks.
   The $45 million library will be constructed with donations to the
private Ronald Reagan library foundation. It will sit in an area of
rolling hills covered with brush, beavertail cactus and wildflowers.
   Former Attorney General William French Smith told the audience
that over 100,000 people have contributed toward the library's cost,
but he did not say how much of the money has been raised.
   Arrayed on the platform next to the Reagans were several members
of the board of trustees of the presidential library foundation,
including former Attorney General Edwin Meese, former National
Security Adviser and Interior Secretary William Clark, former
domestic policy adviser Martin Anderson, and Energy Secretary John
Herrington.
   After his brief speech, Reagan walked about 30 feet up a knoll,
and he and his wife, each wielding stainless steel shovels that
glistened in the bright sun, turned the first shovelsful of dirt as
more than 250 people applauded.
   The building will include underground storage, a museum and
research materials depicting the administration and historical
events during the Reagan years.
   As the curtain draws on the Reagan presidency, the first couple
seems prepared for the transition back to private life. they will
move into a luxurious home in the Bel Air section of Los Angeles in
January _ an estate that they will lease from friends who acquired
the property in their behalf.
   Reagan has said he plans to lecture often ``on the mashed potato
circuit'' and Mrs. Reagan has said she will remain active in the
campaign against drug abuse.
   While in California this week, aides said, the president will act
on various pieces of legislation passed by Congress in its waning
days last month.
   Following their usual pattern, the Reagans also will go horseback
riding, and the president will attend to ranch chores. After their
return to Washington on Sunday, they will have a busy schedule of
parties and other social commitments in their final weeks in the
capital.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
