<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Haiti-Strike     11-21 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti-Strike,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Workers Strike Against Avril Government</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Buses halted, some stores were
closed and school attendance dropped Monday because of a general
strike to protest policies of the military government.
   Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril's government said it ``noted with
satisfaction'' business activity picked up Monday afternoon ``in
spite of the multiple appeals which aimed at the paralysis of
national life by an illegal strike.''
   About one-third of the stores in downtown Port-au-Prince were
closed and most others opened late. Fewer street vendors than usual
were working, traffic was down and schools were poorly attended.
Police were stationed on street corners and soldiers guarded gas
stations, but no violence was reported.
   Radio reports said activity also slowed in many other cities and
towns.
   Haiti's largest labor federation, the Automomous Union of Haitian
Workers, said the strike was a warning to the government against any
attempt to re-establish a dictatorship.
   The two other major labor federations did not take part and only
one major political parties openly supported the strike.
   Avril assumed the presidency in a coup on Sept. 17 in which
noncommissioned officers ousted Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy, sending him
into exile in the neighboring Dominican Republic.
   Avril pledged to restore Haiti's constitution and hold
presidential elections.
</TEXT>
