<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon 2ndLd-Writethru a0666 11-21 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0666,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Say 4 Hezbollah Leaders Escape Car Bombing; Sidon Shooutout</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-5 UPDATE with shootout in Sidon, inserts time
element in lead. PICKS up 5th pvs, The convoy ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BAALBEK, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car bomb exploded Monday near a
motorcade in which four senior leaders of the pro-Iranian Hezbollah
group were riding in east Lebanon's Bekaa Valley, but the
assassination attempt failed, police said.
   Two bodyguards and a pedestrian were slightly wounded, they said.
   No group claimed responsibility.
   Police also said two militiamen were killed and five wounded at
nightfall in a shootout involving rival Sunni Moslem factions in
south Lebanon's southern port of Sidon, but gave no details.
   Police and Hezbollah _ or Party of God _ said a remote-controlled
van packed with 330 pounds of TNT blew up about 450 feet from the
10-car motorcade carrying Sheik Subhi Tufaili, Abbas Mousawi, Hassan
Nasralla and the party's chief spokesman, Sheik Ibrahim Amin.
   The convoy was rolling through Sifri village on the road linking
the northeastern towns of Baalbek and Riyak in the Syrian-policed
valley when the roadside car bomb went off.
   A Hezbollah statement said the three leaders and their companions
were returning to Baalbek, the party's stronghold in the valley,
from a rally in Riyak.
   But police said the convoy only made a brief stop in Riyak. They
said the four leaders were returning via Damascus, the Syrian
capital, from a visit to Iran.
   The Hezbollah statement did not speculate on who set the bomb.
   But it said: ``This is a criminal attempt on the lives of the
three leaders. We possess enough clues that will enable us soon to
uncover the culprits and their masterminds.''
   The Hezbollah has been locked in a struggle with the
Syrian-backed Shiite Amal militia for dominance of the 1 million
Shiites who make up Lebanon's largest single sect.
   Amal's chieftain Nabih Berri last month accused Hezbollah of
engineering the assassination of Amal's top three leaders in south
Lebanon.
</TEXT>
