<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-88 1856EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Onassis-FinalDays     11-21 0711</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Onassis-Final Days,0733</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Relatives, Friends Say Heiress Was Happy In Her Final Days</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Onassis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM H. HEATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christina Onassis was happy and enthusiastic
in the days before she died suddenly. She planned to buy an
apartment and may even have found romance, friends, relatives and
news reports said Monday.
   Ms. Onassis, 37, who died Saturday of what an autopsy report
described as acute pulmonary edema, was a frequent visitor to the
Argentine capital. She was in the city for four days in late October
and returned again on Nov. 9.
   Her visits were motivated by her close friendship with Marina and
Alberto Dodero, members of a wealthy Argentine family that had long
been associated with Ms. Onassis' late father, shipping tycoon
Aristotle Onassis.
   That friendship may have extended to a romantic interest in Mrs.
Dodero's brother, Jorge Tchomlekdjoglou, 43, Buenos Aires newspapers
suggested Monday.
   Ms. Onassis had rented a suite at the luxurious Alvear Palace
Hotel, in the heart of La Recoleta, one of city's most exclusive
areas, filled with expensive restaurants, night spots and boutiques.
   Nevertheless, the heiress wanted to spend ``all the time she
could'' at the Tortuguitas Country Club, where the Doderos have a
weekend home, said Mercedes Zavalia, public relations director for
the hotel.
   ``She had even bought some running shoes to be able to run
there,'' Miss Zavalia told the Buenos Aires newspaper La Razon.
   Miss Zavalia said she often chatted with Ms. Onassis, ``who
insisted on being treated like just another guest.'' She described
the heiress as ``a person who made decisions on the spur of the
moment.''
   ``The other day, for example, she decided to leave the country,
but she must have changed her mind at least five times in the course
of the day,'' Miss Zavalia said.
   Tortuguitas Country Club, 25 miles northwest of the city, is
comprised of about 350 weekend homes owned by wealthy Argentines
   Annabella Onassis, a cousin, recalled that Ms. Onassis attended a
party at the club the night before her death and ``appeared to be
feeling very well.''
   The cousin told reporters that on the day of her death Ms.
Onassis and Mrs. Dodero planned to go swimming in a pool and went to
change shortly before 11 a.m.
   Ms. Onassis took overly long in emerging from the bathroom where
she was changing. Her friend went to look for her ``and found her
lying on the bathroom floor,'' the cousin told reporters.
   A conflicting version was published Monday by the Buenos Aires
newspaper Clarin, which cited Dodero family attorney Juan Carlos
MacDonald as saying the heiress died in her sleep at the Dodero home.
   Family members discounted the possibility that Ms. Onassis could
have committed suicide.
   ``A happy person could never commit suicide and Christina was
content and very happy,'' Mary Onassis, an aunt, told reporters.
``She had no (apparent) health problems.''
   Mary Onassis told reporters that her niece planned to attend a
party Saturday night given by members of Buenos Aires' Greek
community.
   ``Christina was in the best part of her life,'' Mary Onassis said.
   Ms. Onassis also had made plans to attend a Sunday night birthday
party for Greek Orthodox Archbishop Ganadius Chrysolakis, who
presided over her funeral Mass on Sunday morning.
   The archbishop told reporters he spoke to Ms. Onassis only last
Wednesday.
   ``We chatted for a long while and shared a meal,'' Chrysolakis
told the official news agency Telam. ``She told me she was very
happy that a series of family problems she was going through had
been resolved. She was enthusiastic. She was very happy.''
   Tamara Revitis, the archbishop's secretary, told Radio Rivadavia
of Buenos Aires that Ms. Onassis had ``appeared very enthusiastic''
and ``had been making plans to buy an apartment in Buenos Aires''
with the apparent intention of moving to the city. She maintained
homes in Paris and St. Moritz, Switzerland.
   The motive for her decision to buy a home, several Buenos Aires
newspapers suggested, was Ms. Onassis apparently had a romantic
interest in Jorge Tchomlekdjoglou.
   The Doderos and Ms. Onassis' relatives were not immediately
available to comment on published reports that a marriage was in the
offing.
   Ms. Onassis was married and divorced four times and had a
3-year-old daughter.
</TEXT>
