<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ElvisClaim     11-21 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Elvis Claim,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Would-Be Elvis Daughter Loses Claim</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WOODY BAIRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge on Monday dismissed an inheritance
claim by a woman who says her mother had a four-day love affair with
Elvis Presley and that she is his daughter.
   Aspiring singer Deborah Delaine Presley had filed the inheritance
petition in Shelby County Probate Court, which oversees Presley's
will. Judge Joseph Evans ruled there was insufficient evidence to
warrant further review of the claim.
   Miss Presley's request included an affidavit from her mother,
Barbara Jean Young, who said she spent four days with Presley in
1955 at a mobile home near Jackson, Miss.
   ``The only things that stopped us from staying in each others
arms was the need to eat lunch and dinner,'' the affidavit said. It
said Miss Presley was born nine months later.
   Miss Presley's last name was Yandell, until she had it changed.
   When Presley died of heart disease in 1977, his estate was valued
at $5 million to $7 million. Managers of the Presley trust opened
the singer's former Memphis residence to tourists in 1982, and now
the estate is estimated at $50 million. The estate also draws
royalties from Presley's recordings and controls the use of his name
and image.
   A trust monitored by the Probate Court manages the Presley estate
for Lisa Marie Presley, 20, the singer's only legal child, and she
takes it over at age 25.
</TEXT>
