<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Cuomo-Plane     11-21 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cuomo-Plane,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Problems for Cuomo's Airplane</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL STASHENKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The aging state airplane that had to make an
emergency landing with Gov. Mario Cuomo aboard ran into problems
again Monday when pilots decided not to take it up because they
didn't like the way it was handling.
   Department of Environmental Conservation pilots had been planning
to fly the Grumman Gulfstream G1 from an airport near
Mountoursville, Pa., where it made the emergency landing Sunday, to
an aviation company in Wilmington, Del., said department spokesman
R.W. Groneman.
   When the turboprop taxied onto the runway for takeoff, the pilots
decided to return it to the hangar.
   ``They didn't feel comfortable taking it up,'' said Groneman, who
couldn't say what the pilots didn't like about the way the plane was
functioning.
   The plane, the largest in the state's fleet, had been set to fly
to Atlantic Aviation's maintenance center, where the 22-year-old
aircraft underwent a $628,000 overhaul in 1987.
   Earlier Monday, the craft had been inspected by two officials
from the Federal Aviation Administration, said FAA spokeswoman
Kathleen Bergin in Queens. She said she didn't know whether the
federal inspectors had determined why the plane malfunctioned.
   Cuomo, speaking to reporters Monday, tried to play down the
seriousness of Sunday's mishap and said regardless of the plane's
fate, the state cannot afford a replacement. It would cost $12
million to $13 million to buy an airplane of comparable size to the
17-passenger G1.
   ``How could we (buy a new plane), with all of the problems we
have?'' said the governor, whose state is facing a deficit estimated
at nearly $2 billion.
   ``You should ground the governor before you spend $13 million on
a new plane,'' he said.
   When the plane had problems previously, Cuomo said he would use
smaller planes to travel within the state and take commercial
flights on longer trips if it couldn't be repaired.
   Cuomo insisted that the plane remains basically sound, despite
having to make three emergency landings in the past 16 months, twice
with the governor on board.
   ``It's not a dramatic threat to anybody,'' he said. ``If it were,
we wouldn't be on the plane. And if they tell me it's a dramatic
threat, then I won't be on the plane.''
</TEXT>
