<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Baltics 1stLd-Writethru a0729 11-21 0594</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Baltics, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0729,0608</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Recommend Concession to Independent-Minded Republics</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 6th `The Supreme Soviet' UPDATING with
action by Russian Federation. Picks up 7th `As proposed ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A panel considering President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's plans for change recommends curtailing the power of a
new national council in response to accusations that the Kremlin
concentrates too much power in Moscow.
   Pravda, the Communist Party daily, said Monday the commission of
the Supreme Soviet recommended dropping language that gives the new
Council of People's Deputies the power to reject laws adopted by
legislatures of the 15 Soviet republics.
   The commission is reviewing constitutional amendments to be
considered by the national parliament next week.
   Proposed amendments designed to reorganize the governing
apparatus hve generated considerable opposition, particularly in the
independence-minded Baltic republics but also in letters published
by the Soviet press.
   In one manifestation of recent demands for more authonomy,
thousands of Lithuanians chanting ``For shame!'' jammed the center
of Vilnius, capital of Lithuania, on Monday to protest their
legislature's refusal to declare the republic's autonomy from
Moscow, residents said.
   The Supreme Soviet commission, in a Saturday meeting that was the
subject of Pravda's report Monday, also suggested changing language
that authorizes new council to decide the composition of the Soviet
Union, its constituent republics and autonomus regions.
   A dispatch from Tass, the official news agency, said the
Presidium of the Supreme Soviet of the Russian Federation, the
largest republic, denounced the Estonian action as a contradiction
of ``the basic principles of socialist federalism.''
   As proposed by the Kremlin leadership, the amendment empowers the
Council of People's Deputies to ``take decisions relative to the
composition of the U.S.S.R., the approval of the formation of new
autonomous republics and autonomous regions in the composition of
the union republics.''
   According to Pravda, the commission suggested limiting the
council to matters ``on the questions of national-state structure
relative to the jurisdiction of the U.S.S.R.''
   It said changes recommended by the commission were part of an
effort to increase ``the development of the sovereign rights of the
republics.''
   Just how far those ``sovereign rights'' go is a subject of
dispute between Estonia, one of the three Baltic republics, and
central authorities in Moscow.
   Last week, the Estonian legislature adopted a declaration of
sovereignty giving the republic veto power over Soviet laws and
proclaiming once-independent Estonia's power in all matters except
defense and foreign policy
   Although the Supreme Soviet commission sought to limit the power
of the new council, it also condemned the Estonian legislature's
action on grounds that giving laws of a republic authority over
national statutes violates the 1977 Soviet Constitution.
   The Presidium, the Supreme Soviet executive body, has said it
will review Estonia's action and has summoned Estonian leaders to
Moscow to explain.
   Gorbachev's initial personal reaction to developments in the
Baltics was mild. He said during a visits to India such actions were
an exercise of ``perestroika,'' his program to reform the political
and economic system.
   Constitutional amendments proposed by Gorbachev have caused a
furor in Lithuania and Estonia and, and to a lesser degree in
Latvia, because they are seen as limiting the powers of the
republics as the Baltics seek greater control over their own affairs.
   They are part of his political restructuring, which includes
creation of a more powerful presidency and a full-time national
legislature.
   In Vilnius on Monday, the Lithuanian Movement for Perestroika
called a 10-minute protest at noon that a spokeswoman said halted
traffic in the downtown area.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
