<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-ANC     11-21 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-ANC,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ANC Officials, Swazi Citizen, Convicted of Treason, Terrorism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two African National Congress
members were convicted of treason Monday in connection with two mine
explosions, and a Swazi co-defendant was found guilty of terrorism.
   Ebrahim Ismail Ebrahim, a senior member of the outlawed ANC and a
founding member of its military wing, was abducted from Swaziland in
December 1986 and held in solitary confinement until May 1987, when
he was charged with treason.
   He and ANC member Simon Dladla were found guilty Monday in
Pretoria Supreme Court in connection with mine explosions last year
in the Transvaal towns of Volksrust and Breyten.
   The trial had been controversial because of Ebrahim's abduction
from Swaziland by men he identified as South African police. The
defense argued in a separate hearing that South African courts had
no jurisdiction to try Ebrahim.
   Adriaan Vlok, the law and order minister, would not comment on
whether Ebrahim had been abducted but said no South African
policemen were involved if he was kidnapped.
   Although the explosions occurred after Ebrahim was in custody,
the state contended that he was responsible because it said he
coordinated and planned ANC military operations from Swaziland.
   Ebrahim left South Africa in 1979 after completing a 15-year
prison term for various acts of sabotage.
   The judge said co-defendant Anton Mandla Maseko could not be
found guilty of treason because as a Swazi citizen he did not owe
allegiance to South Africa. He was convicted of terrorism.
   The three men are to be sentenced later.
</TEXT>
