<HEAD>Unsafe Methanol Level Found in Portuguese Brandy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS to CORRECT spelling of `Portuguese` in 1st graf; picks
up 2nd graf, pvs, bgng: ``The U.S...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal officials said Monday unsafe levels of
methanol had been found in two brands of Portuguese brandy.
   The U.S. Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms said people
should not drink Aveleda Bagaceira Marc Brandy or Aveleda Aguardente
Reserva but should return the bottle to the retailer.
   The maximum safe level of methanol in brandy is .35 percent by
volume, the federal bureau said. Laboratory testing of the two
brandies found methanol levels from .412 to .660 percent by volume,
the bureau said in a statement.
   The U.S. Food and Drug Administration has said that such levels
of methanol in brandy pose a potential health threat, depending on
how much is consumed.
