<2ND_LINE>AM-PLO, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0741,0725</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mubarak Cautions Israel After Egypt Recognizes Palestinian State</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-14 UPDATE with Mubarak's cautioning Israel.
Changes byline. Picks up 7th graf pvs, ``I am ... with minor editing
to trim and DELETING final two grafs, 17-18, as superseded</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SAMI RIZKALLAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Hosni Mubarak appeared with PLO
leader Yasser Arafat at a joint news conference on Monday and
advised Israel to be careful in its reaction to Egypt's recognition
of the newly proclaimed Palestinian state.
   Mubarak's remark came the day after Egyptian recognition and he
entertained the Palestine Liberation Organization chairman at a
state dinner and a three-hour session of separate and enlarged talks.
   ``Israel should be precise in its statements and should know that
we also want peace,'' Mubarak said.
   ``All the people in the region, including the Israeli people,
want peace.''
   The news conference was carried by the state-owned Middle East
News Agency.
   Mubarak was apparently responding to reported Israeli threats to
delay an Israeli withdrawal from disputed Taba Beach. Israel refused
to return Taba to Egypt when Israel withdrew from Sinai in 1982, but
an international arbitration team ruled two months ago that the area
belonged to Egypt.
   An Israeli government official said in Jerusalem Monday that
Israel's 10-member Inner Cabinet will discuss Egypt's move at a
session Wednesday and will debate such a possibility.
   Mubarak was also referring to Israeli accusations that Egypt
violated the U.S-brokered 1978 Camp David peace accords, which
produced the first peace treaty between Israel and Egypt but failed
to grant any sort of autonomy to the 1.5 million Palestinians in the
Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Arafat flew into Cairo from Baghdad, Iraq, on Monday and said he
and Mubarak will discuss a common approach to a Mideast peace
conference.
   In Jerusalem, Israeli Foreign Minister Shimon Peres on Monday
summoned Egyptian Ambassador Mohammed Bassiouny and expressed
Israel's regret over Cairo's recognition of the Palestinian state, a
ministry official said.
   The official said Peres told Bassiouny the move violated
Israeli-Egyptian treaties that call for the final status of the West
Bank and Gaza Strip to be negotiated in peace talks. Bassiouny told
Peres that recognition did not violate Egypt's agreements with
Israel, he reported.
   Wearing his usual military fatigues and black checked scarf,
Arafat spoke briefly to reporters at the airport before leaving with
Foreign Minister Esmat Abdel-Meguid in a Mercedes Benz flying the
Egyptian and Palestinian flags.
   It was the first time in Cairo that the PLO flag flew on an
official car, an honor normally reserved for heads of state and
ambassadors.
   However, there were no red carpets, military bands or other
trappings of a head of state's arrival.
   ``I am really happy to be here, especially after the declaration
(of a Palestinian state) by the Palestine National Council (the
PLO's parliament),'' Arafat said.
   ``I can brief my brothers, headed by President Hosni Mubarak, on
the details of the PNC and draw a common visualization of effective
steps for the promotion of an international Middle East peace
conference.''
   Since the Palestinian state was declared Nov. 15 in Algiers,
Arafat has flown to Morocco, Mauritania, back to Algeria and to Iraq
to drum up support for future peace moves.
   The Palestinian council declaration did not define the boundaries
of its new state, but implied it meant the West Bank and Gaza Strip,
which Israel captured from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Middle East
war. The declaration said Jerusalem would be the capital of the
Palestinian state.
   Palestinian sources in Baghdad said Monday that Arafat urged Arab
ambassadors there to press the United States to grant him a visa so
he can address the U.N. General Assembly.
   The Israeli official in Jerusalem said Egypt's Bassiouny told
Peres at their 40-minute meeting that Egypt viewed the PLO's
conditional acceptance of U.N. Security Council Resolution 242 as a
recognition of Israel.
   The resolution, adopted after the 1967 war, calls on Israel to
withdraw from captured territory, but also asserts the right of all
countries in the region to live in secure borders.
   Egypt is the third country which has diplomatic relations with
Israel to recognize the declared Palestinian state. The others are
Turkey and Cyprus.
</TEXT>
