<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Azores-Earthquake 1stLd-Writethru a0724 11-21 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Azores-Earthquake, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0724,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quake Rattles Azores</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3d graf `Portugese government' to CORRECT spelling of
Portuguese</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PONTE DELGADA, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An earthquake rocked the Azores
archipelago in the mid-Atlantic on Monday, damaging some buildings
on the largest island, officials said. No injuries were reported.
   The earthquake measured 5.8 on the Richter scale, meaning a quake
capable of causing considerable to severe damage, said Pat Jorgensen
of the U.S. Geologic Survey in Menlo Park, Calif.
   Portuguese government officials said the quake shook the islands
of Sao Miguel, Santa Maria and Terceira at 11:55 a.m. EST.
   Ms. Jorgensen said the quake struck at 3:56 p.m. local time
(11:56 a.m. EST) and was centered about 50 miles north of Sao
Miguel. She said there were reports of minor damage and the temblor
was felt over a wide area.
   Buildings were damaged in northern Sao Miguel, largest of the
Portuguese chain's nine islands, but there were no reports of
injuries, the Portuguese news agency Lusa reported.
   It said many people on the island panicked and roofs, stone walls
and chimneys were damaged.
   Tremors also were felt on Santa Maria and Terceira, where the
United States has an air base. The Azores are near the North
Atlantic Ridge, a seismically active line stretching north and south
in the Atlantic Ocean, where two plates of Earth's crust are pulling
apart.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an
earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a
seismograph. A quake of magnitude 4 can cause moderate damage, one
measuring 5 can cause considerable damage and a quake of magnitude 6
can cause severe damage.
   A earthquake that hit the Azores Jan. 1, 1980, killed at least 49
people and injured more than 300 on Sao Jorge and Terceira.
</TEXT>
