<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Europe-Weather     11-21 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Europe-Weather,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Winter Storms Frustrate Military, Motorists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Winter storms stranded thousands of
motorists on icy highways Monday and forced postponement of an
important military ceremony because a French general could not get
there.
   Ice-and-snow storms whipped across many sections of West Germany,
bringing rush-hour traffic to a halt on the high-speed autobahns and
wreaking havoc with air traffic. Traffic snarls as long as 15 miles
were reported on some highways, along with hundreds of minor
accidents.
   In Switzerland, the first big snow of the season closed Alpine
mountain passes, clogged roads and delayed air travel.
   Red Cross workers took hot tea to motorists caught in traffic
jams in southern West Germany. Dozens of vehicles ran out of gas
while waiting to move.
   A collision involving 15 trucks and a passenger car backed up
traffic on an autobahn near Ulm. Police said one person was injured
in the collision.
   Gen. Gilbert Forray, the French army chief of staff, was
scheduled to meet his West German counterpart, Gen. Henning von
Ondarza, in the southern town of Boeblingen for an official ceremony
marking formation of a joint French-German brigade.
   Forray's plane could not land at Stuttgart because of bad weather
and the ceremony was postponed, with a new date not specified,
German officers at Boeblingen said. Officials said 49 flights were
canceled at Stuttgart.
   West Germany and France agreed last year to create a joint army
brigade.
   ZDF television said schools in Saarland schools closed because of
slippery roads.
   More than 4 inches of new snow was reported in parts of southern
West Germany.
   Snow blanketed eastern Switzerland and the western Jura hills.
Zurich reported 6 to 8 inches and St. Gall 10 inches.
   San Bernardino and Fluela passes were closed temporarily and the
St. Gotthard pass was shut for the winter, the Swiss Touring Club
said. Seven other passes were closed earlier this month.
   Snow blocked runways and hampered visibility at Zurich's
international airport, delaying flights up to three hours, an
airport spokesman said. Police reported many highways blocked by
auto accidents.
</TEXT>
