<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Homelands     11-21 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Homelands,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Botha Meets Leaders Of Impoverished Homelands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President P.W. Botha met Monday
with the leaders of the country's four nominally independent black
homelands and declared the group part of a unified ``economic
community of southern Africa.''
   In a statement later, Botha said he discussed economic matters,
political reform and foreign relations with the leaders of Transkei,
Ciskei, Venda and Bophuthatswana.
   ``We are a community which places emphasis on economic
cooperation and development,'' the statement said.
   The statement did not announce any agreements, but said the group
had decided to refer to itself in the future as the ``economic
community of southern Africa.''
   The homelands, which are not recognized by any foreign countries,
are heavily dependent on South African aid to support their meager
economies.
   In addition to economic difficulties, political turmoil and
frequent reports of widespread corruption have plagued several of
the homelands.
   In Transkei, lengthy hearings have been held into corruption
allegations against George and Kaiser Matanzima, brothers who ruled
the homeland from 1976 until 1987, when George Matanzima, then prime
minister, was ousted in a coup.
   The homeland now is ruled by a 33-year-old army commander, Bantu
Holomisa. He recently said it might be possible for Transkei to
rejoin South Africa if apartheid _ South Africa's racial segregation
system _ were abolished.
   Lennox Sebe, president of Ciskei, has often tilted with
Transkei's rulers. Both neighboring homelands, separated by a strip
of South African territory, are Xhosa tribal areas and Ciskei
accuses Transkei of plotting to take it over. Several of Sebe's
relatives, whom he had imprisoned for plotting against him, escaped
with the help of a band of armed white men believed to be South
Africans, and fled to Transkei in 1987.
   In Bophuthatswana, an attempted coup by dissident soldiers in
February was put down when South African troops rescued President
Lucas Mangope, who had been seized by the rebels.
   In Venda, thousands of students have boycotted classes to protest
alleged cover-up of ritual murders. Police acknowleged that ritual
murders took place and said they were investigating. No official
account of the motives for the murders has been advanced.
   In addition to the four nominally independent homelands, six
``self-governing'' territories exist, which also rely heavily on
South Africa for economic help.
</TEXT>
