<2ND_LINE>AM-Keith, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0717,0469</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tropical Storm Keith Hovers In Gulf, Could Strike Florida</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS grafs 4-5, `At 5' to UPDATE with 8 p.m. EST position,
direction, movement. Picks up 6th graf pvs, `But Sheets....'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TRACY FIELDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tropical storm Keith, just short of becoming the
year's sixth hurricane, soaked the Yucatan Peninsula on Monday and
moved into the Gulf of Mexico on a course expected to veer toward
Florida, forecasters said.
   ``It's a strong tropical storm on the borderline of a
hurricane,'' said Bob Sheets, director of the National Hurricane
Center.
   Keith's top sustained winds were hovering at about 65 mph, Sheets
said; 74 mph is the threshold for a storm to be upgraded to a
hurricane.
   At 8 p.m. EST, the storm was centered near latitude 23.1 north
and longitude 87.0 west, about 400 miles southwest of Fort Myers,
Fla. Forecasters said Keith was moving north at less than 10 mph and
was expected to turn east in the next 12 to 24 hours.
   ``It's moving toward the north, out in the south-central Gulf,''
said Sheets. ``The highest probability (of landfall) is the middle
of Florida's west coast'' late in the week.
   But Sheets emphasized that Keith is unlikely to become a storm on
the order of Gilbert or Joan, which devastated wide areas of the
Caribbean and Central America in September and October.
   ``I think it'll be just barely a hurricane,'' he said.
   On Monday, the storm's rains soaked an area from Mexico across
western Cuba to the Florida Keys, but spared the Yucatan Peninsula
city of Cancun from major damage, according to Alejandro Alvarado,
general manager of the Sheraton Hotel there.
   ``I just went around and you can see two or three things down on
the main street,'' he said. ``There's lots of water, lots of
puddles.''
   Alvarado said two or three light poles, apparently ones that were
being installed to replace those knocked down during Gilbert and
weren't yet firmly in place, had blown over. A few new palms fell as
well. He said hotels wee not be evacuated.
   The resort town is still recovering from Gilbert, which caused
extensive damage in September.
   While still a tropical depression, Keith passed south of Jamaica
late Friday and early Saturday, pouring almost 4 inches of rain on
Kingston in 24 hours. It also dumped rain on Honduras before heading
north into the Gulf.
   Tropical depressions are upgraded to tropical storms when their
top sustained winds reach 39 mph. Keith reached that status Sunday.
   Keith is the 11th named storm of the 1988 Atlantic hurricane
season, which runs from May 1 to Nov. 30. Five of the storms reached
hurricane strength, but only Gilbert and Joan did major damage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
