<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Canada-Mulroney     11-21 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Mulroney,0564</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Brian the Builder' Back for Another Term</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BAIE1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For someone with a reputation as a conciliator,
Prime Minister Brian Mulroney certainly loves a good fight.
   He likes to portray himself as a statesman and Canada's most
competent leader, but he thrives on old-fashioned politicking.
   Mulroney appeared headed for another term in Monday's election,
the first time since 1953 that a Canadian leader was able to put
together consecutive majority governments.
   It was a slimmer margin this time than in 1984, when he led his
Progressive Conservative Party to one of the most impressive
landslides in Canadian history.
   The 49-year-old prime minister comes from a working class family
in Baie-Comeau, on the north shore of Quebec's St. Lawrence. He was
ambitious and built a successful legal and corporate career in
Montreal.
   He first tried for the Conservative Party leadership in 1976 but
was not successful until 1983. He also was first elected to the
House of Commons that year.
   Mulroney is the first bilingual native of Quebec to lead his
party, and he has used that fact skillfully in expanding the
Conservatives' base in that critical, largely French-speaking
province.
   Support for cronies was charged during his first years in office,
dropping his popularity drastically in the public opinion polls.
   Eight Cabinet ministers resigned in separate incidents, but by
the time he called the election Oct. 1 Mulroney had distanced
himself from the controversies and was able to point to an
experienced management team.
   He planned to stage the campaign on competency and the prosperity
that lasted through his term to create 1.3 million jobs in Canada.
   That all changed midway through the race when the free trade
agreement with the United States took off as the No. 1 issue,
turning the campaign into an emotional tide that for a time appeared
to be sinking Mulroney.
   He emerged from the protective cover of statesman to stage a
hard, direct fight.
   By the campaign's closing days, Mulroney was exuberantly telling
crowds at his rallies that they had a choice between opposition
Liberal Party ``John (Turner) the Ripper or Brian the Builder.''
   He described the opponents of the trade agreement he signed last
January with President Reagan as jittery, negative defenders of past
traditions that could not survive in the modern world.
   Mulroney, by contrast, saw himself as a ``nation builder,'' ready
to lead a competent Canada into full competition with the much
larger and more powerful United States.
   The phrase surfaced in the last of six hours of debate last
month, when Turner accused the prime minister of selling out Canada
with the free trade agreement.
   Mulroney replied that he carried through on the agreement to
build Canada, ust as his father had gone to northeastern Quebec 55
years ago where he and hundreds of other laborers built a small town.
   ``I believe that in my own modest way, I am nation building
because I believe this benefits Canada, and I love Canada,'' the
prime minister said.
   Although Turner was widely believed to be the winner of the
debate, the momentum did not carry through to the end of the
campaign.
   The prime minister is a Roman Catholic. He is married and has
four children.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881121-0193 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-88 2128EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HollywoodFashion     11-21 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hollywood Fashion,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Designers Bemoan Lack Of Fashion Consciousness Among Stars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RADNOR, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Today's Hollywood stars either don't know how
to dress or don't care what the public thinks about them, top
industry fashion designers say.
   Asked to name six Hollywood women with class and taste,
``Dynasty'' designer Nolan Miller could come up with two: Diahann
Carroll and Linda Evans.
   ``All you have to do is catch a plane to see how far fashion has
gone downhill,'' he said in the Nov. 26 issue of TV Guide magazine,
published here. ``You see actresses in jogging suits _ I can't
imagine someone working in their garden this way, let alone going on
a trip. They owe it to the public, I feel.''
   But some of those sweat pants are made of silk and cashmere, and
``Wheel of Fortune'' co-host Vanna White said fans prefer the casual
look.
   ``They think I'm a real person,'' she said. ``I mean, I wear nice
sweats. I'm presentable. And I think it's great because stars are
humans, just like everybody else.''
   Herbert Fink counts Corbin Bernsen, Harry Hamlin, Michael Landon,
Farrah Fawcett and Jaclyn Smith among the clientele at his four
shops on opulent Rodeo Drive in Beverly Hills.
   While some of his customers spend $40,000 to $60,000 yearly on
clothes, not everyone knows how to spend the money well, he said.
   ``Stars today are sort of a strange breed,'' he said. ``Some of
them reach stardom very quickly. Quite often they're from small,
unsophisticated areas, so they really have no idea of how to dress.
They wear the wrong colors, the wrong styles. They have all this
money and they almost don't know how to spend it.''
   Robert Turturice, Emmy-winning costume designer for
``Moonlighting,'' says Cybill Shepherd entrusts him either to design
or shop for all the clothes she wears privately.
   ``She knows the time when it's important to look a certain way
and she knows the times when it's OK to be relaxed,'' he said.
   For glamour, however, Turturice turns to Miss Shepherd's co-star,
Bruce Willis, who loves tuxedos.
   ``I think I've made eight or 10 of them so far for him,''
including one in black suede, he said.
</TEXT>
