<HEAD>Two Killed in Explosion at China's Great Wall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two lovers married to other people died in an
explosion on China's famous Great Wall, apparently in a suicide
pact. The blast injured a New Zealand tourist, the official Xinhua
News Agency said Tuesday.
   Police said a 33-year-old man and a 29-year-old woman detonated a
homemade explosive Monday, Xinhua said. The pair, both from Jilin
province in northeast China and both married to other people, were
seen hugging just before the 11:40 a.m. blast.
   A New Zealand woman, traveling with her sister in a tour group,
received head and possible eye injuries and underwent surgery late
Monday, the New Zealand Embassy said.
   An embassy official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said her
injuries were ``potentially serious.'' Her name was withheld pending
notification of relatives.
   The woman and her sister had joined a tour group visiting China's
famed landmark at Badaling, a restored section of the wall about 40
miles northwest of Beijing. Other members of the group escaped
injury.
