<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-88 2213EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FuelSpill     11-21 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fuel Spill,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Officials Resign, One Suspended in Fuel Spill Aftermath</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two fire inspectors resigned and a third was
suspended over ``shoddy'' handling of documents concerning an
Ashland Oil Inc. diesel fuel spill in January, a police official
said Monday.
   Allegheny County police Superintendent Robert Kroner said the
county fire marshal's office failed to properly review Ashland's
plans to reassemble a storage tank that collapsed Jan. 2 in nearby
Jefferson and spilled about 750,000 gallons of fuel into the
Monongahela River.
   Kroner said detectives also found that secret internal documents
concerning the tank were released to outsiders he would not name.
   Fire Marshal Martin Jacobs, 38, and Chief Inspector Charles
Kelly, 58, resigned after meeting with Kroner on Friday, Kroner said.
   Deputy Fire Marshal Edward Babyak, 52, refused Kroner's offer to
resign and has been suspended pending action by the Allegheny County
commissioners, Kroner said.
   ``Our investigation revealed some procedural mistakes, some work
actions that were not conducive to running a good fire marshal's
office, and some other items that we don't want to discuss at this
time,'' Kroner said.
   County Solicitor James Dodaro said the action against the three
officials has no bearing on whether the oil company followed proper
procedures in the reconstruction of the storage tank.
   Dodaro said the company never received nor paid for a certificate
of approval to build the tank.
   Kroner began investigating the fire marshal's office on Oct. 14
after he said Babyak produced a copy of a memorandum regarding the
tank during legal depositions that were part of Ashland Oil's
defense in a federal lawsuit.
   Since soon after the spill, Jacobs and his staff maintained that
they knew of no memo or any other correspondence giving Ashland
approval to rebuild the tank.
   On Oct. 14, according to Kroner, Ashland Oil attorneys had
possession of the fire marshals' internal memo, which never should
have been disclosed to anyone outside county law enforcement offices.
   Kroner said the memo claims that Kelly had inspected the area of
the tank, looked at some aerial photos of the tank farm, and had
approved ``the beginning or start of the project.''
   Ashland Oil has claimed it had approval to rebuild the tank on
the site.
   ``That's semantics, but it will be argued in court,'' Kroner
said. ``Up until these people left (the fire marshal's office), they
still denied they gave verbal approval.''
   Kroner said Jacobs had denied the existence of the internal memo
until last Thursday, when he admitted he found the original in his
desk on Nov. 3.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
