<DOCNO> AP881121-0197 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-88 2225EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Colonialism     11-21 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Colonialism,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. To Call For Colony-Free World</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The General Assembly is ready to demand a
worldwide end to colonialism and to condemn South Africa's rule of
South-West Africa.
   The assembly appears certain to approve a resolution Tuesday
declaring the 1990s to be the International Decade for the
Eradication of Colonialism. It also will probably pass a resolution
denouncing South Africa's control of South-West Africa, or Namibia.
   Last year, a resolution calling for Namibian independence passed
131-2, with seven abstentions. Only the United States and Britain
voted against it.
   South Africa was stripped of its voting rights in the General
Assembly in 1974.
   When the United Nations was established in 1945, 750 million
people lived without self-government in territories dependent on
colonial powers. By 1985, fewer than 3 million people still lived in
such territories.
   Talks are under way to grant independence to Namibia's 1.5
million residents and Western Sahara's 117,000.
   A tentative accord reached last week among South Africa, Cuba and
Angola paves the way for South Africa to grant independence to
Namibia, with the one-year transition possibly beginning early next
year. Cuba would remove its troops from Angola, where it is
supporting the Marxist government against U.S.- and South
African-backed rebels.
   South Africa has ruled Namibia since it took the former German
colony during World War I.
   The United Nations also is mediating peace talks on the Western
Sahara between Morocco, which occupies most of the northwest African
territory, and the Polisario independence movement fighting the
Moroccan army.
   Under a tentative agreement, about 2,000 U.N. peacekeepers would
monitor a referendum that would result in Western Sahara's
independence or affiliation with Morocco.
   Less likely to be decolonized is the former Portugese colony of
East Timor. Indonesia invaded the 550,000-resident island in 1975.
   Britain continues to claim the Falkland Islands, insisting that
the 1,800 Falkland residents wish to remain subjects of Britain.
Argentina also claims the islands, and the two nations fought a war
over their possession in 1982.
   Puerto Rico was removed from the U.N. list of non-self-governing
territories in 1952, when it adopted a constitution and status as a
U.S. commonwealth.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881121-0198 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-88 2235EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Mideast-Britain     11-21 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Mideast-Britain,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Reorganization Ends British Dominance Of Arab-Israeli U.N.
Diplomacy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's traditional leadership of U.N.
diplomatic efforts in the Arab-Israeli conflict ended Monday with a
reshuffle of senior posts in the world body, an official said.
   U.N. spokeswoman Nadia Younes announced ``structural changes''
taking effect immediately, transferring Undersecretary-General
Marrack Goulding's responsibility for Arab-Israeli problems directly
to Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar.
   Goulding, a Briton, will head the Office of Special Political
Affairs, with responsibility solely for all peacekeeping operations,
except for U.N. military observers in Afghanistan and Pakistan.
   The changes end Britain's longstanding ``portfolio'' for
Arab-Israeli affairs at the United Nations, under which British
officials at the United Nations conducted most diplomacy in the
region.
   Under the reorganization, Perez de Cuellar is taking more direct
control over diplomacy and arrangment of peace accords, and
delegating the implementation of those arrangements to senior
officials.
   The first major step in that direction came in June and July when
Perez de Cuellar took charge of cease-fire negotiations between Iran
and Iraq.
   The U.N. mediation of the Afghan accords were conducted by Diego
Cordovez of Ecuador, who received credit for that settlement.
   Ms. Younes said the secretary-general is making the changes ``in
response to the increasing demand for his good offices in the
maintenance of international peace and security and for United
Nations peacekeeping operations.''
   She refused to characterize the shuffle as a promotion or
demotion for anyone involved.
   Goulding will also be in charge of ``the planning and conduct of
future peacekeeping operations,'' a formidable task with several
potential new missions on the horizon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
