<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Reagan-Nuclear-Reax     11-21 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Nuclear-Reax,0542</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Utility Officials Originated Executive Order</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MOKRZYCKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEABROOK, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Utility officials originated the idea for
the executive order President Reagan signed giving the federal
government broad powers in nuclear power plant emergency planning, a
top executive of the stalled Seabrook nuclear project said Monday.
   There had been reports the order originated within the Department
of Energy, as well as speculation that New Hampshire Gov. John
Sununu _ a staunch Seabrook advocate whom President-elect George
Bush last week named his chief of staff _ had a hand in conceiving
the idea. Sununu had denied it.
   John Eichorn, chairman of the Seabrook joint owners' committee,
said neither the Energy Department nor Sununu came up with the
proposal.
   ``I'm sure it was the utility people,'' Eichorn said in an
interview at Seabrook after a news conference by Nuclear Regulatory
Commission Chairman Lando Zech.
   Zech said Seabrook could receive a low-power license by Christmas
if questions about plant owners' finances are resolved _ but he
indicated he considers that a big ``if.'' Zech noted that lead owner
Public Service Company of New Hampshire is under bankruptcy
protection.
   An NRC rule says plant finances do not have to be investigated
before a license is issued. Utility officials said they believed
Zech signaled that he personally favors waiving that rule, although
he made no clear statement on a waiver.
   A draft of the presidential order surfaced in June, sparking an
outcry from Seabrook foes and some supporters too. New Hampshire's
all-Republican congressional delegation, whose four members
conditionally support Seabrook, met with Reagan this summer and
asked him not to sign the proposal.
   But late Friday Reagan signed a revised version of the order,
which requires the Federal Emergency Management Agency to carry out
nuclear plant evacuation plans when state or local governments
refuse to cooperate.
   The order appears aimed primarily at Seabrook and the Shoreham
plant on New York's Long Island, both of which are completed but
stalled because of government opposition to evacuation plans. In
Seabrook's case, the opposition comes from neighboring
Massachusetts, which has six communities within Seabrook's 10-mile
emergency planning zone.
   Asked for details on how the order came to be signed in its final
form, Eichorn said, ``We were cut out of that process ... six to
nine months ago, and frankly I don't know where it's been in the
meantime.''
   Asked then what role Seabrook officials had in the order, Eichorn
said, ``We were interested in having it conceived.''
   ``I don't like taking the whole credit, but we certainly were
involved'' in originating the proposal, Eichorn said. He said
Shoreham officials also were involved.
   Zech, meanwhile, told reporters he had not seen the order and was
not sure how it could help Seabrook.
   Also on Monday, Gov.-elect Judd Gregg said he takes Sununu at his
word that he was not involved in getting Reagan to sign the order.
   During the weekend, Gregg suggested it was no coincidence that
Reagan signed the order the day after Sununu was named the next
White House chief of staff. But Sununu flatly denied any involvement.
   ``I take him at his word,'' Gregg said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881121-0200 </DOCNO>
