<HEAD>Gunman Kills Officer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gunman killed a police officer
and wounded another Monday night in a town north of Belfast, then
fled on a motorcycle, police said.
   The slain officer, identified as 50-year-old William Monteith,
was filling in for a colleague on sick leave when he was shot in
Castlederg, 60 miles northwest of Belfast and close to the border
with the Irish Republic, police said.
   The second officer, identified only as Monteith's nephew, was
grazed in the head by a bullet, they said.
   The shooting took place shortly before the officers were to have
closed security barriers to protect the town at night from Irish
Republican Army bomb attacks. The British Broadcasting Corp. in
Londonderry said it had a telephone call claiming IRA responsibility
for the attack.
   The victim was the sixth policeman killed this year and the 257th
since the mostly Roman Catholic IRA began its violent struggle in
1969 to end British rule in the predominately Protestant province.
