<HEAD>For Release, Tuesday, Nov. 29</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Today is Tuesday, Nov. 29, the 334th day of 1988. There are 32
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   In 1963, President Lyndon B. Johnson named a commission headed by
Earl Warren to investigate the assassination of President John F.
Kennedy.
   On this date:
   In 1530, Cardinal Thomas Wolsey, one-time adviser to England's
King Henry VIII, died.
   In 1864, a Colorado militia killed at least 150 peaceful Cheyenne
Indians in what became known as the Sand Creek Massacre.
   In 1890, the first Army-Navy football game was played, at West
Point, N.Y. Navy sank Army, 24-0.
   In 1924, Italian composer Giacomo Puccini died in Brussels before
he could complete his final opera, ``Turandot.'' (It was finished by
Franco Alfano.)
   In 1929, Navy Lt. Cmdr. Richard E. Byrd radioed that he'd made
the first airplane flight over the South Pole.
   In 1945, the monarchy was abolished in Yugoslavia and a republic
proclaimed.
   In 1947, the U.N. General Assembly passed a resolution calling
for the partitioning of Palestine between Arabs and Jews.
   In 1952, President-elect Dwight D. Eisenhower kept his campaign
promise to visit Korea to assess the war.
   In 1961, Enos the chimp was launched from Cape Canaveral aboard
the Mercury-Atlas V spacecraft, which orbited Earth twice and landed
off Puerto Rico.
   In 1967, Secretary of Defense Robert S. McNamara announced he was
leaving the Johnson administration to become president of the World
Bank.
   In 1981, actress Natalie Wood drowned in a boating accident off
Santa Catalina Island, Calif., at age 43.
   In 1986, actor Cary Grant, died in Davenport, Iowa, where he had
scheduled a public appearance. Grant was 82.
   Ten years ago: The United Nations observed an ``international day
of solidarity with the Palestinian people,'' an event boycotted by
the United States and about 20 other countries.
   Five years ago: The six astronauts aboard the space shuttle
Columbia concentrated on their round-the-clock experiments, one day
after being launched from the Kennedy Space Center.
   One year ago: A Korean Air jetliner disappeared off Burma, with
the loss of all 115 people aboard; South Korean authorities charged
North Korean agents had planted a bomb aboard the aircraft. Cuban
detainees released 26 hostages they had been holding for more than a
week at the Federal Detention Center in Oakdale, La.
   Today's birthdays: Sportscaster Vin Scully is 61. Sen. Paul
Simon, D-Ill., is 60. Musician Chuck Mangione is 48. Skier Suzy
Chaffee is 42. Actor-comedian Howie Mandel is 33. Actress Cathy
Moriarty is 28.
   Thought for today: ``A free press is not a privilege but an
organic necessity in a great society. Without criticism and reliable
and intelligent reporting, the government cannot govern.'' _ Walter
Lippmann, American journalist (1889-1974).
</TEXT>
