<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-88 1355EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-APN--Soviets-RelivingHistory ADV04-2Takendle10millioncallsinlessthantwodays.Ittookthefirstcable22yearstoachievethatsamestatistic.
  11-21 0801</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Soviets-Reliving History, ADV 04-2 Takes,0819</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv04
^AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Dec. 4
^From AP Newsfeatures</NOTE>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 4 b&w
photos.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ For most of the 70 years since the Soviet Union
came into being, Soviet history was tailored and falsified to suit
the rulers in the Kremlin and the party dogmatists. In today's freer
atmosphere, long suppressed truths are allowed to emerge, and the
nation is trying hard to come to grips with them.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a cool pine glade north of the Byelorussian
capital of Minsk where Soviet families used to come to picnic,
stroll or play chess, two schoolboys made a grisly discovery.
   Digging around in the Kuropaty forest during their May Day
holiday last spring, the boys unearthed some human skeletons that
started a grim search for historical truth.
   Since then, archaeologists have made wholescale excavations, and
researchers now estimate that more than 100,000 people were shot and
buried in mass graves there during the political purges of the late
1930s.
   In the Soviet Union, the past never lies far beneath the surface.
History is an abiding obsession here.
   For the Soviet nation, whose 70-year existence fits into a single
human lifespan, the past surges up again and again to influence the
present. In the more open atmosphere permitted by President Mikhail
S. Gorbachev's policy of glasnost, Soviets are trying to come to
grips with their nation's often dark, troubling and contradictory
legacy _ and use it to map a course for the future.
   ``People write heatedly and passionately about the events of 50
years ago as if they were writing about today's problems,''
Gorbachev said this year. ``There is nothing surprising about this.
They are talking about the most important thing for us ... about how
it could happen that, along with the heroic achievements of the
people, crimes against them became possible.''
   World War II is re-fought several times a week on state-run
television, in movies and documentaries. Rainy fall days barely thin
the throngs outside the red brick gates of Moscow's Novodevichy
Cemetery, where Soviets come to see the tombs of departed Kremlin
leaders who once fixed the course of their lives.
   History is never far behind the headlines:
   _ Armenians waging a long, noisy campaign to annex the
Nagorno-Karabakh region of neighboring Azerbaijan are contesting a
Soviet government decision made in 1923 that awarded the
predominantly Armenian region to Azerbaijan.
   _ In the three Baltic republics, mass movements arise to demand
greater autonomy from Moscow. Some Estonians, Latvians and
Lithuanians even seek total independence. Demonstrations are
triggered by each anniversary of the 1939 Hitler-Stalin pact that
awarded control of the states, then sovereign nations, to the Soviet
Union, which absorbed them.
   _ Gorbachev, embarked on a bold course to revitalize the nation's
economy, trim its bureaucracy and get the citizenry more involved in
decision-making, rarely speaks publicly without citing the
stagnation of Leonid I. Brezhnev's rule and the harsh administrative
grip imposed by dictator Josef V. Stalin.
   In the atmosphere of freer inquiry and debate fostered by
glasnost, the study of the past has become both an eagerly shared
passion and a bitter, divisive issue for Soviets, with the top man
in the Kremlin out in front with the calls for increased candor.
   ``One cannot agree with those who propose that we forget our
history or use only a certain part of it,'' Gorbachev said in
January. ``All this enables us to draw lessons for the present ...
and to disclose more fully the potential of socialism and its
values.''
   But more than 3{ years into Gorbachev's rule it still isn't clear
whether glasnost will bring unhampered historical scholarship and
the right to differ on fundamental questions or just substitute one
Kremlin orthodoxy for another.
   Gorbachev himself recently chaired the meeting of a special
Communist Party commission preparing a new ``concise history'' of
the party, showing how keenly he wants his influence to be felt in
the new Soviet view of the past.
   School history texts, full of ritual self-congratulations,
radiant socialist futures and cartoon-like heroes and villains, were
thrown out and are being rewritten.
   Windows on the past, shut tight for years by the censor, have
been opened. Soviets now jostle at lending libraries for works about
the long-concealed ``blank spots'' in their history. The book most
in demand is Anatoly Rybakov's ``Children of the Arbat,'' a novel
about the bloody swath cut through society by Stalin's political
terror that left its traces of horror at Kuropaty.
   And history in the Gorbachev era has meant the humbling of the
memories of men who, while alive, were spoken of as the worthy
spiritual heirs of Soviet founder Vladimir I. Lenin.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
