<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-88 1357EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-APN--Soviets-RelivingHistory ADV04-1stAdd   11-21 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Soviets-Reliving History, ADV04-1st Add ,0645</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv04</NOTE>
<BYLINE>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</BYLINE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Dec. 4</NOTE>
<HEAD>MOSCOW: Vladimir I. Lenin.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   A Leningrad monument to Brezhnev was spirited away at night. A
vandal at Moscow State University spilled ink on a memorial plaque
to former Kremlin ideologue Mikhail A. Suslov. The city of Izhevsk,
which once bore the name of Dmitri F. Ustinov, spent more than $3.2
million to wipe the late defense minister's name off street signs,
official stationery and railway timetables.
   For Gorbachev and his allies, history matters because it bares
the mistakes of past Kremlin leaders and points away from what
Gorbachev wants to avoid: the totalitarianism and bureaucratic
choke-hold on society that marred Stalin's rule, the erratic
capriciousness of Nikita S. Khrushchev, the complacency and moral
rot under Brezhnev.
   ``It is said that people learn from mistakes, and nations learn
from tragedies. Let us learn,'' one author, L. Ovrutsky, said in a
newspaper article on Soviet history this year.
   Gorbachev also seeks to right what he regards as historical
injustices. By rehabilitating some of the revolutionaries and
visionaries Stalin destroyed, Gorbachev has been able to resurrect
their once-discredited ideas as ideological underpinning for his own
reforms.
   Training glasnost's spotlight back into the past has had
sensational results. Among the revelations this year:
   _ Brezhnev reportedly was clinically dead at one point in 1976
but recovered at least partially and remained Soviet president until
his death in 1982.
   _ Stalin was described by one Soviet newspaper as a paranoid
whose brain was damaged by a stroke.
   _ Nikolai I. Bukharin and other Stalin foes shot as ``enemies of
the people'' in the 1930s are now said to have been framed.
   Such reports have startled a country long fed a diet of
reassuring Kremlin communiques.
   ``In the past two years, I have learned more than I did in the
previous 50 years of my life,'' one middle-aged Muscovite recently
told a newspaper.
   Predictably, the questioning, doubts and criticism, where before
there was often only praise, have produced a backlash among Soviets
who feel that their entire history, even the building of socialism
itself, has been besmirched.
   ``I would very much like to understand: who needs, and why, to
have every prominent leader of the party Central Committee and the
Soviet government compromised after he leaves office and discredited
in connection with his actual or supposed mistakes and calculations
... Where did we get this passion for squandering the prestige and
dignity of the leaders of the world's first socialist country?'' a
Leningrad teacher wrote in the Sovietskaya Rossiya daily earlier in
the year.
   The official response to that letter, signed by Nina Andreyeva,
demonstrated how explosive the issue of history in the Soviet Union
can be _ and the limits still drawn on historical scholarship.
Pravda, the party's principal organ, attacked its fellow newspaper
for printing a document lauding Stalin and forced Sovietskaya
Rossiya to recant by printing the Pravda attack.
   Despite glasnost, Stalin or Brezhnev are rarely defended in
print. Since Gorbachev's policy is avowedly the opposite of theirs,
praise for his predecessors could be, or might seem to be, an attack
on Gorbachev or his policy of change.
   But on the whole, glasnost has meant a dramatic widening of the
historical field, and a coming to terms with some of the
uncomfortable truths of the Soviet past that long lay hidden or were
played down. Historian Fyodor Burlatsky was referring to the 1953-64
Khrushchev era, but might well have been speaking of all Soviet
history, when he said:
   ``For a long time, a very long time, talking about those stormy
years was not accepted practice. It was as if someone's hand had
ripped out an entire chapter from our chronicle.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Dec. 4</NOTE>
