<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Soviets-Assessing History, ADV 04 ,0422</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv04
^AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Dec. 4</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-APN--Soviets-Reliving History</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   MOSCOW (AP) _ Mikhail S. Gorbachev is leading his nation in a
reassessment of its past that he calls indispensable for charting
its political future. How do Soviets now view the 70 years of their
country's history? Here is a sampler of recent comment:
   
   THE RUSSIAN REVOLUTION _ ``Maybe the revolution was a mistake?...
Such are the doubts of many people, and to be quiet about it is to
drive the sickness inside.'' (author Boris Kulikov, writing in Nash
Sovremennik magazine)
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   JOSEF V. STALIN _ ``Under Stalinism, order was no myth. But now
that Comrade Stalin is no longer with us, he's being blamed for
everything. As if he personally made arrests, presided over `troika'
sessions (summary trials), made denunciations etc.'' (Ya. Mesechkov,
a reader of Ogonyok)
   ``Stalinism is the curse that is hanging over our people and
reducing to nothing the efforts of one generation after another.''
(closing words of the film ``The Process'')
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   WORLD WAR II _ ``We often portray combat operations in a
one-sided fashion that leaves the enemy _ his real power and
aggressive intentions _ outside the picture. But millions of Soviet
people did not die in a tilt with windmills! ... There is the matter
of our allies. Usually, very little has been said about them.''
(Dmitri A. Volkogonov, head of the Defense Ministry's Military
History Institute)
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   NIKITA S. KHRUSHCHEV _ ``A people that had once elevated Ivan the
Terrible ... could not accept, after Stalin, a public figure devoid
of mystical magic, an earthbound and fallible leader who was subject
to mistakes and delusions.'' (historian Fyodor Burlatsky)
   ``He was reared in the atmosphere of the `great leader syndrome.'
He breathed in its vapors, and did not find in himself the strength
to resist the destructive feeling that he was a chosen person and
absolutely infallible.'' (author Boris Yasilyev, writing in Izvestia)
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   LEONID I. BREZHNEV _ ``At one time in early 1976, he was
clinically dead and after being revived, had to wait for three
months for his thinking and speech to normalize ... The Soviet
leader's senility, infirmity and sickness became a subject not so
much of compassion and pity on the part of Soviet citizens, but
rather of irritation and mockery ...'' (historian Roy Medvedev)
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Dec. 4</NOTE>
