<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-88 1408EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--HawkMan ADV04-2Takes   11-21 0922</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Hawk Man, ADV 04-2 Takes,0951</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv04
^AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Dec. 4
^From AP Newsfeatures</NOTE>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 3 b&w
photos.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ Twenty years ago, an anonymous donor left an
injured hawk on Leonard Soucy's doorstep. Whoever did it picked the
right house. Soucy has since patched up thousands of birds, not to
mention the occasional lame duck.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By SID MOODY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILLINGTON N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It is hard to pinpoint just when a man
decides to turn his back yard into a repair shop for wrecked birds.
   For Leonard Soucy it probably came 20 years ago when an anonymous
someone, like an unwed mother abandoning her newborn in a basket at
the church door, left a red-tailed hawk with a broken wing in a
cardboard box on his front stoop.
   It was a challenge Soucy couldn't say no to. He still can't.
   That is why his current back yard is an intensive care facility
of assorted cages _ some the size of boxcars _ in which he endeavors
to restore to the wild squadrons of sick and injured owls, hawks,
eagles, falcons and selected songbirds. And the occasional lame duck.
   In earthly terms appropriate to a pirate's parrot, Soucy tells
how birds have taken over his home, his bank account, his job and
even his wife, Diane.
   ``Birds have eaten me up. They've consumed my life.''
   These are the birds who came to dinner, as it were, for whose
convalescence Soucy flies in 10,000 crickets a week from a Tennessee
breeder, millions of grub worms from California, grasshoppers galore
from Georgia and 150,000 rodents a year.
   ``I have 10,000 meal worms here right now, and they're just
snacks,'' exclaims Soucy to whom sotto voce is an abomination.
   ``This cost $100,000 last year. If the food wasn't donated, it
would have cost $250,000. Just one rat costs $2.50. A mouse is
$1.09. But I have to do it. No one else is going to.''
   Soucy may have as many as 500 recovering birds at a time in his
100,000 cubic feet of cages. There's a barred owl on the mend from
entanglement with a kite string. A golden eagle with a broken wing.
Hawks shot by what Soucy calls unprintable ``slobs.'' Orphaned birds
raised from infancy. An oriole that will winter over because it did
not recover until after the last flight south.
   Soucy still tries to sandwich his profession as a self-employed
tool and die pattern maker around a hobby that was once a Sopwith
Camel and is now a B-52. This sometimes requires him to go to his
paying job at 2 a.m. There are emergency calls at all hours.
   ``A bird gets hit, falls out of the nest. It doesn't belong to
the police. Not the dog warden. Doesn't belong to anybody. So they
say `Call Soucy.''' A screech owl flies down a chimney and catches
fire. Call Soucy. A goshawk crashes through a picture window and
lands dazed on a coffee table. Call Soucy.
   ``There's nobody else to pass them to. The bird stops here.''
   Last year, Soucy's busiest yet, 1,485 wild birds ended up on his
doorstep. This included 240 raptors, the carnivorous birds he
specializes in. About half recovered and were returned to the wild.
Repair is not cheap.
   ``To do an intramedulary fusion of a bird's wing bone with a pin
can cost $400 for the operation. Post-op care can approach $1,000.''
   Fortunately Soucy has two understanding veterinarians nearby _
Drs. Andrew Major in Plainfield and Ken Jacobsen in Basking Ridge _
who donate their surgical skills.
   ``We can keep a bird alive 90 percent of the time. But can we
restore it 100 percent? The bird won't make it in the wild if it's
only 75 percent. So we keep about 100 for educational lectures at
schools and such and euthenize the rest.''
   Soucy's preoccupation with raptors is evolutionary. He was born
in Cedar Grove, N.J., 57 years ago when it had some open land, not
the 40,000 people it's packed with today. He learned nature from an
uncle, a hunter, a species Soucy has no quarrel with despite the
many gunshot-maimed birds he's treated.
   ``No competent, moral hunter will shoot hawks and owls. The
bleeping slobs do.''
   His interest was piqued years ago when he read an article in
Audubon magazine on hawks. So he and Diane went out to Hawk Mountain
in eastern Pennsylvania to see the fall migration when thousands of
raptors may fly by in a day riding the thermals south.
   ``I couldn't imagine 1,000 hawks in the whole world much less
overhead.''
   Gunners used to shoot hundreds of birds in a day at Hawk Mountain
just to try their aim. This ended in 1934 when a wealthy woman from
New York, Mrs. Rosalie Edge, acquired the mountain as a refuge for
the birds and birdwatchers. Cape May, an even bigger migrating
junction at the tip of New Jersey, was another gunnery range. This
stopped when the federal government outlawed shooting raptors in
1972.
   By then Soucy and Diane had been in the bird repair business for
four years. They had rehabilitated that first red tail and released
it. One thing led to another, so they bought a home in semi-rural
land next to the Great Swamp Wildlife Refuge here. It started out as
a backyard hobby, a gesture to right some of the wrongs committed by
the biggest raptor of them all, man.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881121-0222 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-88 1409EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--HawkMan ADV04-1stAdd   11-21 0858</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Hawk Man, ADV 04-1st Add,0879</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv04</NOTE>
<BYLINE>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</BYLINE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Dec. 4</NOTE>
<HEAD>MILLINGTON, N.J.: all, man.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``The stupidity of man not doing better gradually enraged me. All
things on earth are valuable to us because they help stabilize the
darn thing. I was raised to think man owned the world. We've got to
get out of this idea because we're a part of it. It's all our world.
We've got to take care of Momma Earth.''
   He had no illusions about it being easy.
   ``Historically this country has a love-hate relationship with
raptors. We put the bald eagle on our national seal. But there used
to be a bounty on them. People don't care if a robin kills a worm.
But it's what's being killed that matters. A fox that kills a
chicken is a bad fox. If it kills a snake, it's a good fox. To
hunters a hawk that killed a rabbit was a bad thing, so they killed
the hawk and then the rabbit. Farmers thought raptors were vermin,
but very, very, very few hawks will kill chickens. But that's a hard
sell.''
   Soucy accepts raptors for what they are, meat-eaters in nature's
scheme, just like the folks at Burger King.
   ``Raptors are truly remarkable animals. An owl can see a lighted
match a half-mile away. A hawk two miles up can see a rabbit and
know it's a rabbit. They probably have the best eyesight in the
whole world.'' He admires their efforts to try and adapt to a world
not of nature's making. For study he's trapped a snowy owl
underneath the wing of a Concorde jet parked at Kennedy airport.
   As Soucy's reputation spread so did the cages out back. But he's
a realist. He will not turn away a tearful youngster who shows up
with a baby phoebe that has fallen out of the nest. But his eye
cannot be on every sparrow.
   ``Obviously there are limits.''
   He and Diane learned as they went along, designing cages and
treating the patients so as not to make permanent welfare cases of
their ailing flock. There are triumphs.
   ``In 1982, which happened to be the national year of the bald
eagle, one of them fell out of the sky. It ended up here. I took it
to Bill Hobby, a local vet, and he got an IV into the bird. He found
it had too much mercury in its blood. Six weeks later we flew him
down to Chesapeake Bay in a donated Lear jet with an NBC-TV crew and
returned a healthy eagle to the sky.''
   In time the big birds began running into big money. ``It costs
$175 to air freight a recovered osprey down to Florida after
migrating season. I've shipped ferruginous hawks to Arizona. When it
looked like Diane was going down in a heap and I couldn't afford it
any more, a friend said we should incorporate.''
   They are now The Raptor Trust, eligible for tax-exempt donations.
A local lumber company donates wood for cages. AT&T, which has huge
office complexes in the area, gave $7,000 for a new cage. In the
summer the Soucys have five full-time staffers and 25 volunteers.
The hobby has become one of the 10 biggest bird recovery operations
in the nation.
   ``We took a five-day vacation this year, the first in 16 years. I
hired Jean Stamy, an ex-teacher, to show school groups around. I
told her she'd work harder and be paid less if she came to me. I
kept my promise.
   ``The reality is, how big can we get? We don't charge for our
services _ whom do you send a bill to? _ so we have to beg. That's
what I've become. A beggar.''
   Soucy has raised $185,000 to buy the property next door for more
space and an educational center to make a hard sell a little easier.
   ``I like to think we're setting an example. In the last 20 years
Americans have gone back to being more intolerant of nature, gone
back to their computers and Porsches. If they had more sympathy for
the planet that sustains us, maybe they wouldn't puke on their world
so much.
   ``I figure I've put 100,000 hours into all this, and I've never
taken a dime out,'' said Soucy strolling among the cages under the
penetrating stare of his patients.
   Maria, the golden eagle, a permanent resident, eyed him
dispassionately. Three snowy owls watched unblinkingly. A clutch of
great horned owls, as stately as Supreme Court justices in a group
portrait, perched motionless on a dead limb. Their thoughts about
Leonard Soucy, if any, were inscrutable. His weren't.
   ``I've thought weekly I'd finally give it up. Maybe something
died you'd worked hard over. Twenty years I've been out in the back
yard putting broken birds back together. Where did all that time
go?''
   He stared back at the owls.
   ``I don't think I would do it all over again.''
   He reconsidered. ``I don't know.''
   He brightened.
   ``But I've probably got more `God bless you's' in my life than
most people.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Dec. 4</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881121-0223 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-88 1417EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--Mr.Bojangles ADV04-1stAdd   11-21 0778</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Mr. Bojangles, ADV 04-1st Add,0810</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv04</NOTE>
<BYLINE>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</BYLINE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Dec. 4</NOTE>
<HEAD>NEW YORK: buy music.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   One night David Bromberg, who'd played guitar live with Arlo
Guthrie on his hit ``Alice's Restaurant'' on New York
``underground'' radio station WBAI, and Walker were ``hobnobbing
around in the Village.'' Bromberg persuaded Walker to go to WBAI and
perform ``Mr. Bojangles.'' The station recorded it and kept playing
it. People listening to Circus Maximus in Greenwich Village would
ask who wrote ``Mr. Bojangles.'' Walker was hot. He says, ``I cut
three albums in about a five-month period.
   ``I didn't like the city atmosphere of cutting records. I decided
I wanted to get out. I live my life. In the '70s I was in Texas.
Doing what I wanted to do, I wound up having the strongest part of
my career.
   ``I don't have a career. I have an adventure with a guitar.''
   With his Lost Gonzo Band, Walker cut four records between 1974
and '78. ``Viva Terlingua'' became his biggest-selling album.
   These days, Walker travels with another Texas
performer-songwriter and their guitars. He says, ``I go out and work
about 10 days a month, on average. Any more money than that and
you've got to pay the IRS all of it.
   ``The Charlie Daniels Band goes on those huge endurance tours. He
has three semi-trailers and two buses.
   ``You can play it on the guitar and people will be touched. I
played two nights in a beautiful wooden concert hall in Hanover,
N.H., with 1,100 people there. Three nights later I was in Keene,
N.H., a theater that held about 750 people. I had two guitars and my
songs and stories. People had a great time. You need to have a
well-rounded repertoire. The symplicity of doing it is enjoyable. It
leaves room for profit for the promoter and the artist.
   ``Steve Fromholz opens for me. He wrote `I'd Have To Be Crazy'
for Willie Nelson. I've cut a duet with Willie, one of Steve's
songs, `The Man with the Big Hat's Buying.' Steve and I have been
doing it for the last few concerts as an encore and it has been
knocking them out.
   ``It was time to do something simple again.
   ``I was running myself pretty ragged through the 1970s with the
Gonzo Band. We did 150 or 200 shows a year, an album every six
months and were partying pretty hard while we were touring. We'd
party at night, travel, do a show. We had two chartered planes with
us. If we were within an hour's flight of New Orleans we'd fly there
and party in the French Quarter till 5 in the morning. We were
tearing it up. We were on that kind of roll. We thought it was fun.
   ``In 1979 I found out I had five years with no tax records. My
people had paid some but the records were shoddy. I owed quite a bit
and penalties. I had a lot of that to catch up.
   ``When I hit 1980 I decided it was time to make some lifestyle
changes and patch some holes up. I had a 2-year-old daughter. I
started scaling down a bit, some tours with the band and some solo.
I got my wife more involved with the accounting and myself more
entangled with the business end of it. She has been my manager since
1985.
   ``I had to re-mortgage the house. This is the first year since
1968 I don't owe anything. I'm actually able to make some gains.
   ``Jessie Jane is 10 now and Django Cody is 6. I wrote `Django's
Lullaby' for him. I make up a lot of songs I don't write down, that
my family can feel and hear them, that I can make my home happy with
my music.
   ``Django's going to be a golfer. I've been telling him you can
play golf longer than any other sport. With golf and a little music,
he can have a good life.''
   At 46, Walker has long-range goals. ``I want to be a productive
artist. I want to chronicle my life as I go through it, the hell
raising and having fun when I was younger, kids and family, the
deepening of my relationship with my wife. I sing about those.
   ``I think you realize you haven't told people you love how much
you love them often enough. I imagine I'll be writing more songs
like that. I've been lucky to have this career, not really playing
by all the rules. But the game is still a good song. That keeps me
in the game.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Dec. 4</NOTE>
