<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--LampreyThreat ADV04-2Takes   11-21 0753</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Lamprey Threat, ADV 04-2 Takes,0768</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv04
^AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Dec. 4</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo.)
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ Sea lampreys, eel-like creatures that attack
salmon and trout, are threatening the fishing industry at Lake
Champlain, the nation's sixth-largest freshwater lake. The lampreys,
which number in the tens of thousands, are finding new targets:
bass, pike, and in some cases, swimmers.</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KEKIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PLATTSBURGH, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nancy Papineau still shudders at the
memory of the slimy tangle of suction-cup-filled mouths and
tooth-laden tongues in the fish tank at Dave Richard's Bait Shop.
``Absolutely gross. Horrible,'' she says.
   Richard agrees: Sea lampreys aren't a pretty sight. Nonetheless,
he's displayed them off and on for four years. With lampreys
threatening the local sport-fishing industry, Richard wants folks to
know what they look like.
   ``It's real serious,'' says Richard, who also fishes
commercially. ``I'd say if they don't control them the lake will be
dead within the next 10 years. They're getting on everything.''
   No one knows for certain how the lampreys, which are indigenous
to the ocean and have no natural predator, entered Lake Champlain.
One theory suggests that they hitched rides on boats. Regardless of
how they arrived, they've been there for over a century _ and
lately, people who rely on the lake for their livelihoods don't like
what they're seeing.
   Goose Gagnon is one of them. He quit his job in a furniture
factory last year to devote all his time to commercial fishing.
``There will be days when you come out and every fish you land has a
(lamprey) hit on them, more than one,'' says Gagnon, who's been
fishing the lake for over 30 years. ``Some I've cut open and I
refuse to eat because the meat looked bad.''
   Gagnon's not alone.
   ``I've seen fish jump that had five or six (lampreys) on 'em, and
usually they're about 8 inches long,'' says Ken Coleman, who moved
to Willsboro from Michigan three years ago. ``And they will stay
with that fish as long as possible. In most cases that one hit
doesn't kill the fish. This is why you'll see fish with scars. And
if they lose that fish they'll take another one, so they may go
through three or four fish until they reach their full size.''
   ``It's pretty severe,'' acknowledges Paul Neff, an aquatic
biologist with the New York State Bureau of Fisheries. ``Sea lamprey
activity is intense, there's a big population, in the many tens of
thousands. We should be seeing fish 8 to 15 pounds, and we just
aren't seeing them. Lake Champlain historically had a tremendous
population of Atlantic salmon, and that population went right down
the tubes. It also had a good lake trout population, and that went
right down the tubes.''
   Lampreys are blamed for much of that loss. They spawn in wetlands
and streams that feed the lake, and their larvae can live there for
three or more years. Tom Jolliff, sea lamprey unit leader for the
New York Bureau of Fisheries, says one female might spawn up to
100,000 eggs at a time. And each lamprey can live up to 17 years,
killing 40 pounds of fish during its life.
   Lampreys, which can grow longer than 20 inches, normally do their
damage in the deepest extremities of their habitat. Using their
mouths and tongues, the lampreys latch onto fish, bore holes in
their sides and literally suck the life out of the fish until they
are near death.
   These days the lampreys in Lake Champlain _ the sixth-largest
freshwater lake in the nation _ are acting more like predators than
the parasites they actually are. Their favorite targets are no
longer just salmon and lake trout.
   ``They're hitting pike and bass _ scaly, warm-water fish that
they never hit before,'' says Mike Brown, an outdoors writer who
lives on the lake. ``I caught a lot of pike last year that were 32
inches long and only weighed three pounds. They were like stick
fish.''
   ``The lamprey bothers the lake trout and the salmon, but it's
nothing compared to the job it's doing on the brown trout and the
steelheads,'' says Coleman, who dealt with a similar problem in the
Great Lakes when he worked for the Michigan game department. ``You
don't see a brown trout in here more than 2 years old.''
   Fishermen, aren't the only ones feeling the effects.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881121-0225 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-88 1421EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--LampreyThreat Adv04-1stAdd   11-21 0758</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Lamprey Threat, Adv 04-1st Add,0770</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv04</NOTE>
<BYLINE>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</BYLINE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Dec. 4</NOTE>
<HEAD>PLATTSBURGH, N.Y.: the effects.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``Swimmers are even being hit,'' says New York Assemblyman Chris
Ortloff, whose district borders the lake. ``What that tells us is
that there are so many lamprey that they're indiscriminately
attaching themselves to whatever swims by because there simply
aren't enough trout and salmon in the lake to support them all.''
   The situation has been getting worse since the mid-1970s _ ever
since New York and Vermont began stocking hundreds of thousands of
salmon and trout every year to make the 125-mile-long lake a
sport-fishing Mecca.
   John Anderson, a Vermont fisheries manager, says one reason for
the stocking was to study the lamprey problem.
   ``Some people think we've dragged our feet,'' Anderson says.
``But if we went ahead (and treated the lake without evaluating the
situation) we'd have been hauled into the courts and we'd be there
forever.''
   Still, the study has taken nearly a decade and makes no sense to
Coleman. ``Why on earth they ever did what they did is beyond me,''
he says. ``They re-created the fishery backward. They should have
treated the lampreys first and then stocked the fish. They gave them
food so, bang, the population soared.''
   Last August, New York, Vermont and the Canadian province of
Quebec signed an agreement to work together to improve the lake. In
addition, Vermont and New York are cooperating on a plan to control
the lampreys. The New York State Department of Environmental
Conservation, the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service and the Vermont
Department of Fish and Wildlife have assembled a 433-page draft
environmental impact statement in connection with a proposed lamprey
control program. If it works, officials estimate 500 jobs would be
created and increased sport fishing would generate $2.5 million to
$3.5 million a year.
   The plan calls for two so-called ``lampricides'' to be applied
twice, in four-year intervals, in 14 streams _ nine in New York and
five in Vermont _ and five stream-delta areas. The experiment, which
would begin next fall, would cost about $3 million.
   TFM is the main chemical that would be used. The amount applied
kills lampreys but can be metabolized by most other fish and has not
harmed water fowl, mammals or humans. It's been used extensively and
successfully in the Great Lakes and in two of New York's Finger
Lakes (Cayuga Lake and Seneca Lake) and has proven relatively
harmless. The main detriment is that some non-target organisms _
invertebrates such as worms and insects on which fish feed _ will be
killed, but not to any great extent, according to the environmental
statement.
   Bayer 73, the other chemical, is used in other countries to treat
tapeworm in humans and in this country to treat domestic animals.
   As usual, the notion of applying chemicals to the environment is
creating apprehension.
   ``My organization is very concerned about the program and its
impact,'' says Joan Mulhern, associate director of the Vermont
Public Interest Research Group, a privately funded citizen action
group. ``We've been studying the environmental impact statement and
identifying what we think are inadequacies with that report. We've
found a lot of discrepancies between the environmental impact
statement and information from the Environmental Protection Agency
about the chemicals that are going to be used. There's a lot more
information that needs to be given to the public.''
   Like VPIRG, the Lake Champlain Committee, a natural resource
advocacy group based in Burlington, Vt., hasn't taken a stand on the
matter yet, but its members are also concerned.
   ``We want to know alternatives,'' says spokeswoman Lori Fisher.
``We don't want the public money to get only channeled into a
proposal that would stimulate recreational trophy fishing.
   ``We can't lose sight of the fact that we have fish for human
consumption significantly impacted by PCBs and chlordane. There's a
rule to eat only one fish a month out of the lake. We need a
considerable amount of money to find a solution to that. We can't
lose sight of those types of problems. We want people to look at the
larger picture.''
   New Yorkers got the chance to voice their views on the matter
recently at hearings in Ticonderoga and Plattsburgh, and sentiment
favored treating the lake. Vermonters will get their turn at public
hearings next February. Officials from both states will assess the
public's reaction and decide whether to go ahead with the plan. For
it to work, both states must cooperate.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Dec. 4</NOTE>
