<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-88 2136EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--HomeVideo ADV00   11-21 1215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Home Video, ADV 00,1265</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video News and Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Videos reviewed this week: ``Shakedown,'' ``The Moderns,''
``Sleepaway Camp II.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``Shakedown'' (MCA Home Entertainment; VHS-Beta, $89.95; Rated R).
   
   Trashing New York City's sleazy 42nd Street strip in a stupid
chase scene is the emotional center of ``Shakedown,'' a violent,
improbable crime thriller that lasted five minutes in theaters and
went immediately to videocassette.
   It stars Peter Weller and Sam Elliott, two talented and
disciplined actors who must be thoroughly embarrassed by their
involvement in this witless film, but struggle vainly to breathe
some humanity into two-dimensional roles.
   The name of the screenwriter-director is being withheld to
protect his career. Well, all right. It's James Glickenhaus. That's
G_L_I_C_K_E_N_H_A_U_S.
   This ugly little movie plays like a sadistic Looney Tune, with
3.5 crazy chase scenes, a half-dozen explosions, psychotic,
cartoonish behavior by practically everyone, pointless vulgarity and
mayhem.
   Elliott is the cop pal of Weller, a lawyer about to marry and
work for his fiancee's Daddy on Wall Street. His last case as a
public defender is a self-defense plea for a crack dealer who's
killed a crooked cop in a drug deal.
   Of course, the lawyer's Old Flame is prosecuting the case and
they hop into bed without a thought for the personal or legal ethics
of the situation. As the crooked cops close in on Our Heros, there
is much bashing and chasing and shooting and blowing up of things.
   If that's what you're looking for, this movie has it.
   _ By Scott Williams, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``The Moderns'' (Nelson Entertainment; VHS-Beta, $89.98; Rated R)
   
   Why would a woman take a bath lathered in tiers of pearls? It's
certainly not the best way to get the neck clean.
   Probably because Linda Fiorentino already had read this silly
script and expected to be surprised by a nude Keith Carradine who
moments before was downstairs trying to sell a painting to her
art-collector husband, Bertram Stone. Isn't it every woman's fantasy
to make love on the bathroom floor wearing pearls and patches of
soap bubbles?
   Carradine's character is called Nick Hart, giving us Hart vs.
Stone. So don't ask who will end up with lovely, bathing-beauty
Rachel.
   The raging husband (John Lone), is abusive to Rachel, kicks Hart
in the face in a boxing ring after challenging him to a duel and
burns Modiglianis in the fireplace. After first, of course, cutting
one of the model's breasts from the canvas because a critic said its
nipple looked like a wart.
   Why does Rachel stay with Stone? Money. Hart, a starving painter,
lives in a garret and even forges masters to survive. He couldn't
possibly buy the pouting, languid Rachel enough pearls in which to
bathe.
   Besides, this is Bohemian Paris of the 1920s, and writer-director
Alan Rudolph presents these characters on the cutting edge of a new
artistic era as single-dimensional saps and lunatics.
   He and co-writer Jon Bradshaw may have meant well, but the
archness and self-conscious pretension with which they translate
avant-garde to the screen sets one's teeth on edge. It's difficult
to decide if they're insulting their audience or displaying their
own intellectual shallowness. Probably both. The constant lapsing
into French with sporadic subtitles is difficult to deal with,
especially on the small screen. The literary references are obscure
enough that if you don't know them, you won't know what you're not
missing. But when you do catch one, it's generally embarrassingly
gee-whiz.
   ``The Moderns'' is a no-win endeavor: There's no enlightenment,
nor any loving treatment of artistic eccentrics.
   Minor characters, including several drawn from real life, float
through as proof that this was Paris and that it was bizarre.
Gertrude Stein and Alice B. Toklas are spotted at their salon;
Ernest Hemingway is stupidly drunk in every bar.
   Genevieve Bujold and Geraldine Chaplin give credibility to
peripheral but stock roles. Wallace Shawn plays Oiseau, a gossip
columnist who dresses up like a dumpy middle-aged woman so he can go
unobserved to his own funeral, where a graveside priest eulogizes
him as having ``converted gossip into poetry.''
   Oiseau gets off most of the goofier lines, including telling Hart
at the railroad station: ``I just ran into Maurice Ravel in the
men's room, but he didn't recognize me.'' Who would, in those high
heels and cloche hat?
   Oiseau sashays past Kevin J. O'Connor, playing the besotted
Hemingway, who is mumbling lines that conclude with ``Paris is a
portable banquet.''
   ``You should work on that,'' quips Oiseau with the hindsight we
all have that it utimately will read ``Moveable Feast.''
   As he and Hart head back to the United States, Oiseau says he's
glad to be leaving Paris because ``the imitators are imitiating the
imitators. Hollywood will be like a breath of fresh air.''
   Amen. The city depicted here is not only stagnant, but
bush-league.
   _ By Theasa Tuohy, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Sleepaway Camp II: Unhappy Campers'' (Nelson Entertainment;
VHS-Beta, $79.98; Rated PG)
   
   Dear Mommy and Daddy: Here I am at Camp Rolling Rock. Angela, our
new counselor, is real neat. She plays a great guitar and sings real
good, and loves to take us on nature hikes. Last night, one of the
kids, Phoebe, told us about a 14-year-old boy who everybody picked
on. Well, he killed a bunch of people six years ago at Camp Arawak.
Angela got real mad at Phoebe for telling that story and took her
back to the cabin. But we never saw Phoebe again. Angela told us the
next day that she had to send her home. There are these other two
girls who like to smoke cigarettes and stay up late with boys.
Angela got real mad at them, too, and had to send them home. Angela
gets mad at a lot of people and they disappear. I don't think I like
Camp Rolling Rock too much. I am not a happy camper. But please
don't let Angela send me home ...
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   And dear viewer, whatever you do, avoid ``Sleepaway Camp II.''
This ``Friday the 13th'' ripoff stars Pamela Springsteen (``Fast
Times at Ridgemont High'') as the killer counselor who dispatches
campers faster than you can rev up your chainsaw. She slices and
dices all over the place and does in one little darling by stuffing
her down the outhouse comode.
   You can pretty much figure out who Angela is. The why is slightly
more elusive, as it normally is in these movies.
   The fright level in this Michael A. Simpson film, which was
written by Fritz Gordon, is not very high. You won't bite your
fingernails but you might kick yourself for staying with this movie
for longer than 10 minutes.
   _ By Dolores Barclay, AP Arts Editor.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for children
under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
