<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Food:DrinkingSurvey     11-21 0179</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Food: Drinking Survey,0180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>FOOD: Drinking Survey</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Southerners drank more alcoholic beverages
than residents of any other U.S. region last year, and households
with incomes above $35,000 drank more than any other income group, a
study found.
   The study, released by the alcoholic beverage research
publication Impact, was based on diaries kept by 12,000 people
during 1987. The survey, compiled by NFO Research Inc. of Toledo,
Ohio, covered beverage consumption by location, time of day, sex,
age, geographic region and household income.
   The South, when considered as one of four U.S. regions, drank the
most alcoholic beverages _ 32.3 percent of all consumed _ followed
by the Northeast at 24.8 percent, the North Central region at 24.1
percent and the West at 18.8 percent. But the West led the nation in
wine consumption, at 31.3 percent of all wine drunk.
   Southerners drank 39.2 percent of all wine coolers and 33.8
percent of beer, leading in those categories. Consumption of
distilled spirits, or hard liquor, was almost evenly divided among
the four regions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881121-0253 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-88 0206EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Food:WrestlingCaterer     11-21 0509</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Food: Wrestling Caterer,0524</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Food: Wrestling Caterer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN L. ADLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Neil LeClerc clearly is one guy you wouldn't want
to mess with on the wrestling mat _ or in the kitchen.
   At 24, LeClerc has a solid hold on two divergent careers. In
fact, when they're in season, many of the wrestlers who train under
LeClerc try to think about anything but food. Making weight is all
that matters and the delicacies that come out of LeClerc's kitchen
wouldn't help that cause.
   ``They have joked about it,'' LeClerc says of the wrestlers he
coached at Troy High School last season. ``They would make comments
like, `Are you going to make us something to eat after practice,
coach?'''
   As a macho sport, wrestling seems to have little in common with
catering.
   But LeClerc points to the precision of preparing a special food
dish and the technique needed to successfully perform a difficult
wrestling move.
   LeClerc's business, called Charmont, is busier than ever these
days. With wrestling season coming, the gas on the stove will be
turned down as the heat on the mat is turned up.
   LeClerc is in his first season as head coach at Southfield High
School, where the wrestling program has been lackluster in recent
years.
   When athletic director Art Carinci heard LeClerc was a caterer,
he was pleased.
   ``My reaction was, `That sounds great. He could cater our sports
banquet,''' Carinci says.
   But Carinci says LeClerc was hired for his wrestling, not his
culinary, credentials. After the job was posted among teachers and
staff, Carinci interviewed and hired LeClerc, whose catering
business is in nearby Royal Oak, Mich.
   LeClerc has been wrestling since kindergarten; his kitchen career
began at 13 when he weighed dough at a pizza parlor owned by a
family friend. Then came the sauce. Later, he experimented with
homemade soups at the Maple House restaurant.
   LeClerc has worked in other restaurants and, in 1987, he received
an associate degree in culinary arts.
   ``It was realizing that I had a talent early,'' LeClerc says.
``There were certain things I could do that other people in the
restaurant who were much older and more experienced couldn't do.''
   While he has plenty of wedding and church business right now,
LeClerc is probably two years away from opening his own kitchen.
When that happens, he has a new name in mind, ``What Dreams Are Made
Of.''
   LeClerc says he sees his kitchen vocation as helping his coaching
job.
   ``Maybe if I did do the sports banquet and the basketball coach
liked the food, he'd give up the gym one or two days a week so the
wrestling team could use it,'' he says.
   LeClerc says he knows of no colleagues who cook at all, let alone
to make a living. The federal government doesn't either.
   ``We keep track of people who have two jobs but we kind of keep a
little more in the mainstream,'' says Kathryn Hoyle, a spokeswoman
for the U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881121-0254 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-88 0212EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Food:RockefellerCenter     11-21 0772</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Food: Rockefeller Center,0789</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>FOOD: Rockefeller Center</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE SCHROEDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With more than 25,000 restaurants within its
borders, New York City might well be considered the culinary
crossroads of the world.
   Diners can choose from what the New York Convention and Visitors
Bureau describes as a ``cornucopia of international cuisines,''
including Brazilian, Cajun, Chinese, French, German, Greek, Indian,
Italian, Japanese, Mexican, Russian, Spanish, Thai or Vietnamese
specialties.
   But at Rockefeller Center, in the very heart of Manhattan,
patrons also might encounter such attractions as ``Breakfast at the
O.K. Corral,'' lunch selections from ``The Firefighter's Cookbook,''
or a dinner menu built around recipes borrowed from the tasty meals
served to Ringling Brothers and Barnum & Bailey circus performers.
   Such offbeat items are most often seen on the menus of the
American Festival Cafe, one of three restaurants wrapped around the
famed ice-skating rink (which becomes an open air garden cafe during
the warm weather season).
   The other two eateries are the elegant Sea Grill, which
specializes in seafood, and Savories, a casual restaurant geared to
speedy service and takeout delectables. The emphasis at all three is
on all-American dining. The wine list is strictly domestic and the
beer choices feature regional American brews.
   Customers at the American Festival when the ``O.K. Corral''
breakfast was offered in 1986 found such imaginative menu offerings
as apples baked in bourbon, eggs scrambled with frizzled beef jerky,
oatmeal flapjacks with molasses-stewed prunes and Judge Roy Bean's
beans.
   Ruth Epstein, who has helped plan and promote such
off-the-beaten-track themes since the restaurant opened four years
ago, explains how beans usually were prepared in the judge's ``Wild
West'' days:
   ``By the time the pale pink beans called Arizona strawberries had
cooked all night in their covering of bourbon, onions, molasses,
salt pork and spices, the bourbon's alcohol had entirely evaporated,
leaving behind only the mellow smoky flavor of Kentucky's pride as a
reminder of the previous evening's carouse.''
   According to Miss Epstein, public relations consultant for
Restaurant Associates, which operates the three eateries, adopting
new themes and changing menus several times a year is not a simple
task _ especially when the restaurant serves about 450,000 meals
annually, matching the combined total of 450,000 meals served at the
other two restaurants.
   ``It's not the easiest thing in the world to do with a
restaurant, because change _ as it is for people _ is difficult for
restaurants. You have to extend yourself to change rather than keep
on doing the same thing,'' she explains.
   ``Changing a menu requires an extraordinary pulling together of a
very large team. Everybody has to cooperate when you have a
change...When I have an idea _ sometimes even supplying recipes for
them _ the chef is always there because the cooking people are
involved from the beginning.
   ``There's also the purchasing and marketing departments, and the
liquor buyers, and so on. Then when the new menu is set and tested
and ready to be printed on paper it involves everybody in the
restaurant who serves it.
   ``There are meetings by our management staff to teach people who
serve it what it is, how it looks, how it tastes, how it's served.''
   When ``firehouse cooking'' was the theme early last year, the
program was billed as a tribute to America's firehouse chefs. All of
the recipes were created by firefighters and most were taken from
John Sineno's best-selling ``The Firefighter's Cookbook.''
   During the testing of the chef's cooking of recipes being
considered for the menu, the Firefighters Tasting Panel discovered
something new, Miss Epstein recalls.
   As she explained in the American Festival newsletter:
   ``They pointed out that there must be some mistake in the
manicotti _ delicious as it was (and please pass some more) theirs
had never had a sauce like that. It took our forensic team some time
to determine that two recipes had inadvertently been combined and
that Danny Prince's manicotti had been topped with a sauce based on
his artichoke pie. Thus are great dishes born.''
   It was named ``Manicotti with Accidental Sauce'' and was the
first dish to earn a place on the firehouse cooking menu.
   The circus theme featured a menu recalling the days when Ringling
Brothers and company played under canvas and traveled on a train a
hundred cars long, carrying some 1,400 people, lions, tigers and
elephants.
   The fun menu, ``The Cooking of the Circus Stars,'' was printed in
red, white and blue and borrowed the traditional hyperbole of circus
promotions. It declared the offerings as ``The Most Gorgeous and
Princely Spectacle of Monumental Magnificence Ever Beforked.''

</TEXT>
</DOC>
