<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Food:WineBooks     11-21 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Food: Wine Books,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>FOOD: Wine Books</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANITA ISSEN MIZNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>For The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A selection of new books exploring the routes, and roots, of wine:
   _ ``The New Frank Schoonmaker Encyclopedia of Wine,'' revised and
expanded by Alexis Bespaloff'' (Morrow, $22.95).
   There are 400 new entries and maps in this reference book by a
highly-regarded wine journalist and connoisseur, with 50 pages of
appendixes relating to wine production, vineyards, and wine and food
suggestions. Information is listed alphabetically and concisely.
   _ ``Notes on a California Cellarbook,'' by Bob Thompson
(BeechTree, $19.95).
   An in-depth visit to Thompson's personal cellar choices, most
from older, established wineries, with insights into the California
wine industry and old and new wines.
   _ ``American Vineyards,'' by Barbara Ensrud (Stewart, Tabori &
Chang, $35).
   The wine columnist and author reports on the yesterday, today and
tomorrow of American wines and finds the future is bright for the
still young industry. Charles Dorris' museum-quality photographs
take the reader along on their travels to the wineries.
   _ ``The 1989 Great American Vineyards,'' photography by Gale
Gleason (Prince St. Editions, $14.95).
   This is the third edition of photographer Gale Gleason's travels
around America's vineyards, featuring 52 award-winning wineries in
the datebook that is subtitled ``A Weekly Tour of America's
Wineries.'' It includes recipes from 10 leading chefs, originally
created for the American Institute of Wine and Food.
   _ ``Wines of the Rhone Valley and Provence,'' by Robert M. Parker
Jr. (Simon & Schuster, $22.95).
   Parker believes that Rhone Valley wines are among France's best,
yet least-known values. He also covers the seven wine districts of
Provence, with classifications, tasting notes and recommendations
for visitors to wineries in both areas.
   _ A new 1988-89 soft-cover edition of ``The Wine Spectators Wine
Country Guide to California,'' a directory of the state's wineries,
wine country restaurants and lodgings, has been published by The
Wine Spectator magazine.
   Nine regional maps pinpoint winery locations, with a state map
linking the regions to major highways.
</TEXT>
