<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Food:Survey     11-21 0133</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Food: Survey,0135</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>FOOD: Survey</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Chicken, fish and fresh vegetables rated the most healthy among
foods in a survey of adult consumer habits, and more people consider
pizza very good for you than they do pork.
   The results come from a 1987 Yankelovich Monitor Report, a
national sampling survey reported in Successful Farming magazine.
   Chicken was the meat respondents were most likely to eat fairly
regularly, the choice of 84 percent. Twenty percent rated beef as
``very good for you,'' 13 percent felt that way about pizza,
followed by coffee (10 percent) and pork.
   Of the adults sampled, 65 percent said they were eating the same
amount of beef they did a year previous, 26 percent said they were
eating less and 8 percent responded more.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
