<DOCNO> AP881121-0265 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-88 0216EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Food:SpecialtyProduce     11-21 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Food: Specialty Produce,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>FOOD: Specialty Produce</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supermarket produce counters are taking on a
special look these days, with bean sprouts, bok choy, guava and
other exotic items catching the eye of food shoppers, says an
Agriculture Department economist.
   ``Specialty fruit and vegetable displays form a fundamental part
of the new up-scale image of many produce sections,'' says Catherine
Greene of the department's Economic Research Service.
   Rising demand for specialty produce is in line with a general
increase in fruit and vegetable consumption, she says. On the
average, Americans consumed 427 pounds of fruits and vegetables last
year, up 12 percent since 1972. That is a farm weight equivalent
before trimming, processing and after-harvest losses, she says.
   Greene, writing in the agency's National Food Review, said there
are a number of reasons.
   ``Americans have become more health conscious, eating lots of
fruits and vegetables as part of a well-balanced diet,'' she said.
``Consequently, we want a huge selection of produce.''
   Further, Americans travel more frequently than they used to, and
many want ``foreign'' foods when they return home.
   ``Unusual fruits and vegetables are appearing on restaurant
menus,'' Greene said. ``Also influencing our diets are recent
immigrants from the Caribbean, Central America and Southeast Asia
who have brought their native foods with them.''
   A survey conducted for a trade journal, The Packer, showed the
most frequently tried specialty fresh vegetables were alfalfa and
bean sprouts, followed by snow peas, pearl onions, parsnips, leeks,
baby vegetables, Chinese cabbage and shallots.
   Moreover, about a third of those surveyed also had seen or heard
of less widely known specialty vegetables such as Belgian endive,
bok choy, celeriac, daikon, kohlrabi, parsley root and Jerusalem
artichoke.
   The most frequently tried specialty fresh fruits, in order, were
pomegranates, persimmons, kumquats, quince and guavas.
   Additionally, at least a third of those surveyed had seen or
heard of breadfuit, passion fruit, plantains, prickly pear and red
bananas. But some fruits were nearly unkown: Asian pears,
carambolas, cherimoyas, sapotes, radiccho and rappini.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881121-0266 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-88 0217EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Food:ZagatRankings     11-21 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Food: Zagat Rankings,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>FOOD: Zagat Rankings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Four Seasons, the handsome hangout of the
rich and powerful, has edged longtime leader Lutece as New Yorkers'
favorite restaurant, according to the 1989 Zagat Survey.
   The elegant walnut-paneled restaurant in the Seagram Building
garnered the most points when the Zagat Survey asked some 3,500
respondents to list their five favorite restaurants.
   Lutece, the classic French restaurant that had ruled Zagat's
roost for 10 years, slipped to second, followed by La Cote Basque,
Le Bernardin and Chanterelle.
   But that's the popularity contest, with The Four Seasons getting
about 300 more mentions than the smaller Lutece.
   ``It's a combination _ the great architecture of Philip Johnson,
it's the most professionally run restaurant I know of, and the food
is really good,'' said Tim Zagat, editor of the survey, about The
Four Seasons.
   As for the former king, ``Lutece is still a fantastic restaurant,
but it has competition,'' he said.
   ``Also, people's expectations of Lutece are so unbelievably high
that there is a certain amount of disappointment, especially when
you have to make a reservation 30 days in advance.''
   When it comes to food rankings, Chanterelle and Lutece were in a
virtual tie, followed by La Cote Basque, Le Bernardin and Lafayette.
The Four Seasons ranked ninth.
   For decor, the winner is a newcomer of sorts _ the refurbished
Rainbow Room atop the RCA Building, which survey participants rated
slightly ahead of Windows on the World, Tavern on the Green and
World Yacht Enterprises, a restaurant on a yacht on the Hudson River.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881121-0267 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-88 0217EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Food:Briefs     11-21 0704</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Food: Briefs,0746</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>FOOD: Briefs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   California's 650 wineries account for about 70 percent of annual
sales and 90 percent of wine production in the United Sttes.
   California started the five-year wine cooler boom, and as the
market went flat, consumers of that white-wine-and-fruit-juice blend
moved up to white wine alone, then the more complex white zinfandel.
   The premium boom was on.
   California's success encouraged winegrape growing far and wide in
the nation, and currently 43 states are making their own wine.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Pilsner-style beer is a light, golden-colored beer named for the
place that made it famous: Pilsen, Czechoslovakia, where they have
been brewing since 1292 when King Wenceslaus granted them the right
to make and sell beer.
   The Pilsner Urquell Brewery today produces about 625,000 barrels
a year, after aging three months in cellars underneath the town of
Pilsen, lagered in oak barrels.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   To some, the island of Montserrat is known as the Emerald Isle of
the Caribbean, harking back to the 1600s, when Irish sailors first
visited. That historical connection comes back in Emmets banana and
cream liqueur, a combination of Irish dairy cream, Irish whiskey and
banana liqueur.
   The drink is imported and marketed by ``21'' Brands Inc. of New
York.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Waiters on Wheels Inc., a San Francisco gourmet delivery service,
offers kung pao squid, veal piccata, quesadilla ranchera and meat
loaf among its entrees.
   Founded by two Greek immigrants, the multi-restaurant delivery
service took what for many takeout eaters was a choice of pizza or
Chinese food, and added French wine, steaks, pasta dishes and an
array of desserts.
   ``We wanted people in the city the chance to not have to eat
pizza,'' said co-founder Takis Zarikos. ``We wanted to offer them
nice, gourmet food.''
   There are similar companies in other cities, such as Chicago and
Los Angeles.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Growing Gourmet is the name of a new line of microwave dinners
aimed at children from age 9 months to 3{ years _ and at busy
working parents.
   It was started in San Francisco by Dave and Linda Shank, both 39,
because, they said, it worked so well for them.
   When Dave Jr. was 1 year old, his mother decided to return to
work as a flight attendant. Knowing she would be gone for week-long
stretches, Mrs. Shank left her husband armed with homemade
casseroles divided into small containers or margarine tubs for
storage in the freezer.
   ``With a microwave, it was really a godsend,'' Shank recalled.
   Among the Growing Gourmet meals for toddlers: chicken vegetable
rice, beef vegetable barley and turkey vegetable pastina. The
packages of two 5.5-ounce servings sell from $2.39 to $2.69.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Premium wine sales in the United States rose 21 percent last
year, accounting for 20 percent of sales and 40 percent of revenues,
according to John Fitzgerald, director of the Texas Wine Marketing
Institute.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   A quarter-pound hamburger, large order of fries and a medium-size
soft drink costs $2.92 in Cincinnati, but $6.25 in Paris, according
to a fast food survey by Runzheimer International, a consulting firm
that specializes in travel and living costs.
   The company found the same fast food meal in New York was $3.90
and $1.81 in Hong Kong.
   Prices were gathered during the first quarter of 1988 using March
1988 exchange rates, Runzheimer said.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   One ounce of ground black pepper is enough to season 1,440 fried
eggs, or enough to sprinkle two breakfast eggs seven days a week for
two years, says the American Spice Trade Association.
   An association newsletter also noted that the three leading
spices in tonnage for 1987 were mustard seed, sesame seed, and
pepper.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The top fruit choice among teen-agers 15 years ago?
   Apples, according to a survey of teen eating habits by MRCA
Information Services, which specializes in gathering and analyzing
marketing information.
   Today's fruit choice? Still, apples.
   Overall, according to the survey, teen-agers eat 35 percent less
fruit now than they did 15 years ago, including a 23 percent drop in
eating apples. Grapes increased by 175 percent in annual per capital
eatings, the survey reported.
   The survey was based on four nationally representative samples of
more than 3,000 teens in 2,000 U.S. households.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
