<DOCNO> AP881121-0268 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-88 0711EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   11-21 0543</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0567</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A special committee considering the unprecedented
multibillion-dollar buyout bids for food and tobacco giant RJR
Nabisco Inc. has disclosed three new or sweetened offers and
extended the deadline for further proposals.
   Proposals now being considered by the committee include sweetened
offers from groups led by RJR management and by the buyout firm
Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co., plus a new, tentative proposal from a
group led by the investment firm First Boston Corp. to buy the
company's tobacco business separately and sell its food businesses.
   Not only did the offers disclosed Sunday top all previous bids,
which were in the $20 billion range, but the committee indicated its
decision to hold the bidding open could mean even higher offers may
emerge.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest points paid to refinance a home
mortgage may not be deducted fully in the year the loan is obtained,
the U.S. Tax Court ruled.
   The court's decision Friday upheld the position taken by the
Internal Revenue Service and means that points must be written off
over the life of a home loan.
   The ruling has no effect on points that must be paid to secure a
loan that is used directly to buy or improve a home.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 30 investors who charged they lost
millions of dollars because of unauthorized high-risk investments by
Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. have settled with the brokerage firm,
officials said.
   The out-of-court settlement announced Friday came shortly after
the resignation of the manager of Dean Witter's Boston office, who
along with a broker and the firm was the target of a lawsuit by a
group of 39 investors.
   Complaints against two other firms, Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
and Merrill Lynch & Co., are pending.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Private and public spending on health increased
nearly 10 percent in 1987 and consumed a record share of the
nation's total economic output, according to a federal report.
   The $500.3 billion spent on health amounted to $1,987 per man,
woman and child and represented 11.1 percent of the gross national
product, according to a report issued Friday by the Health Care
Financing Administration.
   By contrast, health expenditures consumed only 9.1 percent of GNP
in 1980 and 10.7 percent in 1986.
  
