<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Edges Up Against Yen, Share Prices Continue Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar inched up against the Japanese yen
today in cautious trading following last week's concerted central
bank interventions, while share prices continued to rise on the
Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 122.52 yen, up 0.12 yen from Friday's close
of 122.40 yen. Opening at 122.40 yen, the currency moved within a
tight range of 122.37 yen to 122.60 yen.
   ``The dollar-yen rate didn't move very much today mainly because
market players have become extremely cautious after the intervention
by world's major central banks Thursday and Friday,'' said a dealer
with Mitsubishi Bank, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   ``Investors were selling the dollar less, but very few people
were interested in buying the currency,'' he said, adding that it
was not dollar-buying interest that saved the dollar from falling
further but cautiousness over the central bank intervention.
   Dealers said the Bank of Japan did not intervene today.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which gained 103.39 points to
close at a record high of 29,180.20 Friday, added 104.06 points or
0.36 percent to finish at a new record of 29,284.26. The Nikkei rose
119.00 points shortly after the market opened, and managed to
maintain the gain, rising for the seventh straight session since
Nov. 11.
   ``Financial issues attracted participants largely because of the
yen's strength against the dollar,'' said a dealer with Nomura
Securities, Japan's largest brokerage. ``But on the other hand, many
market players were quite afraid that share prices were getting too
high,'' the dealer said, asking he not be identified.
   In moderate trading, volume was estimated at 850 million shares.
</TEXT>
