<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold, 1st Ld-Writethru,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Little Changed</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: CORRECTS to show Canadian dollar down in 8th graf</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was mixed and trading in a narrow range
in Europe today, with the fear of central bank intervention
dampening business, foreign currency dealers said. Gold prices were
little changed.
   Traders in Italy said the market remains bearish about the
dollar's near-term propects. But they said the market also appears
determined to send President-elect George Bush a clear warning that
something must be done quickly to cut the U.S. trade deficit and
federal government spending.
   ``The market doesn't want to wait until Jan. 20,'' when Bush is
inaugurated, said one trader in Milan.
   Most of the world's major central banks bought dollars in several
rounds of coordinated interventions Thursday and Friday, halting a
rapid decline in the U.S. currency.
   ``The interventions of the past days have boosted the dollar only
temporarily, but caution is still recommended,'' said the chief
dealer at a Frankfurt bank.
   ``If one believes that the dollar will weaken, the central banks
are likely to come in again.''
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.12 yen to a closing 122.52. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 122.50 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Friday's
rates, included: 1.7362 West German marks, up from 1.7360; 1.4585
Swiss francs, unchanged; 5.9315 French francs, down from 5.9340;
1.9575 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9610; 1,290.65 Italian lire, down
from 1,293.75; 1.2145 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2343.
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.8150, compared with
$1.8160 Friday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $416.75 a troy ounce,
down from $417.75 bid late Friday. At midmorning Monday, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $416.60.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $416.50, down from $417.80 bid late
Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 33 cents to close at a bid
$418.79.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.11 a troy ounce,
up from Friday's $6.09.
</TEXT>
