<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-88 0947EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-TobaccoMarket     11-21 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tobacco Market,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tobacco: Marketing Officials Optimistic As Burley Season Opens</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. (AP) _ Despite a third straight year of
drought, officials say the burley tobacco going to market today will
be larger and higher in quality than last year's crop.
   The market opens this week in North Carolina and seven other
states, and marketing officials are cautiously predicting that
farmers will have a better selling season this year than last year.
   ``I think the price average will be up, but that will mainly be
because of the higher quality,'' said Joey Coleman, who operates the
two tobacco warehouses in Boone with his father.
   Last year, North Carolina burley prices averaged $150.87 per
hundred pounds, down from the previous season's average of $156.01.
   This season's federal price support average will be $1.50 a
pound, up by slightly more than 1 cent. By grades, the support will
range from 98 cents to $1.63, the same as last season.
   ``It's looking a lot better than it did in July before the rains
came,'' said Ed French of the Federal-State Market News Service in
Lexington, Ky.
   A larger crop is expected this year because of more planted
acreage and slightly higher yields, he said.
   The Nov. 1 crop survey estimates the crop at 538.9 million pounds
for the eight-state burley belt, up from last year's 486.6 million
pounds. Yields are projected at 2,043 pounds an acre, up from 1,943
pounds last year.
   North Carolina's burley crop is expected to total 15.3 million
pounds, up from 14.1 million last year. Yields are projected at
1,800 pounds an acre, slightly more than last year's 1,785 pounds.
   Kentucky produces more than half the total crop. Burley tobacco
is also grown in Virginia, Tennessee, West Virginia, Indiana, Ohio
and Missouri.
   French said it would be difficult to estimate whether demand for
the burley crop would be as strong as for this year's flue-cured
tobacco crop.
   ``Everyone seems to be optimistic,'' he said. But, he added, such
optimism can fade quickly if farmers are disappointed with prices on
opening day.
   Mary Jo Hicks, who is operating both tobacco warehouses in West
Jefferson this season, said she is encouraged by the favorable
comments from government graders and a couple of buyers who watched
farmers bring in tobacco last week.
   ``They are looking at it as a very desirable crop,'' she said.
   In North Carolina, sales will open today at markets in West
Jefferson and Asheville, with the Boone market beginning sales
Tuesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
