<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet10am     11-21 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 10am,0298</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices slumped today amid persistent
worries about the dollar and interest rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 11.91 to 2,050.50
in the first half hour of trading.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by more than 2 to 1 in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 241 up, 513
down and 398 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 15.86 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   After falling sharply since the election early this month, the
dollar steadied late last week as central banks of the
industrialized countries intervened to support it.
   But analysts said many investors remained skeptical that the
dollar would be able to continue strengthening on its own.
   At the same time, brokers said, many participants were taking a
gloomy view of the market outlook, in part because of the
competitive allure of short-term interest-bearing investments
sporting yields of close to 8 percent.
   Intel tumbled 3{ to 19| in the over-the-counter market. Late
Friday the company said its revenues and earnings for the fourth
quarter would fall short of third-quarter levels because of soft
orders for its 80386 microprocessor chip.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
dropped .75 to 149.43. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was up .19 at 286.86.
   On Friday the Dow Jones industrial average rose 9.96 to 2,062.41,
trimming its loss for the week to 4.62 points.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 8 to 5 on the
NYSE, with 840 up, 536 down and 555 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 119.32 million shares, against 141.28
million in the previous session.
</TEXT>
