<1ST_LINE>r f PM-LTV-Bankruptcy     11-21 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-LTV-Bankruptcy,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>LTV To Ask For Eighth Extension In Reorganization Efforts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   LTV Corp., which filed for Chapter 11 protection
from creditors in July 1986, plans to ask a U.S. Bankruptcy Court to
grant an eighth extension to give it time to work out a
reorganization proposal, company officials said.
   In response to the proposed request, LTV creditors have told the
court they reject the company's reorganization plan and will agree
to only one more extension, Joel Zweibel, attorney representing bank
creditors of the aerospace division, told the Dallas Times Herald.
   Attorneys for creditors of the parent company declined to comment.
   LTV faces a growing number of dissenting creditors who claim its
original proposal for settlement is unacceptable or are unhappy with
the length of negotiations.
   Aerospace creditors on Thursday renewed protests to LTV's Nov. 7
request for extension and asked the court for the right to present a
separate reorganization proposal.
   ``The talks are totally stalled. There is no progress, no
movement at all,'' said Zweibel.
   LTV has argued it needs time to work out the complex case, which
involves some 32,000 creditors of the aerospace and steel
conglomerate.
   LTV has ``made very substantial progress,'' said spokesman Chuck
Palmer. ``You would hardly expect 32,000 claims to be resolved in
such a short time.''
   Officials said the extension requestion could come today.
</TEXT>
