<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-88 1055EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-EconomicForecast     11-21 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Economic Forecast,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bank of America says Economy Will Grow in 1989</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's economy will grow for the
seventh straight year in 1989, despite a federal budget deficit that
will swell to $170 billion, according to a Bank of America study
released on Monday.
   The bank's 1989 U.S. Economic Outlook said there will be no
recession, even though economic growth will slow to 2.7 percent from
1988's 3.8 percent.
   ``The annual growth rate, however, masks weaknesses in the
economy, which will become evident in the last half of 1989,'' said
John Wilson, the bank's chief economist.
   After a strong growth rate in the first quarter, the result of
bouncing back from the 1988 drought, ``economic growth will slow to
under 2 percent for the remainder of the year,'' the study said.
   ``The most serious economic policy challenge that the Bush
administration will face is the federal budget deficit, even though
both the politicians and the general public are suffering from
battle fatigue on this issue,'' said Wilson.
   Inflation will increase to 4.9 percent from 4.1 percent in 1988
while the unemployment rate will be around 5.5 percent next year.
   Wage gains are expected to increase an average of 4.3 percent
compared to 3.3 percent, the forecast said. As a result, consumer
prices will be 0.7 of a percentage point higher in 1989 due to wage
pressures.
</TEXT>
