<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Sun-TimesTalks 1stLd-Writethru f0014 11-21 0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sun-Times Talks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0014,0555</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Sides Meet in Last-Minute Effort to Avert Strike</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 13 new grafs to UPDATE with last-minute
negotiations, strike deadline of 2:30 p.m. set; Picks up 7th graf
pvs, ``He said the...'' SUBS last graf with 2 new grafs to UPDATE
with circulation information.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiations between the Chicago Sun-Times and its
unionized editorial employees resumed this morning, hours before a
threatened walkout by the writers, editors, photographers and
support staff.
   A strike deadline of 2:30 p.m. CST today was set by the
negotiating committee of Chicago Newspaper Guild Local 71, though
the deadline could be changed, said Daniel Lehman, the newspaper's
religion writer and a union spokesman.
   Talks resumed at 9 a.m., said Sun-Times spokesman Michael Soll.
   But he added that ``at this time, it looks like 2:30 would be as
far as we can go.''
   Soll said newspaper negotiators were willing to meet around the
clock, and that he hoped the talks would be fruitful.
   ``There appears to be much less anguish and much more hope''
among negotiators on both sides, he said. Salary remained the main
sticking point.
   The Sun-Times' negotiators ``have not yet made their final
offer,'' Soll said, adding he expected that offer to be made at
today's meeting.
   Union leaders met late Sunday night and agreed to accept the
company proposal for a bargaining session today.
   ``We'll keep negotiating until we have a settlement or until we
hit the strike deadline, and then we're out of there,'' said Shane
Gericke, a copy editor and member of the negotiating committee for
the union, which represents 250 reporters, editors, photographers
and support staff.
   ``We decided to give it every shot,'' he said.
   A strike by Sun-Times editorial workers would be the first in the
newspaper's 40-year history.
   Soll said management did not want a strike, but is ``fully
prepared to produce a paper'' using company executives, non-union
editors and outside writers.
   He said the newspaper would continue putting out its three daily
editions.
   Union members have been working without a contract since June 1.
   As the strike deadline approached, guild unit chairman Thomas
Gibbons said the union would walk out if the company continued to
refuse to offer a pay raise.
   The guild has been seeking a 19.5 percent pay raise over three
years, while management's latest proposal was for a 3 percent salary
cut for 18 months, followed by a restoration of current pay levels
for the remainder of the three-year pact, Gibbons said.
   ``We've got to have pay raises in the contract for this to be
settled,'' he said.
   In addition, Gibbons said, differences remained over management
proposals to cut night differential for workers by 40 percent and
exempt eight senior editorial staffers from union jurisdiction.
   Soll said ``the paper is healthy financially'' but must control
its costs to remain competitive with the larger Chicago Tribune,
which has an estimated circulation of 765,000 daily and 1.117
million Sunday.
   The Sun-Times, whose circulation is estimated at 605,000 daily
and 614,000 on Sunday, was purchased from Australian media baron
Rupert Murdoch for $145 million in June 1986 by a group of investors
led by the New York investment firm Adler & Shaykin.
</TEXT>
