<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grain and soybeans were mixed
early in today's session on the Chicago Board of Trade in light,
pre-Thanksgiving trading.
   ``We might already be entering a holiday-type market: thin trade,
quiet markets, light volume,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader with
Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   Most soybean futures were fractionally higher on technical
factors but reports of weekend rain in the soybean regions of
Argentina and Brazil were keeping a rein on the rally, analysts said.
   Grain prices were mostly lower with little fresh news to pull
prices one way or the other.
   In early trading, wheat was unchanged to 1 cent lower with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.10\ a bushel; corn was 1\
cents lower to } cent higher with December at $2.58 a bushel; oats
were } cent lower to { cent higher with December at $2 a bushel;
soybeans were \ cent lower to 1{ cents higher with January at $7.31{
a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly lower in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .25 cent lower to .27 cent higher with December
at 72.62 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .35 cent
lower with January at 81.65 cents a pound; live hogs were .35 cent
lower to .10 cent higher with December at 40.25 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .02 cent to .35 cent lower with February at
42.90 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures closed lower on Friday.
</TEXT>
