<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market suffered a broad setback today
amid persistent worries about the dollar and interest rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 17.42 to 2,044.99
by noontime on Wall Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by more than 3 to 1 in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 334 up, 1,014
down and 461 unchanged.
   After falling sharply since the election early this month, the
dollar steadied late last week as central banks of the
industrialized countries intervened to support it.
   But analysts said many investors remained skeptical that the
dollar would be able to continue strengthening on its own. Indeed,
it fell today against leading foreign currencies.
   At the same time, brokers said, many participants were taking a
gloomy view of the market outlook, in part because of the
competitive allure of short-term interest-bearing investments
sporting yields of close to 8 percent.
   RJR Nabisco climbed 2] to 86]. Directors extended until Nov. 29
the bidding competition to acquire the company.
   Losers among the blue chips included International Business
Machines, down 1[ at 114|; Exxon, down | at 41{; General Electric,
down { at 43], and American Telephone & Telegraph, down ] at 27\.
   Intel tumbled 3| to 19{ in the over-the-counter market. Late
Friday the company said its revenues and earnings for the fourth
quarter would fall short of third-quarter levels because of soft
orders for its 80386 microprocessor chip.
   Other semiconductor issues followed Intel lower. Motorola dropped
~ to 36| and National Semiconductor ] to 8[.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks lost
1.17 to 149.01. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down .46 at 286.21.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 56.28 million shares at noontime,
against 53.49 million at the same point Friday.
