<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Britain-Stocks 1stLd-Writethru   11-21 0170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0177</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shares Dip On London Market</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates thruout with closing figures</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices slid Monday on the London Stock
Exchange as market makers slashed prices in a fruitless bid to
attract buyers.
   The Financial Times index of 100 leading shares finished down
12.3 points, or 0.67 percent, at 1,811.1. The narrower Financial
Times 30-share index was off 8.9 points at 1480.1.
   Volume fell to 359.4 million shares from 567.3 million shares
Friday.
   Dealers cited a decline in the dollar as one reason traders were
wary about committing new funds to the market.
   ``There's a tremulous feeling that no one wants to commit a drop
of funds to this market with the latent uncertainty out there,
especially from the U.S.,'' one dealer said.
   Analysts said the market lacked direction because participants
were sitting out the session in anticipation of this week's U.S.
Thanksgiving holiday and Friday's release of British trade data for
October.
   The Financial Times 500 share index fell 6.43 to 1,031.71.
</TEXT>
