<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-88 1434EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     11-21 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dollar-Gold,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls On Bush Remarks About Deficit, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: An AMs version planned by 5:30 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar fell against all major currencies
in European trading Monday amid continued anxiety about the American
budget deficit. Gold prices declined.
   Currency dealers said the dollar was hurt by remarks from
President-elect George Bush reaffirming that he won't raise taxes to
narrow the huge gap. At issue is whether Bush and the
Democratic-controlled U.S. Congress can agree on spending cuts
needed to trim the deficit.
   Dealers also reported a lack of central-bank intervention Monday
to prop up the dollar's exchange rate as there had been last week.
One trader said the dollar cannot maintain its current exchange
rates without central bank buying.
   The Canadian dollar gained more than two cents in London against
the U.S. dollar on the heels of Saturday's opinion polls predicting
victory in Monday's Canadian general election for Prime Minister
Brian Mulroney's Conservatives.
   In London late Monday, one British pound cost $1.8175, more
expensive for buyers than Friday's late $1.8160.
   Other late rates compared with late rates Friday: 1.7305 West
German marks, down from 1.7360; 1.4575 Swiss francs, down from
1.4585; 5.9305 French francs, down from 5.9340; 1.9550 Dutch
guilders, down from 1.9610; 1,288.62 Italian lire, down from
1,293.75; and 1.2117 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2343.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begains, the dollar closed at 122.52 Japanese yen, up from 122.40
late Friday. But in late London trading the dollar fell lower to
122.20 yen.
   Gold bullion closed in London, the major European market, at
$416.75 a troy ounce, down from $417.75 bid late Friday. The late
price in Zurich was $416.50 an ounce, down from $417.80.
   Gold closed in Hong Kong at $418.79 an ounce, down from $419.12.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at a bid $6.04 a troy ounce,
down from $6.09.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881121-0297 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-88 1527EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Armco-Japanese     11-21 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Armco-Japanese,0510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan Steelmaker Buying Part of Armco Steel Division</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIDDLETOWN, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armco Inc. and a major Japanese
steelmaker Monday announced their intention to form a joint venture
to operate Armco's Eastern Steel Division.
   Robert Boni, Armco's chairman and chief executive officer, said
Armco and Kawasaki Steel Corp. reached agreement in principle to
form the venture to jointly manage and operate the Middletown-based
Eastern Steel Division, which includes Armco's steel mills in
Middletown and in Ashland, Ky.
   The division employs 13,800 people, has annual sales of about
$1.5 billion and annual production capacity of approximately 3.5
million tons of steel.
   The proposed terms of the joint venture provide for Kawasaki to
purchase 40 percent of Armco's Eastern Steel Division for about $350
million with Armco retaining the rest.
   Language in the agreement allows for the two companies to
negotiate an increase in Kawasaki's investment in the venture up to
a maximum of 50 percent, officials said.
   The proposed venture would assume the debts and employee benefit
obligations related to the division's operation.
   Boni said the joint venture would provide new steelmaking
technology for Armco's carbon steel business, would give the
Japanese steelmaker a stake in a major U.S. steel company and would
allow the two firms to better serve Japanese automakers in the
United States.
   ``We are enthusiastic about the prospects for this venture
because it would allow us to add some of the world's best new
technology to our already announced plans to modernize and improve
our two largest flat-rolled carbon steel plants,'' Boni said in a
statement.
   The modernization plan includes quality and productivity
improvements at both Middletown and Ashland. Eastern Steel makes a
broad range of carbon flat-rolled steels for the automotive,
appliance and construction markets.
   Boni said the proposed joint venture is part of Armco's long-term
growth strategy. He said, ``The product and technology fit between
the two companies will provide a foundation for growth that will
strengthen Armco, benefit Kawasaki and, most importantly, better
serve all our customers.''
   No date was projected for completion of the agreement, but Armco
officials said the two firms will complete negotiations and sign a
formal agreement as soon as possible. The contract is subject to
approval by the boards of directors of both companies.
   Armco, which maintains corporate headquarters in Parsippany,
N.J., produces carbon, electrical and stainless steels, steel
products and oilfield machinery and equipment and is in the property
and casualty insurance business.
   Kawasaki is the third largest steel producer in Japan. Like
Armco, it is a world leader in the technology of carbon and coated
steels. The company, with about 27,000 employees, has two major
steel plants in Japan and a modern research center with some 1,300
scientists and technicians. The firm has also recently diversified
into semi-conductors, telecommunications, advanced materials and
high performance ceramics.
   The firm also is part-owner of California Steel Industries Inc.,
based in Los Angeles. Kawasaki had 1986 sales totaling about $6.4
billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
