<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0228</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Rebound; Grains Close Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices rebounded Monday in
afternoon trading to close sharply higher on the Chicago Board of
Trade.
   Corn finished mostly higher while wheat prices fell.
   The turnaround in soybean prices followed steep daily declines in
that market in six of the seven previous trading sessions. Monday's
rally was due largely to profit-taking by speculators who had sold
contracts in earlier sessions in hopes of buying them back at lower
prices, analysts said.
   ``The markets were oversold, overdone, overdue for a rally and it
finally came today in all the pits except wheat,'' said Victor
Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   The soybean market led the rally but wheat did not participate
because of disappointment over the failure so far of U.S. and Soviet
negotiators to work out a new long-term grain sales agreement, he
said.
   At the close, wheat was \ cent to 3 cents lower with the contract
for delivery in December at $4.08 a bushel; corn was 1\ cents lower
to 3 cents higher with December at $2.61\ a bushel; oats were 2{
cents to 5{ cents higher with December at $2.06 a bushel; soybeans
were { cent to 15 cents higher with January at $7.46 a bushel.
