<1ST_LINE>u f AM-OilPrices     11-21 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oil Prices,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Edge Higher, Gasoline Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude oil prices edged higher Monday in light
trading as the oil market awaited news on the prospects for a new
OPEC production agreement.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, contracts for January
delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude, rose
7 cents from Friday's close to settle at $12.98 per 42-gallon barrel.
   Among refined products, the December contract for heating oil
gained 0.71 cent to 43.47 cents a gallon, while the December
contract for unleaded gasoline lost 1.33 cents to 44.32 cents a
gallon.
   Traders attributed the drop in gasoline prices to the end of a
10-day-old refinery strike in Brazil.
   The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries opened formal
talks in Vienna, Austria, aimed at setting new production quotas for
its 13 members. The talks were adjourned after 90 minutes to allow
private negotiations to continue among key members who are trying to
work out a nagging dispute between Iran and Iraq.
   One of the main obstacles to a new agreement has been Iraq's
insistence on a production ceiling equal to Iran's. Traders said
they expected the market to move cautiously until that dispute is
somehow resolved or other measures are approved by the cartel to
rein in production.
   OPEC President Rilwanu Lukman opened the winter meeting of the
cartel by appealing for compromise. He said members must reach a new
accord limiting their oil production or risk a ``serious erosion''
of crude prices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881121-0303 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-88 1643EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-OPEC 1stLd-Writethru   11-21 0918</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-OPEC, 1st Ld-Writethru,0949</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>OPEC Ministers Warned About Falling Oil Prices</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 new graf after 5th graf pvs He said ... to ADD
settlement price on New York Merc. Picks up 6th graf pvs Lukman said
...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC ministers quickly adjourned their
formal talks Monday and resumed private negotiations aimed at
resolving a dispute between Iran and Iraq that is holding up a new
production agreement.
   The ministers met for about 90 minutes before putting off their
formal talks until Wednesday.
   President Rilwanu Lukman opened the winter meeting of the
13-nation Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries by appealing
for compromise. He said cartel members must reach a new accord
limiting their oil production or risk a ``serious erosion'' of crude
prices.
   ``It may be necessary to take one step back now from our
deep-seated principles and beliefs in order to take two steps
forward at a later date,'' he said.
   He said the cartel's problems ``are formidable and yet they are
not insuperable.''
   Crude oil prices edged higher on the New York Mercantile Exchange
in light trading as the market awaited definitive news on the
progress of the talks. Contracts for January delivery of West Texas
Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude, rose 7 cents from Friday's
close to settle at $12.98 cents per 42-gallon barrel.
   Lukman said they had not yet discussed the crucial questions of
oil production, output quotas for member countries and pricing.
   A few hours after the meeting, the ministers resumed some of the
private discussions they have been holding since late last week to
try to resolve the issues separating Iran and Iraq.
   The main obstacle has been Iraq's insistence on a production
ceiling equal to Iran.
   Iranian Oil Minister Gholamreza Aghazadeh met with his Algerian
counterpart, Sadek Boussena, who appears to have become an emissary
between Iran and Persian Gulf countries.
   After the meeting, Aghazadeh told reporters it was still too
early to tell whether an agreement would be reached or not.
Consultations, he said, will continue Tuesday.
   ``If we should (see) some proposal that is good, we accept,'' he
said.
   The ministers want to work out a new arrangement giving each
country a production quota. They want to include Iraq in the system.
Iraq refused to join in the current accord arranged in 1986.
   ``I would be happier if I was inside the agreement,'' said Iraqi
Oil Minister Issam Abdul Raheem al-Chalabi.
   Aghazadeh again said he would oppose quota parity with Iraq. The
two countries have had different ceilings for some time, he said.
   Saudia Arabia and Kuwait have said they will not join a new quota
system unless all 13 members belong.
   The ministers want to use the new accord to cap their runaway
production and lift weak prices. OPEC maintains a benchmark price of
$18 a barrel but prices have been well under that.
   Lukman told the ministers, ``As we are all aware, prices have
been hovering $5 to $6 per barrel below our targeted levels for
several months now.''
   ``If we do not reach such an accord,'' he said, ``then I am
afraid we may see a further serious erosion of these price levels,
to our mutual detriment.''
   Aghazadeh said he has offered to meet with Iraq, Saudi Arabia,
Kuwait and the United Arab Emirates to work out the quota dispute.
   ``We can sit down to solve (the) problem (and have a) discussion
about any matter,'' he said. ``I am very flexible.''
   He also said Iran wants OPEC to give it a higher ceiling in any
new agreement. Iran needs more revenues from its oil to help rebuild
after the 8-year war with Iraq.
   He said Iran will be able within a year to boost its production
of oil to more than 4 million barrels a day. The country, he said,
is currently pumping more than 3 million barrels a day and will
boost that to about 3.3 million in a few months.
   Under the current production agreement, Iran has a ceiling of 2.4
million barrels a day. Iraq, although it refused to join the current
accord, has an allotment of 1.5 million barrels a day.
   Analysts estimate that Iraq has been producing at least 2.6
million barrels a day, an amount that could soar to 3.7 million
barrels in mid-1989 with completion of a new pipeline through Saudi
Arabia to the Red Sea.
   OPEC's current output accord sets total production at about 15
million barrels a day for 12 countries.
   Total cartel production in October was estimated by the
International Energy Agency at nearly 21.1 million barrels, the
highest monthly level in more than five years.
   Aghazadeh has proposed that Iraq be given ``export parity'' with
Iran. That would allow Iran to have a higher overall ceiling to
account for its larger internal oil demand, which it estimates at 1
million barrels a day.
   A possibility for resolving the dispute, analysts suggested,
would be to give Iraq a lower quota on paper. But the difference in
the ceilings would be made up by letting Iraq keep a portion of the
oil produced in an area called the neutral zone, which is shared by
Saudi Arabia and Kuwait.
   The discussions began Thursday evening when the two OPEC
committees _ price evolution and long-term strategy _ held formal
talks.
   Countries belonging to those panels are Indonesia, Saudi Arabia,
Iran, Iraq, Nigeria, Indonesia, Kuwait and Venezuela.
   Other members are Ecuador, Gabon, Libya, Qatar and the United
Arab Emirates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
