<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Manufacturing     11-21 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Manufacturing,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Says Regions Dependent On Manufacturing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Manufacturing jobs are growing faster in
traditional service-sector areas and declining throughout the
once-booming rust-belt states, according to a new report Monday by
the Conference Board.
   California, North Carolina and Florida are among the
beneficiaries of a new geographical realignment of manufacturing,
the report by the business-financed research organization said.
   Meanwhile, manufacturing job growth is continuing to decline in
states like Ohio, Michigan and Pennsylvania, once the guts of the
U.S. industrial heartland.
   ``Employment gains in the manufacturing sector this year will
spread more widely than ever across the United States,'' says Steven
R. Malin, a specialist in economic trends. ``Before the next
national recession, Southeastern and Western states will have added
substantially more manufacturing jobs than states in the North and
East.''
   Seven major states have added more than 738,000 manufacturing
jobs since 1982, the report said. California was in the lead with
228,900, followed by Michigan with 114,500. In the last two years,
however, Michigan has lost 66,000 manufacturing jobs, the board said.
   Also gaining manufacturing jobs since 1982 were North Carolina
91,400; Florida 90,600; Indiana 78,600; Georgia 78,300; and
Minnesota 55,400.
   Among the losers were West Virginia with 7,300 jobs lost since
1982; Connecticut 29,500; Massachusetts 34,700; New Jersey 43,300;
Pennsylvania 52,000; Ohio 63,700; and New York 88,900.
   The Conference Board said the key to manufacturing success next
year will be construction, defense spending and exports.
</TEXT>
