<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     11-21 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls On Bush Remarks About Deficit; Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar weakened Monday against major foreign
currencies in the absence of central-bank buying.
   Gold prices also declined. Republic National Bank quoted bullion
at $415.50 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, down $1.25 from late
Friday.
   The dollar had strengthened in Tokyo but turned lower in Europe
after remarks from President-elect Bush reaffirming that he won't
raise taxes to narrow the huge federal budget deficit.
   ``It's been a slow decline all day,'' said Ronald H. Holzer,
chief currency dealer for Harris Trust & Co. in Chicago.
   Renewed worries about the U.S. trade and federal budget deficits
have pushed the dollar sharply lower in recent weeks, prompting
central banks around the world to buy dollars on Thursday and Friday
to prop up the currency's value.
   But Holzer and other dealers reported a lack of central-bank
intervention Monday.
   ``The absence of internvention today allowed the dollar to ...
fall; that, and the remarks from Bush,'' Holzer said.
   At issue is whether Bush and the Democratic-controlled U.S.
Congress can agree on spending cuts needed to trim the budget
deficit. If left unchecked, dealers fear, it ultimately will hurt
the U.S. economy.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar closed at 122.52 Japanese yen, up from 122.40 yen late
Friday. But in late London trading the dollar fell lower to 122.20
yen, and in New York it fell to 122.025 yen, down from 122.60 late
Friday.
   The British pound cost $1.8175 in London, more expensive for
buyers than Friday's late $1.8160. Later, in New York, sterling
fetched $1.8235, down from $1.8155 late Friday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Friday,
included: 1.72815 West German marks, down from 1.7370; 1.45495 Swiss
francs, down from 1.4600; 1.20695 Canadian dollars, down from
1.2300; 5.9070 French francs, down from 5.9365; and 1,284.575
Italian lire, down from 1,292.00.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Friday, included
: 1.7305 West German marks, down from 1.7360; 1.4575 Swiss francs,
down from 1.4585; 5.9305 French francs, down from 5.9340; 1.9550
Dutch guilders, down from 1.9610; 1,288.62 Italian lire, down from
1,293.75; and 1.2117 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2343.
   The Canadian dollar gained more than two cents in European and
domesitc trading against the dollar on the heels of Saturday's
opinion polls predicting victory in Monday's Canadian general
election for Prime Minister Brian Mulroney's Conservatives.
   On the New York Commodity Exchange, gold for current delivery
fell to $415.80 a troy ounce from $417.40 late Friday.
   Gold bullion closed in London at $416.75 an ounce, down from
$417.75 bid late Friday. The late price in Zurich, Switzerland, was
$416.50 an ounce, down from $417.80.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold closed at $418.79 an ounce, down from
$419.12.
   Silver prices also declined. On the New York Comex, silver fell
to $6.010 a troy ounce from $6.08 Friday. Bullion traded late in
London at a bid $6.04 a an ounce, down from $6.09.
</TEXT>
