<1ST_LINE>u f AM-BlinderProbe     11-21 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Blinder Probe,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Probe of Blinder-Robinson Continues</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal probe of a penny-stock brokerage firm's
records continued Monday as government spokesmen declined comment on
what the investigation was seeking.
   ``I'm afraid no one can make any comment,'' said assistant U.S.
Attorney Howard Zlotnick in Las Vegas, Nev., where the current probe
of Denver-based Blinder, Robinson & Co. originated.
   However, Steven B. Theyes, Blinder, Robinson's senior vice
president, on Monday said the search warrant was directed at records
of 53 investors ``none of whom are present or former officers,
directors, stockbrokers, or agents of Blinder, Robinson'' and 16
publicly traded issues ``none of which were underwritten by Blinder,
Robinson.''
   ``It's their privilege to claim anything they want,'' was
Zlotnik's reply.
   Earlier, Blinder, Robinson lawyers said documents which agents
for the Internal Revenue Service and U.S. Treasury were looking for
had been given to the Securities and Exchange Commission months ago.
   ``We are conducting business,'' Theyes said Monday. He noted,
however, that business is being conducted at about 40 percent of
normal strength, in view of an agreement reached before a U.S.
District Court judge in Denver between the company and agents
continuing their probe within the firm's offices.
   Theyes said he had about 60 staffers working Monday compared with
a normal force of about 150.
   Theyes said he hoped the search of files would wind up Monday
night. He said 24 Treasury agents launched the probe with a federal
search warrant Saturday morning and that by midday Monday, the
agents had confined their efforts to records in storage rooms.
   The brokerage firm has 66 offices in 37 states nationwide and
posted 1987 revenue of about $130 million. It specializes in penny
stocks, which are cheap, high-risk securities not usually traded on
major stock exchanges.
   Blinder, Robinson has been the subject of earlier federal
investigations involving allegations of fraud, markups and
misrepresentation.
   Last year, the Securities and Exchange Commission launched a
probe of Blinder, Robinson, alleging that customers had been
defrauded.
   The SEC also had two other actions pending against the company,
which was the nation's largest penny-stock broker. Those allegations
accused the company of bookkeeping violations.
   The National Association of Securities Dealers levied penalties
of $250,000 against the company in 1987 for charging excessive
markups in the price of shares for one of its issues.
   The company was suspended from doing business for five days and
six executives were suspended from the brokerage business for 90
days.
</TEXT>
