<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-88 1947EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Drexel-Judge     11-21 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drexel-Judge,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drexel Asks for Rehearing on Judge Disqualification</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. requested a new
hearing Monday in its attempt to oust the judge presiding over the
federal civil-fraud case facing the Wall Street investment firm.
   In a 15-page petition to the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals,
attorneys for Drexel and other defendants asked a three-judge panel
that had rejected their earlier request to rehear the matter, refer
it to the entire 12-judge appellate bench or allow a separate
hearing before another lower court judge.
   Last week, the three-judge panel ruled 2-1 that Drexel's effort
to disqualify U.S. District Judge Milton Pollack from the case on
grounds of conflict of interest was unwarranted.
   The defendants had argued that Pollack's wife, Moselle, stands to
gain at least $30 million from the sale of her stock in Palais Royal
Inc., a Houston-based retailer going private in a transaction Drexel
is helping finance.
   Drexel's lawyers said the indirect relationship between Drexel
and Pollack's family created the appearance of bias and required
Pollack to disqualify himself.
   Pollack, an 82-year-old jurist known for tough rulings in
white-collar fraud cases, has denounced Drexel's maneuvering to oust
him as a nonsensical ploy. He has said his wife's business affairs
have nothing to do with Drexel.
   Some lawyers familiar with the Drexel case have said they
believed the defense maneuvering is part of a broader strategy to
get a more lenient judge.
   It was unclear how the 2nd Circuit would respond to Drexel's
request for a rehearing on Pollack. Such requests are seldom granted.
   Drexel is facing numerous civil charges leveled by the Securities
and Exchange Commission in September that the firm conspired with
now-imprisoned speculator Ivan Boesky to trade on inside
information, manipulate stock and commit other frauds. The firm has
denied the accusations.
   In addition, a federal grand jury has been considering whether to
indict Drexel and some key employees on criminal charges. There has
been persistent speculation that the charges could be announced soon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
