<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Pepperell-Farley     11-21 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pepperell-Farley,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Rules Against West Point in Farley Takeover</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal court on Monday rejected two efforts by
West Point-Pepperell Inc. to stave off a buyout by Farley Inc. of
Chicago.
   Textile maker Pepperell had asked the 11th US Circuit Court of
Appeals to stay a U.S. District Court ruling allowing the takeover
bid and to grant an injunction postponing the bid while the lower
court ruling was appealed.
   A three-judge panel denied both motions but granted a Pepperell
motion for an expedited appeal.
   Pepperell had argued that an injunction would be only temporary
and could not harm Farley but that denial of one could cause serious
harm to Pepperell.
   Farley announced in May that it would try to buy Pepperell.
Farley owns about 9.8 percent of the company's stock. It has offered
around $1.57 billion, or $48 a share, for outstanding shares and
associated rights of Pepperell stock in an offer originally
scheduled to expire at midnight Monday.
   ``We are pleased by the court's decision to deny (Pepperell's)
application for a stay and also by its decision to expedite the
hearing,'' said William Farley, chief executive officer.
   Farley also said he's extending the offer to Wednesday, Nov. 30,
to expire at midnight New York time.
   Farley has secured financing but says three conditions must be
met before it will complete the tender offer.
   One is that Pepperell remove the hurdle caused by its ``poison
pill'' shareholders' rights plan, which allows shareholders not
involved in a takeover attempt to buy additional Pepperell shares in
case of a buyout attempt. This makes a buyout more expensive.
   U.S. District Judge Ernest Tidwell invalidated two key aspects of
the ``pill'' last week. The rest remains in place, where Pepperell
officials say they intend to keep it.
   Farley also wants Georgia's anti-takeover statute ruled
unconstitutional and insists that at least two-thirds of Pepperell's
shareholders tender their shares.
   Tidwell has taken the anti-takeover statute under advisement but
has not said when he might rule.
   ``Financing is the only thing Farley has in the bag,'' said Josie
Esquivel, an analyst for Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
``Even if shareholders tender 70 percent of their stock, Farley
still has to meet the other two conditions.''
   Farley manufactures Fruit of the Loom underwear. Pepperell
products include Gold Toe socks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
