<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-88 1856EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Earns-LTV     11-21 0476</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-LTV,0493</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>LTV Posts $1.24 Billion Loss in Third Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   LTV Corp. reported on Monday a third-quarter net
loss of $1.24 billion, which company officials attributed largely to
Chapter 11-related special charges.
   A change in accounting principles for post-employment medical and
life insurance benefits also had a negative impact on results,
officials of the diversified company said.
   The loss compares with a net profit of $109.7 million, or 91
cents a share, in the third quarter of 1987.
   LTV officials said the special charges and the accounting change
are important elements in moving the company toward its Chapter 11
reorganization.
   ``Because LTV is in Chapter 11, we believe it is appropriate for
the company to record all its liabilities, including the liability
for these post-employment benefits, so that they may be
appropriately dealt with in the reorganization process,'' said
Raymond Hay, LTV's chairman and chief executive officer.
   Angela Tese, a bankruptcy specialist for Cole & Deitz in New
York, said Monday's announcement of a negative net worth was not a
good signal for the company.
   ``They'll have to prove to the (bankruptcy) court that the plan
is feasible,'' Tese said. ``They are going to have to be able to
demonstrate to the court that they are healthy enough and that they
won't have to reorganize again sometime soon.''
   The third-quarter special charges total $1.34 billion, ost of
which is non-cash. They include:
   _$950 million for Chapter 11 creditors' claims;
   _$350 million for a reduction of assets and other anticipated
costs in the divesture of LTV Steel Co.'s bar business, as well as
additional costs incurred in the rationalization of other steel
facilities;
   _$41 million for the write-off of goodwill recorded in connection
with the company's 1983 acquisition of Sierra Research Corp.
   Without the two elements, LTV said its net income would have been
$132.2 million for the third quarter and $453.7 million for the
first nine months of the year. That would have compared with $109.7
million and $362.0 million for the respective periods in 1987.
   The change in accounting principle alters the method of
accounting for post-employment medical and life insurance benefits
and resulted in a one-time, non-cash charge of $2.26 billion,
recorded as of last Jan. 1.
   ``The accounting method adopted by LTV recognizes the
post-employment medical and life insurance benefits earned by all of
the company's retirees and active employees,'' Hay said.
``Previously these costs were recognized only as they were paid.''
   The change in accounting principle reduced operating income by
$32.1 million for the third quarter and $98.2 million for the
nine-month period.
   For the first nine months, LTV reported a net loss of $3.25
billion, which company officials also attributed to the special
charges and accounting change. That compared with a net profit of
$362.0 million, or $3.07 a share, in the same nine-month period of
1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
