<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Britain-BP     11-21 0207</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-BP,0214</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BP Accepts Bids for 15 Percent of Magnus Oil Field</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Petroleum PLC said on Monday that it had
accepted bids totalling $267 million for 15 percent of its Magnus
oil field in the British sector of the North Sea.
   The company said it was selling a 5 percent stake to Sun Oil
Britain Ltd., 5 percent to Repsol Exploration Ltd. and 2.5 percent
each to Goal Petroleum PLC and Braspetro Oil Services Co.
   Details of individual tenders were not disclosed, but the sale
valued each 1 percent of Magnus at an average of $17.8 million.
   BP Exploration Managing Director Hugh Norton said the company was
pleased with the transaction ``against a background of uncertain oil
prices.''
   To BP, the proceeds of the sale represented a return equivalent
to a crude oil price of $22 per 42-gallon barrel in 1989, rising in
real terms to $25 in 1995, Norton said. The company believes it
``sensible to realize this extra value now to invest in other
oppportunities for the benefit of our shareholders,'' he added.
   Completion of the sale is subject to the necessary regulatory
approvals, including that of the British energy secretary in the
transfer of license interests to the purchasers.
</TEXT>
