<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-88 2002EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-FTC-Hoechst     11-21 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FTC-Hoechst,0261</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FTC Charges Merger Could Lessen Competition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Trade Commission charged Monday
that the 1987 merger of Celanese Corp. into American Hoechst Corp.
could lessen competition in the manufacture and sale of a widely
used plastic.
   The commission's administrative complaint said the creation of
the new Hoechst Celanese Corp. ``could substantially lessen
international competition in the manufacture and sale of acetal,'' a
plastic used in items such as car parts and disposable lighters.
   In 1987, before the two companies merged, the FTC had contended
the merger could reduce competition in the production of polyester
textile fiber in the United States. A consent agreement was worked
out which allowed the merger to go ahead.
   FTC spokeswoman Susan Ticknor said the new complaint would be
considered by an administrative law judge, and hearing dates were
expected to be set on Jan. 3.
   Hoechst Celanese, which is based in Somerville, N.J., issued a
statement saying it was confident it will prevail in the matter.
   ``We are astounded that the FTC has decided to pursue it,'' said
James Conway, vice president and general manager of the Engineering
Plastics Division. ``The matter will have no impact on our
day-to-day activities.''
   Before the merger, Hoechst AG, the company's West German parent,
and Celanese Corp. manufactured acetal in West Germany through a
joint venture, Ticona Polymerwerke GmbH. The FTC is contending the
merger eliminated competition between Celanese and Ticona in the
world acetal market, affecting prices in the United States, Hoechst
Celanese stated.
</TEXT>
