<DOCNO> AP881121-0317 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-88 1929EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-BankingLaw     11-21 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Banking Law,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Jersey Interstate S&L Law Declared in Force</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Jersey banking officials announced
Monday that the state's new interstate savings and loan law had
taken effect, allowing savings institutions from 13 other states to
make acquisitions in New Jersey.
   The law took effect Nov. 15, but until the announcement it had
been unclear when the measure, signed into law last year, actually
would take force, said Kyra Lindemann, a spokeswoman for the state
Department of Banking.
   ``Today we have given our savings and loan associations the same
tools and flexibility so that they may continue to be progressive
and effective players in the ever-expanding ... marketplace,'' she
said in a statement.
   The law allows federally or state-chartered institutions with
proper insurance to engage in interstate acquisitions with similar
thrifts on a reciprocal basis. That means New Jersey institutions
also may make acquisitions in those other states.
   State Banking Commissioner Mary Parell determined that 13 states
meet New Jersey's reciprocity test, Ms. Lindemann said. The states
are: Arizona, Idaho, Kentucky, Maine, Michigan, New York, Ohio,
Oklahoma, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Utah, West Virginia and Wyoming.
</TEXT>
